<H2>LEGEND.1 Safety</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Safety notices are printed throughout this manual. =
<B>DANGER</B>=20
notices warn you of conditions or procedures that can result in death or =
severe=20
personal injury. <B>CAUTION</B> notices warn you of conditions or =
procedures=20
that can cause personal injury that is neither lethal nor extremely =
hazardous.=20
<B>Attention:</B> notices warn you of conditions and procedures that can =
cause=20
damage to machines, equipment, or programs. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.1.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>LEGEND.1.1 United Kingdom</A> </LI></UL>
<HR>

<H3>LEGEND.1.1 United Kingdom</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><A name=3DWRN><EM>Warning:</EM> <EM>This</EM> <EM>IBM</EM>=20
<EM>product</EM> <EM>is</EM> <EM>made</EM> <EM>to</EM> <EM>high</EM>=20
<EM>Safety</EM> <EM>standards.</EM> <EM>It</EM> <EM>complies</EM></A>=20
<EM>inherently</EM> <EM>with</EM> <EM>Telecommunication</EM> =
<EM>safety</EM>=20
<EM>standards.</EM> <EM>It</EM> <EM>is</EM> <EM>not</EM> =
<EM>designed</EM>=20
<EM>to</EM> <EM>provide</EM> <EM>protection</EM> <EM>from</EM>=20
<EM>excessive</EM> <EM>voltages</EM> <EM>appearing</EM> =
<EM>externally</EM>=20
<EM>at</EM> <EM>its</EM> <EM>interfaces.</EM> <EM>Therefore,</EM> =
<EM>when</EM>=20
<EM>this</EM> <EM>product</EM> <EM>is</EM> <EM>connected</EM> =
<EM>to</EM>=20
<EM>a</EM> <EM>public</EM> <EM>telecommunication</EM> <EM>network</EM>=20
<EM>via</EM> <EM>any</EM> <EM>other</EM> <EM>equipment,</EM> =
<EM>and</EM>=20
<EM>you</EM> <EM>connect</EM> <EM>to</EM> <EM>this</EM> <EM>product</EM> =

<EM>items</EM> <EM>not</EM> <EM>supplied</EM> <EM>by</EM> <EM>IBM</EM>=20
<EM>United</EM> <EM>Kingdom</EM> <EM>Ltd.,</EM> <EM>you</EM> =
<EM>must</EM>=20
<EM>comply</EM> <EM>with</EM> <EM>mandatory</EM> =
<EM>telecommunication</EM>=20
<EM>safety</EM> <EM>requirements.</EM> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>You may do this either by choosing products which also are =
approved as=20
complying to BS6301 or British Telecom Technical Guide No. 26, or by the =
use of=20
approved safety barriers. Consult the local office of your public=20
telecommunication operator, for advice and permission to make the =
connections.=20
<HR>

<H2>LEGEND.2 Electronic Emission Notices</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The following warning statements (required by country =
regulatory=20
agencies) are applicable in the countries indicated. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
   <B>Federal</B> <B>Communications</B> <B>Commission</B> <B>(FCC)</B> =
<B>Statement</B>
<P>
   <B>Note:</B>  This equipment has been tested and found to comply with =
the limits
   for a Class A digital device, pursuant to Part 15 of the FCC Rules.  =
These
   limits are designed to provide reasonable protection against harmful
   interference when the equipment is operated in a commercial =
environment.
   This equipment generates, uses, and can radiate radio frequency =
energy
   and, if not installed and used in accordance with the instruction =
manual,
   may cause harmful interference to radio communications.  Operation of =
this
   equipment in a residential area is likely to cause harmful =
interference,
   in which case the user will be required to correct the interference =
at his
   own expense.
<P>
   Properly shielded and grounded cables and connectors must be used in =
order
   to meet FCC emission limits.  IBM is not responsible for any radio or
   television interference caused by using other than recommended cables =
and
   connectors or by unauthorized changes or modifications to this =
equipment.
   Unauthorized changes or modifications could void the user's authority =
to
   operate the equipment.
<P>
   This device complies with Part 15 of the FCC Rules.  Operation is =
subject
   to the following two conditions:  (1) this device may not cause =
harmful
   interference, and (2) this device must accept any interference =
received,
   including interference that may cause undesired operation.
<P>
</P></PRE>

Canada</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

R=E8glement sur le mat=E9riel brouilleur du Canada.=20
<HR>

<H3>LEGEND.2.3 Japanese Voluntary Control Council for Interference =
(VCCI)=20
Statement</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This equipment is Class 1 Equipment (information equipment to =
be used=20
in commercial and industrial districts) which is in conformance with the =

standard set by Voluntary Control for Interference by Data Processing =
Equipment=20
and Electronic Office Machines (VCCI) with an aim to prevent radio =
interference=20
in commercial and industrial districts. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>This equipment could cause interference to radio and television =
receivers=20
when used in and around residential districts. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Please handle the equipment properly according to the instruction =
manual.=20
<HR>

<H2>LEGEND.3 System Security Advice</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This product is intended for use within a single establishment =
and=20
within a single homogeneous user population. For sensitive applications=20
requiring isolation from each other, management may wish to provide =
isolated=20
cabling or to encrypt the sensitive data before putting it on the =
network.=20

<A name=3DHDRSAFEINS>
<H2>LEGEND.6 CE Safety Inspection Procedures</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>If a safety inspection is required, start the procedure with =
the IBM=20
5494 Remote Control Unit (the 5494) power turned <B>OFF</B> and the =
electrical=20
power cord removed from the power outlet. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>See the following documentation for information about safety =
inspections: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>All service memorandums, engineering change announcements (ECAs), =
and=20
  service aids (SAs) for this 5494 <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <LI><CITE>Electrical</CITE> <CITE>Safety</CITE> <CITE>for</CITE>=20
  <CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>Customer</CITE> <CITE>Engineers</CITE>, =
S229-8124 <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><CITE>General</CITE> <CITE>Safety</CITE> <CITE>Course</CITE>, =
80114. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL></OL></LI></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.6.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>LEGEND.6.1 How to Conduct This Safety Inspection</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.6.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>LEGEND.6.2 External Inspection</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.6.3?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>LEGEND.6.3 Internal Inspection</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.6.4?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>LEGEND.6.4 Safety Label</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.6.5?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>LEGEND.6.5 Grounding Circuits</A> </LI></UL>
<UL></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRCONDUCT>
<H4>LEGEND.6.1 How to Conduct This Safety =
Inspection</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This inspection guide helps identify unsafe conditions on =
5494s that=20
you are inspecting. At the time of manufacture, each 5494 has all the =
necessary=20
safety items installed to protect the owners, operators, and service =
personnel=20
from injury. This inspection addresses only these items. You should use =
good=20
judgment to identify possible safety hazards not covered by this =
inspection=20
guide. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If unsafe conditions are present, contact your field manager for =
the=20
suitable action to be taken before you service the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Also, consider the following safety hazards that can be present: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Electrical hazards, especially primary power. For example, a frame =
without=20
  a good ground can cause serious or lethal electrical shock. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Exploding hazards. For example, a damaged cathode ray tube (CRT) =
face or=20
  distorted capacitors can explode and cause serious injury. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Chemical hazards. For example, the use of solvents not specified =
by IBM=20
  may result in electrical, mechanical, or toxic hazards. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>This guide contains a safety inspection =
procedure for the following: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>External inspection=20
  <LI>Internal inspection. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.6.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRLABELS">"Safety=20
Label" in topic LEGEND.6.4</A> shows the location of the safety label on =
the=20
5494. Refer to this figure as you do the safety inspection.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDREXTINSP>
<H4>LEGEND.6.2 External Inspection</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Do the following checks: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Is the external cover present, installed correctly, and in good =
condition?=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Is the 5494 power cord in good condition? Is the power cord part =
number=20
  correct for this unit? Refer to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/8.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRPARTCAT">Topic=20
  8, "Parts Catalog."</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Does the 5494 have the correct approved power plug for your =
country? (See=20
  <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/8.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRPARTCAT">Topic=20
  8, "Parts Catalog" </A>for the correct plug type.) <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Is the power connector at the back of the 5494 damaged? =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Is the ac ground connection good from one end of the power cord to =
the=20
  other? The resistance of this conductor should be less than 0.1 ohm. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Is the customer's line voltage the correct voltage for the power =
supply in=20
  the 5494? </LI></OL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRINTINSP>
<H4>LEGEND.6.3 Internal Inspection</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Do the following checks: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Is the power supply cover present and securely fastened? =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Are there any obvious non-IBM engineering changes? If the answer =
to this=20
  question is yes, complete <CITE>Non-IBM</CITE> <CITE>Alteration</CITE> =

  <CITE>Attachment</CITE> <CITE>Survey</CITE>, G150-0197. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Are there any loose screws, contaminating chemicals, signs of =
water or=20
  moisture, signs of fire or smoke damage, metal particles or dust, or =
any other=20
  internal conditions that look hazardous? <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Are any cables visibly worn, pinched, or damaged in any way? Check =
the=20
  primary power area for broken wires. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Does the 5494 chassis have a good ground? The grounding circuits =
are shown=20
  in <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.6.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRGROUND">"Grounding=20
  Circuits" in topic LEGEND.6.5</A>. Measure the resistance from the =
ground pin=20
  on the ac power plug to any portion of the metal chassis that does not =
carry=20
  electrical current. Resistance must be less than 0.1 ohm. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Are any of the capacitors in the power area leaking or distorted? =
</LI></OL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRLABELS>
<H3>LEGEND.6.4 Safety Label</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Check the safety label as shown in the following figure: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Is there a hazardous voltage label attached to the power supply?=20
  <LI>Are all parts installed in place securely? <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGFIGUNIQ4>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-7?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 7" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P7.gif"></A>         </A>
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<HR>

width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Make sure that the grounding circuits shown in the following =
figure=20
are present and secure. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGFIGUNIQ5>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=

CE</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Caso uma inspe=E7=E3o de seguran=E7a seja necess=E1ria, =
inicie-a com a for=E7a=20
da Unidade de Controle Remoto 5494 da IBM (5494) <B>DESLIGADA</B> e o =
cabo de=20
for=E7a desconectado da tomada el=E9trica. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Para maiores informa=E7=F5es sobre inspe=E7=F5es de seguran=E7a, =
consulte as=20
publica=E7=F5es relacionadas abaixo: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Todas as notas de funcionamento, an=FAncios sobre altera=E7=F5es =
de engenharia=20
  (ECAs) e aux=EDlios de servi=E7os (SAs) para este 5494 <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><CITE>Electrical</CITE> <CITE>Safety</CITE> <CITE>for</CITE>=20
  <CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>Customer</CITE> <CITE>Engineers</CITE>, =
S229-8124 <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><CITE>General</CITE> <CITE>Safety</CITE> <CITE>Course</CITE>, =
80114. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL></OL></LI></UL>

  =

02/LEGEND.7.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>LEGEND.7.1 Como Realizar a Inspe=E7=E3o de =
Seguran=E7a</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =

<A name=3DHDRCNDUCT>
<H4>LEGEND.7.1 Como Realizar a Inspe=E7=E3o de =
Seguran=E7a</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Este guia de inspe=E7=E3o ajuda a identificar condi=E7=F5es =
perigosas no 5494s=20
que est=E1 sendo inspecionado. Na fabrica=E7=E3o, todos os itens de =
seguran=E7a=20
necess=E1rios s=E3o instalados no 5494 para proteger os propriet=E1rios, =
operadores e=20
equipe de manuten=E7=E3o de ferimentos. A inspe=E7=E3o visa apenas esses =
itens. Voc=EA=20
deve usar sua capacidade de discernimento para identificar poss=EDveis =
condi=E7=F5es=20
perigosas de seguran=E7a que n=E3o estejam mencionados neste guia de =
inspe=E7=E3o. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Caso existam condi=E7=F5es perigosas, entre em contato com o =
gerente de =E1rea=20
para conhecer a a=E7=E3o a ser tomada antes de trabalhar no 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Tamb=E9m analise as condi=E7=F5es perigosas abaixo: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Perigos el=E9tricos, especialmente a for=E7a prim=E1ria. Por =
exemplo, uma=20
  estrutura sem a aterragem correta pode causar um choque el=E9trico =
grave ou=20
  letal. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Perigos de explos=F5es. Por exemplo, a superf=EDcie danificada de =
um tubo de=20
  raios cat=F3dicos (CRT) ou capacitores danificados podem explodir e =
causar=20
  ferimentos s=E9rios. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Perigos qu=EDmicos. Por exemplo, a utiliza=E7=E3o de solventes =
n=E3o especificados=20
  pela IBM pode produzir perigos t=F3xicos, mec=E2nicos ou el=E9tricos. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>Este guia cont=E9m os procedimentos de =
inspe=E7=E3o de seguran=E7a para: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Inspe=E7=E3o externa=20
  <LI>Inspe=E7=E3o interna. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>A se=E7=E3o <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.7.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRLBLS1">"R=F3tulo=20
de Seguran=E7a" in topic LEGEND.7.4</A> apresenta a localiza=E7=E3o do =
r=F3tulo de=20
seguran=E7a no 5494. Consulte a figura, conforme realiza a inspe=E7=E3o =
de seguran=E7a.=20

<A name=3DHDRETINSP>

  LEGEND.7.5</A>. Me=E7a a resist=EAncia do pino de aterramento na =

<A name=3DHDRCNDUCT2>
<H4>LEGEND.8.1 Comment proc=E9der =E0 une inspection de =
s=E9curit=E9</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Ce guide d'inspection vous aidera =E0 identifier tout risque =
potentiel=20
pour la s=E9curit=E9 sur les 5494s que vous inspectez. Au moment de sa =
fabrication,=20
chaque 5494 est =E9quip=E9 de dispositifs de s=E9curit=E9 destin=E9s =E0 =
garantir la=20
s=E9curit=E9 des utilisateurs, des op=E9rateurs et du personnel de =
maintenance. Ce=20
guide ne concerne que ces dispositifs. D'autres risques ne sont =
peut-=EAtre pas=20
abord=E9s ici. Il vous appartient d'en =E9valuer l'importance. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Si les conditions de s=E9curit=E9 ne sont pas r=E9unies, contactez =
le=20
responsable de secteur pour conna=EEtre la marche =E0 suivre avant de =
r=E9parer un=20
5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Voici des exemples de situations dangereuses comportant des =
risques pour=20
votre s=E9curit=E9 : <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Risques =E9lectriques, en particulier concernant le bloc =
d'alimentation=20
  primaire. Par exemple, un ch=E2ssis qui n'est pas mis =E0 la terre =
peut causer un=20
  choc =E9lectrique grave, voire mortel. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Risques d'explosion. Par exemple, un tube =E0 rayon cathodique =
endommag=E9 ou=20
  des condensateurs d=E9form=E9s peuvent exploser et causer de graves =
accidents. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Risques chimiques. Par exemple, l'usage de solvants non indiqu=E9s =
par IBM=20
  peut entra=EEner des accidents =E9lectriques, m=E9caniques, ou =
toxiques. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>Ce guide explique les proc=E9dures =E0 =
suivre pour les inspections de=20
=E9curit=E9 suivantes : <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Inspection externe.=20
  <LI>Inspection interne. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>La figure <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.8.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRLBLS">"Etiquette=20
de s=E9curit=E9" in topic LEGEND.8.4</A> montre l'emplacement de =
l'=E9tiquette de=20
s=E9curit=E9 sur le 5494. Reportez-vous =E0 cette figure pour proc=E9der =
=E0 l'inspection.=20

<HR>
<A name=3DHDRETINSP2>
<H4>LEGEND.8.2 Inspection externe</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>V=E9rifiez les points suivants : <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Le carter de protection est bien install=E9 et en bon =E9tat. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Le cordon d'alimentation du 5494 est en bon =E9tat et adapt=E9 =E0 =
cette unit=E9.=20
  (Voir <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/8.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRPARTCAT">Topic=20
  8, "Parts Catalog"</A> pour obtenir la r=E9f=E9rence.) <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Le 5494 est =E9quip=E9 de la fiche de prise de courant conforme =
aux normes en=20
  vigueur dans votre pays. (Voir <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/8.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRPARTCAT">Topic=20
  8, "Parts Catalog" </A>pour conna=EEtre le type de fiche appropri=E9.) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Le connecteur d'alimentation =E0 l'arri=E8re du 5494 n'est pas =
endommag=E9. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>La mise =E0 la terre c.a. fonctionne d'un bout =E0 l'autre du =
cordon=20
  d'alimentation. V=E9rifiez que le conducteur de mise =E0 la terre a =
une r=E9sistance=20
  inf=E9rieure =E0 0,1 ohm. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>La tension secteur de l'utilisateur est adapt=E9e au bloc =
d'alimentation du=20
  5494. </LI></OL>

<A name=3DHDRINTISP2>
<H4>LEGEND.8.3 Inspection interne</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Suivez les proc=E9dures suivantes : <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Assurez-vous que le carter du bloc d'alimentation est en place et=20
  solidement fix=E9. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>V=E9rifiez s'il y a des modifications techniques non IBM. Le cas =
=E9ch=E9ant,=20
  remplissez le formulaire <CITE>Non-IBM</CITE> <CITE>Alteration</CITE>=20
  <CITE>Attachment</CITE> <CITE>Survey</CITE>, G150-0197. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Portez une attention particuli=E8re =E0 l'int=E9rieur de =
l'appareil : vis=20
  desserr=E9es, produits chimiques polluants, signes d'humidit=E9 ou de =
liquide,=20
  traces de fum=E9e ou de feu, limaille ou poussi=E8re sont =E0 =
proscrire. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Les c=E2bles ne doivent =EAtre ni effiloch=E9s, ni endommag=E9s, =
ni us=E9s.=20
  Inspectez le bloc d'alimentation primaire pour =EAtre s=FBr qu'aucun =
c=E2ble n'est=20
  rompu. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>V=E9rifiez la mise =E0 la terre du ch=E2ssis du 5494. Les circuits =
de mise =E0 la=20
  terre sont repr=E9sent=E9s dans la figure<A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.8.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRGRND">=20
  "Circuits de mise =E0 la</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.8.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRGRND">terre"=20
  in topic LEGEND.8.5</A>. Mesurez la r=E9sistance entre la tige de =
terre du=20
  cordon d'alimentation c.a. et n'importe quelle partie du ch=E2ssis =
m=E9tallique=20
  non =E9lectrifi=E9e. Elle ne doit pas d=E9passer 0,1 ohm. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Assurez-vous qu'aucun des condensateurs du bloc d'alimentation ne =
fuit ou=20
  n'est d=E9form=E9. </LI></OL>

<H2>LEGEND.9 Procedimientos Para Inspection De Seguridad De =

</P></PRE>Si se necesita llevar a cabo una inspecci=F3n de seguridad, =
empiece el=20
procedimiento con el interruptor de corriente de la Unidad de Control =
Remoto IBM=20
5494 (la 5494) en <B>OFF</B> y con el cord=F3n el=E9ctrico desenchufado =
del=20
tomacorriente. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Para m=E1s informaci=F3n sobre las inspecciones de seguridad, =
consulte las=20
siguientes referencias: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Todos los memorandums sobre servicio, avisos sobre cambios =
t=E9cnicos y=20
  ayudas para servicio para esta 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->

<H4>LEGEND.9.1 C=F3mo se Debe Llevar a Cabo Esta Inspecci=F3n de =
Seguridad</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Esta gu=EDa de inspecci=F3n ayuda a indentificar condiciones =
peligrosas en=20
la 5494 que est=E1 examinando. Durante la fabricaci=F3n, cada 5494 tiene =
todos los=20
art=EDculos de seguridad instalados para proporcionar protecci=F3n =
contra cualquier=20
da=F1o a los due=F1os, operadores y personal de servicio t=E9cnico. =
Deber=E1 usar buen=20
juicio para identificar si hay condiciones peligrosas de seguridad que =
no est=E9n=20
cubiertas en la gu=EDa de inspecci=F3n. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>Si determina que se encuentra presente cualquier condici=F3n de =
peligro,=20
p=F3ngase en contacto con el gerente en su =E1rea para que le recomiende =
la acci=F3n=20
que deber=E1 tomar antes de proporcionar servicio t=E9cnico a la 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Tambi=E9n considere las siguientes condiciones de peligro que =
pueden estar=20
presentes: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Peligros el=E9ctricos, especialmente de la corriente principal. =
Por ejemplo,=20
  un cuadro que no est=E9 bien conectado a tierra puede causar un choque =
el=E9ctrico=20
  serio o a=FAn fatal. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Peligros de explosi=F3n. Por ejemplo, un tubo de rayos cat=F3dicos =
(CRT) que=20
  tenga la cara da=F1ada o cuyos capacitores est=E9n distorsionados =
puede explotar y=20
  causar da=F1os serios. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Peligros por productos qu=EDmicos. Por ejemplo, el uso de =
solventes que no=20
  est=E9n especificados por IBM puede resultar en peligros el=E9ctricos, =
mec=E1nicos o=20
  de toxicidad. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>Esta gu=EDa contiene el procedimiento de =
inspecci=F3n de seguridad para=20
las siguientes =E1reas: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Inspecci=F3n externa=20
  <LI>Inspecci=F3n interna. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.9.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRLBLS2">"Etiqueta=20
de Seguridad" in topic LEGEND.9.4</A> donde est=E1 la etiqueta de =
seguridad en la=20
5494. Consulte esta figura cuando lleve a cabo la inspecci=F3n de =
seguridad.=20
<HR>

<H4>LEGEND.9.2 Inspecci=F3n Externa</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Lleve a cabo las siguientes comprobaciones: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>=BFEst=E1 presente, correctamente instalada y en buena condici=F3n =
la cubierta=20
  exterior? <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFEst=E1 en buena condici=F3n el cord=F3n el=E9ctrico de la 5494? =
=BFEs este el=20
  cord=F3n adecuado para este aparato? (Consulte <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/8.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRPARTCAT">Topic=20
  8, "Parts Catalog"</A> para averiguar el n=FAmero correcto de este =
repuesto.) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFTiene la 5494 el tomacorriente aprobado para su pa=EDs? =
(Consulte <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/8.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRPARTCAT">Topic=20
  8, "Parts Catalog" </A>para averiguar el tipo adecuado.) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFEst=E1 da=F1ado el conector de corriente en la parte trasera de =
la 5494? <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFEst=E1 buena la conexi=F3n a tierra de la corriente ca de un =
extremo a otro=20
  del cord=F3n el=E9ctrico? La resistencia de este conductor deber=E1 =
ser menor de 0,1=20
  ohm. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFEs el voltaje de la l=EDnea del cliente el correcto para la =
fuente de=20
  alimentaci=F3n de energ=EDa de la 5494? </LI></OL>
<HR>

<H4>LEGEND.9.3 Inspecci=F3n Interna</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Lleve a cabo las siguientes comprobaciones: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>=BFEst=E1 presente y bien asegurada la cubierta de la fuente de =
alimentaci=F3n=20
  de energ=EDa? <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFExisten cambios que obviamente no son de tecnolog=EDa IBM? Si =
la respuesta=20
  a esta pregunta es si, llene el formulario <CITE>Non-IBM</CITE>=20
  <CITE>Alteration</CITE> <CITE>Attachment</CITE> <CITE>Survey</CITE>, =
G150-0197=20
  [Cuestionario Sobre Cambios y Accesorios no IBM]. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFPuede ver tornillos flojos, contaminaci=F3n por productos =
qu=EDmicos, se=F1ales=20
  de agua o humedad, se=F1ales de da=F1o por fuego o humo, part=EDculas =
de metal o=20
  polvo, o cualquier otra condici=F3n interna que le parece peligrosa? =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFEst=E1 cualquiera de los cables visiblemente d=E9bil, roto o =
da=F1ado de alguna=20
  otra forma? Chequee el =E1rea de la energ=EDa principal para ver si =
hay cables=20
  rotos. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFEst=E1 bien conectado a tierra el chasis de la 5494? Los =
circuitos de=20
  puesta a tierra se muestran en<A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.9.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRGRND2">=20
  "Circuitos de Puesta a Tierra" in</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/LEGEND.9.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRGRND2">topic=20
  LEGEND.9.5</A>. Mida la resistencia desde el conector a tierra en el=20
  tomacorriente de energ=EDa ca hasta cualquier porci=F3n del chasis de =
metal que no=20
  lleve corriente el=E9ctrica. La resistencia deber=E1 ser menor de 0,1 =
ohm. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>=BFSe est=E1 saliendo o est=E1 distorsionado cualquiera de los =
capacitores del=20
  =E1rea de energ=EDa? </LI></OL>

  de alimentaci=F3n de energ=EDa? <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

  <LI>=BFEst=E1n bien instaladas y aseguradas todas las partes? =

<BR>

failures=20
in the IBM 5494 Remote Control Unit (hereafter referred to as the =
<I>5494</I>).=20
This book also contains information that you need to verify that the =
5494 is=20
operating correctly after a repair is complete. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>

<H2>PREFACE.1 Who Should Read This Book</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This book is for qualified maintenance personnel who service =
the 5494.=20
Maintenance personnel should have completed the 5494 education course.=20

a vertical line to the left of the change. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/CHANGES.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20

<HR>

<H3>CHANGES.1 Sixth Edition (November 1996)</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This manual supports the IBM 5494 Remote Control Unit Release =
3.2. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Release 3.2 of the 5494 provides the following changes that affect =
the=20
maintenance of the 5494: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>| The 5494 Frame Relay Token-Ring (FR-TR) Bridge Feature is =
available.=20
  <BR>| The 5494 operates as a bridge and forwards such protocols as IP =
and=20
  <BR>| IPX over the Frame Relay "virtual LAN." This feature consists of =
two=20
  <BR>| FR-TR Bridge System Diskettes and requires the installation of =
the <BR>|=20
  5494 Memory Expansion Feature. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| The 5494 Memory Expansion Feature is available. It consists of =
an <BR>|=20
  additional 2 MB of memory and installation instructions. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| The 5494 Utility Program can be run with DOS/V (Japan). =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| You can configure the 5494 to use the permanent (Universal) =
address on=20
  <BR>| the 5494 LAN card. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| You can configure the 5494 to set its date and time to the same =
date=20
  <BR>| and time used by the primary AS/400 system. This is useful in =
<BR>|=20
  coordinating error messages. The 5494 date and time is reset when the =
<BR>|=20
  controller is varied on. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| You can use the 5494 Utility Program to create a backup =
configuration.=20
  <BR>| When this configuration is placed on the 5494 system diskette =
and the=20
  <BR>| diskette used to power on the controller, the backup =
configuration is=20
  <BR>| used instead of the configuration in permanent storage. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| Continued operation of the 5494 is possible after experiencing =
<BR>|=20
  twinaxial cabling problems (error code 152). You can press =
<B>Enter</B> on=20
  <BR>| the 5494 Keypad, type <B>1</B> to select normal operations when =
message=20
  <BR>| <TT>002-05|.......0</TT> appears, and press <B>Enter</B> a =
second time.=20
  The 5494 will <BR>| activate in normal mode and log any twinaxial =
errors as=20
  they occur. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| Support has been added for LAN printers. </LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRLIBUSE>
<H1>1.0 Topic 1. Introduction</H1></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<BR>
</PRE>
<P>This topic contains the following information: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>How to use this book <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>General information about the IBM 5494 Remote Control Unit =
(hereafter=20
  referred to as the <I>5494</I>) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>A description of problem determination and maintenance for the =
5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL></OL></LI></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20

<A name=3DHDROVRVEW>
<H2>1.1 How to Use This Book</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This book contains the information you need to isolate and =
repair=20
failures in the 5494. If you need a general introduction to the 5494, =
begin with=20
<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRPRDINFO">"General=20
Product Information" in topic 1.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>If you do not need an introduction to the 5494, begin with<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAPS">=20
Topic 2,</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAPS">"Maintenance=20
Analysis Procedures (MAPs)," beginning at</A><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0100">=20
"MAP 0100: Start</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0100">of=20
Call," to diagnose</A> failures. From <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAPS">Topic=20
2</A>, you will be directed to other topics to complete the task. Use <A =

href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/8.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRPARTCAT">Topic=20
8, "Parts Catalog," to get</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/8.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRPARTCAT">the=20
information you</A> need to order replacement parts.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRPRDINFO>
<H2>1.2 General Product Information</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The 5494 supports synchronous data link control (SDLC), X.21, =
X.25,=20
Token-Ring, Ethernet, and Frame-Relay protocols with communication =
speeds up to=20
19.2 Kbps when using EIA 232D, V.24, or V.28 interfaces, and speeds up =
to 128=20
Kbps when using X.21 or V.35 interfaces. Both 4-Mbps and 16-Mbps =
token-ring=20
speeds are supported; for Ethernet, 10 Mbps is supported. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The 5494 acts as an editing controller for a nonprogrammable =
workstation=20
(NWS). It processes keystrokes and fields locally without communicating =
with the=20
Application System/400 (AS/400) system, thus improving response time for =

processing keystrokes and providing feedback to the operator. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| For a programmable workstation (PWS) or a LAN-attached =
printer, the=20
5494 <BR>| manages the exchange of information between the PWS and the =
AS/400=20
system <BR>| over the communication network and allows multiple =
LAN-attached=20
devices to <BR>| share one communication line to the AS/400 system. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| Using the 5494 Frame Relay Token-Ring Bridge Feature, the =
5494=20
bridges <BR>| protocols such as IP or IPX from a token-ring attached PWS =
over a=20
frame <BR>| relay network. The bridge partner receiving these frames can =
be an=20
AS/400 <BR>| or another bridge such as the IBM 6611, 2217, or PS/2 =
running <BR>|=20
RouteXpander/2. Any protocols supported by the bridge partner can be =
<BR>| used.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The 5494 provides: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>(Offline) extended diagnostics that test all internal hardware =
components=20
  and automatically wrap and test 5494 communication cables. See <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
  Extended Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>(Online) concurrent mode that displays 5494 internal information. =
This=20
  information can be accessed at the 5494 operator panel, a PWS, or an =
NWS. See=20
  <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM2013">Topic=20
  6, "Concurrent Mode from the Operator Panel or</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM2013">Utility=20
  Program," and</A><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRDWSCONM">=20
  Topic 7, "Concurrent Mode from an NWS (Online)"</A> for more =
information. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>The 5494, now available in only one =
model, can connect up to 56=20
twinaxial workstations (seven workstations per port) if the Twinaxial =
Expansion=20
Kit is installed. The 5494 communicates with an AS/400 system that is =
running=20
Operating System/400 (OS/400) Version 2 Release 1 (Modification 1) or =
higher.=20
OS/400 Version 2 Release 3 or higher is required for 56-device support. =
The=20
workstations can be connected to the 5494 using twinaxial cabling, the =
IBM=20
Cabling System, or telephone-twisted pair (TTP) cable using the IBM 5299 =

Terminal Multiconnector Model 3. Both analog and digital communication =
networks=20
are supported.<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGTRGC">=20
Figure 1</A> is an example of this support. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGTRGC>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-15?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 15" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P15.gif"></A>          </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 1. Example of a 5494 AS/400 Attachment Configuration
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>In addition to the configurations listed previously, the 5494 =
supports=20
attachment to a LAN. The LAN can be either Token Ring or Ethernet and =
the 5494=20
can attach to one or the other, but not both. The Token-Ring Upgrade Kit =
or the=20
Ethernet Upgrade Kit allows for one of the following LAN configurations: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>LAN Gateway configuration <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This configuration allows connection of a maximum of 80 downstream =

  workstations (56 of which can be attached to twinaxial ports). =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGC1F1">Figure=20
  2</A> is an example of this configuration. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>LAN AS/400 system attachment configuration <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This configuration allows connection of a 5494 to an AS/400 system =

  through a LAN. A maximum of 56 workstations can be attached to =
twinaxial=20
  ports. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGC2F2">Figure=20
  3</A> is an example of this configuration. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>The Twinaxial Expansion Kit provides =
additional twinaxial ports by=20
adding a second twinaxial adapter in the 5494 to support an additional =
28=20
twinaxial workstations. This Twinaxial Expansion Adapter supports four=20
additional twinaxial ports, for a total of 56 twinaxial devices. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| The 5494 Frame Relay Token-Ring Bridge Feature requires an=20
additional 2MB <BR>| (megabytes) of memory for the 5494. This memory is=20
available as the 5494 <BR>| Memory Expansion Feature. The FR-TR Bridge =
Feature=20
on the FR-TR Bridge <BR>| System Diskette bridges frames from=20
token-ring-attached PWSs over the <BR>| frame relay network. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| The Twinaxial Expansion Kit, Token-Ring Upgrade Kit, Frame =
Relay=20
<BR>| Token-Ring Bridge Feature, Memory Expansion Feature, and Ethernet =
Upgrade=20
Kit are features and must be purchased separately. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGC1F1>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-16?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 16" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P16.gif"></A>          </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 2. Example of a 5494 LAN Gateway Configuration
<P>
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGC2F2>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-17?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 17" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P17.gif"></A>          </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 3. Example of a 5494 LAN AS/400 Attachment Configuration
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The 5494 can be configured to communicate concurrently with up to =
four=20
AS/400 systems over a single physical link. Concurrent host attachment, =
as it is=20
called throughout this manual, permits NWSs and printers to communicate =
with=20
different AS/400 systems within the communication network without using =
AS/400=20
display station or printer passthrough functions. PWSs attached to a =
5494 have=20
always had this ability. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Concurrent host attachment uses the SNA session level routing =
capabilities=20
of an APPN network or SNA subarea network to reach multiple AS/400 =
systems in=20
the network.<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGCHANET">=20
Figure 4</A> is an example of this configuration. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGCHANET>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-18?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 18" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P18.gif"></A>          </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 4. Example of a 5494 Concurrent Host Attachment
<P>
</P></PRE>

<A name=3DHDRGENLOC>
<H3>1.2.1 Front and Back of the 5494</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This section contains figures that will help you locate the =
5494=20
liquid crystal display (LCD), light-emitting diodes (LEDs), field =
replaceable=20
units (FRUs), and cable connectors. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/1.2.1?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGC1F2">Figure=20
5</A> shows the front and back of the 5494 and identifies the LCD, LEDs, =
power=20
push button, and cable connections that you may need to locate. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGC1F2>   <A =

             Installed

<H3>1.2.2 5494 FRUs</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRANDR">Topic=20
5, "Removal and Replacement Procedures,"</A> contains removal and =
replacement=20
procedures for the following 5494 FRUs: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Cover=20
  <LI>Host-twinaxial adapter and Twinaxial Expansion Kit=20
  <LI>Token-Ring adapter=20
  <LI>Ethernet adapter=20
  <LI>Power push button and speaker assembly=20
  <LI>Diskette drive=20
  <LI>Operator panel=20
  <LI>Single inline memory module (SIMM)=20
  <LI>Power supply=20
  <LI>Planar. </LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMIM0320>
<H3>1.2.3 5494 Operator Panel Components</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<BR>
   The operator panel is located on the right-hand front side of the =
5494 and
   consists of a keypad, an LCD, and four LEDs (Ready, Call 5494 =
Service, See
   PD Guide, and Test Mode) that indicate operating status.  An 8051
   microprocessor controls the LCD, LEDs, and the keypad.  =
Communications
   between the planar and the operator panel are through a serial port.
<P>
</P></PRE>The following sections describe the 5494 LCD, keypad, and =
LEDs.=20
<HR>

<H3>1.2.4 LCD Description</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-20?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 20" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P20.gif"></A>         =20
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE>The LCD has 16 character positions. It is blank and displays a =
cursor=20
in <BR>| the rightmost position when not in use. When the 5494 operator =
panel is=20
in use, there will always be a message code (002-01 in the above =
example)=20
displayed on the left-hand side of the LCD. The message codes are =
described in=20
<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMESSAGE">"Message=20
Codes" in topic 3.1</A>. When the 5494 is in use, the LCD can also =
contain, in=20
the data field on the right-hand side of the LCD, a system reference =
code (SRC)=20
or information as defined by the message code. In the example, the data =
field=20
contains an SRC. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If an error occurs before or during normal operation, both a =
message code=20
and an SRC will be displayed on the LCD and an LED will be lit. If more =
than one=20
error occurs during normal operation, the message codes and SRCs will =
cycle at=20
3-second intervals. If the error clears (a link is established after a =
failure,=20
for example), the message code and SRC will be removed from the LCD by =
the 5494.=20

<HR>

<H3>1.2.5 Codes Displayed on the LCD</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<BR>
   The codes that are displayed on the LCD are used to determine the
   condition of the 5494 hardware and software and can be displayed as =
the
   result of an error or a request for information.<A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPD">  Topic 3, "5494 Message</A>
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPD">Codes and System Reference Codes =
(SRCs)," contains the 5494 message codes</A>
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPD">and</A> SRCs that can be displayed.
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Note:</B> If you are viewing requested information, when =
finished=20
you should always press <B>Esc</B> to clear the LCD. If an error occurs =
while=20
you are viewing requested information, the Call 5494 Service or See PD =
Guide LED=20
will be lit to indicate that an error exists.=20
<HR>

<H3>1.2.6 Keypad Description</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The keys on the keypad allow commands to be entered and sent =
to the=20
5494, and include: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>Req</B>=20
  <DD>Initiates a request function <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>PF1</B>=20
  <DD>Used for special requests <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>PF2</B>=20
  <DD>Used for special requests <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Esc</B>=20
  <DD>Used to cancel a request <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Alt</B>=20
  <DD>Enables the alternate hexadecimal values of keys 4 through 9, to =
be used=20
  with keys PF1, PF2, and Esc for additional special functions. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Enter</B>=20
  <DD>Signals to the 5494 the end of an input string <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Clear</B>=20
  <DD>Clears a value being entered and allows you to begin again =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>0</B> <B>to</B> <B>9</B>=20
  <DD>Numerics 0 to 9 <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Alt+4</B>=20
  <DD>Hexadecimal A <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Alt+5</B>=20
  <DD>Hexadecimal B <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Alt+6</B>=20
  <DD>Hexadecimal C <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Alt+7</B>=20
  <DD>Hexadecimal D <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Alt+8</B>=20
  <DD>Hexadecimal E <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Alt+9</B>=20
  <DD>Hexadecimal F <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Up</B> <B>arrow</B>=20
  <DD>Used to scroll up through several choices or panels of data =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Down</B> <B>arrow</B>=20
  <DD>Used to scroll down through several choices or panels of data =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Left</B> <B>arrow</B>=20
  <DD>Used to move the cursor left or scroll to additional fields of =
data <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Right</B> <B>arrow</B>=20
  <DD>Used to move the cursor right or scroll to additional fields of =
data.=20
</DD></DL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRLEDDESC>
<H3>1.2.7 LED Descriptions</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<BR>
   There are six LEDs on the front of the 5494:  the Power On LED, the
   Diskette Activity LED, and the four operator panel LEDs.  The =
following
   list describes each LED.
<P>
</P></PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>Power</B> <B>On</B>=20
  <DD>When this green LED is on, it indicates that the 5494 is receiving =
power. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Diskette</B> <B>Activity</B>
  <DD><B>LED</B> When this amber LED is on, it indicates that the 5494 =
is=20
  reading or writing to the diskette in the diskette drive. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> Do not remove the diskette from the diskette =
drive or=20
  turn the 5494 power <B>OFF</B> (<B>0</B>) while the diskette activity =
LED is=20
  on. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Ready</B>=20
  <DD>When this green LED is on, it indicates that the 5494 has =
successfully=20
  completed a power-on self-test (POST), has loaded its code, and is =
ready for=20
  operation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Call</B> <B>5494</B> <B>Service</B>=20
  <DD>When this amber LED is on, it indicates that the 5494 has detected =
a=20
  problem, has isolated the problem to the 5494, and that 5494 service =
should be=20
  called. The LCD displays additional information to define the problem. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>See</B> <B>PD</B> <B>Guide</B>=20
  <DD>When this amber LED is on, it indicates an error condition that =
cannot be=20
  immediately isolated to the 5494. The customer may or may not need to =
do=20
  additional problem determination to isolate the failing element and =
determine=20
  which service vendor to call. The LCD displays additional information =
to=20
  define the problem. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Test</B> <B>Mode</B>=20
  <DD>When this amber LED is on, it indicates one of the following =
conditions: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>If the Ready LED is off, the 5494 is running tests.=20
    <LI>If the Ready LED is on, the 5494 is in configuration mode or =
concurrent=20
    mode information can be viewed from a workstation. =
</LI></UL></DD></DL>
<HR>

<H3>1.2.8 Diskette Drive</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The diskette drive allows the 5494 to load information stored =
on the=20
system diskette into the 5494 storage. It also allows the 5494 to copy =
error and=20
configuration information to the system diskette. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The diskette drive has a diskette-eject button and one LED. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The diskette activity LED comes on when the diskette drive is =
running. The=20
diskette-eject button is used to eject the diskette from the diskette =
drive for=20
removal.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRDISKET>
<H3>1.2.9 Diskettes</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Four 3.5-inch diskettes are shipped with the 5494: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>One 5494 System Diskette and one backup copy of the 5494 System =
Diskette <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Keep the backup copy of the 5494 System Diskette with an=20
  <CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>5494</CITE> <CITE>Remote</CITE> =
<CITE>Control</CITE>=20
  <CITE>Unit</CITE> <CITE>Problem</CITE> <CITE>Determination</CITE>=20
  <CITE>Guide</CITE> <CITE>Quick</CITE> <CITE>Reference</CITE> in the =
front=20
  pocket of the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>One 5494 Utility Program diskette for Disk Operating System (DOS) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>One 5494 Utility Program diskette for Operating System/2 (OS/2) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| <B>Note:</B> The Frame Relay Token-Ring Bridge Feature =
includes=20
  two 5494 <BR>| FR-TR Bridge System Diskettes. They are used in place =
of the=20
  base <BR>| 5494 System Diskettes when configured for the bridge. The =
5494=20
  <BR>| Utility Program diskettes are the same whether the feature is =
used or=20
  <BR>| not. </LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRDISKETR>
<H3>1.2.10 Diskette Replacement</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>
<P>To order replacement diskettes for the 5494: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Inside the U.S. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Make sure that you have the serial number of your 5494 available. =
Call=20
  1-800-334-1089. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Outside the U.S. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Make sure that you have the serial number of your 5494 available.=20
  Contact your local IBM branch office. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><B>Note:</B> Replacement system diskettes =
can be used immediately=20
with the 5494. You do not need to copy your configuration data to a new=20
diskette.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRBEEPS>
<H3>1.2.11 Beeps that Occur during Power-On</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<BR>
   The 5494 uses beeps during power-on to help indicate if the 5494 is
   correctly installed and functioning, if there are hardware problems, =
or if
   there is a 5494 system setup problem.  The following list describes =
the
   meaning of the beeps:
<P>
</P></PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>1</B> <B>beep</B>=20
  <DD>Indicates that no problems have been detected during the POST. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>2</B> <B>beeps</B>=20
  <DD>Indicates that a problem has been detected. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>A message code will be displayed on the LCD (if possible) =
indicating the=20
  type of problem. If the problem does not prevent the POST from =
continuing, the=20
  POST will wait for input from the operator panel keypad. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>3</B> <B>beeps</B>=20
  <DD>Indicates that either the operator panel or the planar is =
defective and=20
  must be replaced. </DD></DL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMIM0460>
<H3>1.2.12 5494 Software Configuration</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The first time the 5494 power is turned <B>ON</B> (<B>|</B>), =
the 5494=20
searches for configuration data in storage. If it does not find =
configuration=20
data in storage, the 5494 searches for configuration data on the system=20
diskette. If that data has not been changed since the diskette was =
manufactured,=20
the 5494 automatically enters configuration mode, thus allowing the=20
configuration information to be entered. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The 5494 supports three methods of entering the configuration =
information:=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Using the 5494 Utility Program on a personal computer (PC), =
Personal=20
  System/2 (PS/2) computer, or Personal System/55 (PS/55) computer. If =
the=20
  Utility Program is being operated in interactive mode, the =
configuration files=20
  can be sent to the 5494 directly from the computer. Otherwise, it is =
stored on=20
  diskette. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Using the keypad and the LCD on the operator panel. A =
configuration file=20
  previously created on diskette can be copied to 5494 storage. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Using a 5250 NWS attached to the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL>Each method of configuration is explained in the=20
<CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>5494</CITE> <CITE>Remote</CITE> =
<CITE>Control</CITE>=20
<CITE>Unit</CITE> <CITE>User's</CITE> <CITE>Guide</CITE>.=20
<P><PRE></PRE>If a new system diskette is installed in the 5494's =
diskette drive=20
and valid configuration data is in storage, the 5494 copies the =
configuration=20
data from storage onto the new system diskette, automatically creating a =
backup.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If the 5494's power is <B>ON</B> (<B>|</B>) and the configuration =
data in=20
storage is bad, for example, the 5494 uses the backup configuration file =
on the=20
system diskette to operate and displays a message code on the LCD =
indicating=20
that the 5494's storage is defective. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE><BR>| <B>Note:</B> If the 5494 is configured with an incompatible=20
configuration, the <BR>| 5494 enters configuration mode to allow you to =
enter=20
the correct <BR>| information when you first power <B>ON</B> (|) the =
5494 with=20
the 5494 FR-TR <BR>| Bridge System Diskette.=20
<HR>

5494.=20
  See <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=

<A name=3DHDRMIM2050>
<H2>1.3 Error Information</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Two error logs are kept to record errors that occur on the =
5494 and=20
all attached workstations: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>The 5494 error log <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>The error log buffer <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The contents of the error log buffer are transmitted to the AS/400 =

  system and stored there when the error log buffer is full, and at the =
end of=20
  each session. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL>Communication error counters and statistical =
counters are=20
also kept by the 5494 and transmitted to the AS/400 system. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSTATCNT">"Statistical=20
Counters (6E</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSTATCNT">and=20
6F)" in topic B.10</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSAND3">"Communication=20
Error and Statistical Counters" in</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSAND3">topic=20
B.10.1</A>, and <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.10?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRTRDSC">"Displaying=20
5494 LAN Gateway Statistical Counters" in</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.10?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRTRDSC">topic=20
6.2.10 </A>for more information.=20

NWS, or a PWS. See <A=20

<A name=3DHDRPHILOS>
<H3>1.3.2 Problem Determination and Repair</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>If the Call 5494 Service LED on the 5494 is on, the customer =
records=20
the error information and contacts 5494 service. You should bring any =
FRUs that=20
were indicated by the error information. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If the See PD Guide LED is lit, the customer first performs the =
problem=20
determination procedures (PDPs) to determine if a problem exists. The=20
<CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>5494</CITE> <CITE>Remote</CITE> =
<CITE>Control</CITE>=20
<CITE>Unit</CITE> <CITE>User's</CITE> <CITE>Guide</CITE> and a =
workstation=20
attached to the 5494 are used to perform these procedures. The =
customer's PDPs=20
may produce an SRC, a message code, or a symptom. The customer should =
provide=20
you with the SRC, message code, or symptom. You should confirm that the =
customer=20
used the PDPs. If the PDPs indicate a 5494 failure, you should bring any =
FRUs=20
that were indicated by the message codes or SRCs. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>5494</CITE> <CITE>Remote</CITE>=20
<CITE>Control</CITE> <CITE>Unit</CITE> <CITE>Maintenance</CITE>=20
<CITE>Information</CITE> is designed for you (the on-site CE) to use in=20
resolving the majority of 5494 problems quickly and efficiently. Begin =
all 5494=20
problem analysis at <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0100">"MAP=20
0100: Start of</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0100">Call"=20
in topic 2.1.1 </A>and continue as directed from that point. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The following information is described in this book to aid you in =
on-site=20
problem isolation: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Power-on diagnostics=20
  <LI>(Offline) extended diagnostics=20
  <LI>(Online) concurrent mode=20
  <LI>Online (AS/400 system) tests=20
  <LI>Cable signal quality check and other service aids. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>When you complete the FRU replacement, =
use <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRVER">"Verifying=20
5494 Operation" in</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRVER">topic=20
4.3 </A>to verify that the 5494 is repaired and operating correctly. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If you cannot resolve the problem using this book, request =
technical=20
assistance. The problem may require special tools or procedures that are =

available only through the service support structure. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> Do not stack another 5494 or any electrical =
equipment=20
directly on top of the 5494. This could result in intermittent errors =
during=20
operation.=20

<A name=3DHDRMAPUSE>
<H2>2.1 Using the MAPs</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>These MAPs are designed for use with <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCEPROC">Topic=20
4, "5494 Verification</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCEPROC">Procedures."</A>=20
Definitions of terms and abbreviations that are not common, but are used =
in the=20
MAPs, are in the glossary of this book. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>When you use the MAPs, you must: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Read carefully. The MAPs produce reliable results only if you =
follow=20
  instructions and answer the questions accurately. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Follow the sequence. Always perform the procedure one step at a =
time. Some=20
  steps have additional information that pertains to that step. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Follow the instructions. Carry out the instructions exactly and in =

  sequence. Questions rely on instructions given immediately before the=20
  questions. Do not change the conditions resulting from the =
instructions before=20
  you answer the questions. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL></OL></LI></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>2.1.1 MAP 0100: Start of Call</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>2.1.2 MAP 0200: Twinaxial Workstation MAP</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =

<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMAP0100>
<H3>2.1.1 MAP 0100: Start of Call</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE></PRE>Before beginning, record all symptoms reported by the =
customer. If=20
the 5494 is powered on, record any failure indications that you observe =
at the=20
operator panel and the workstation screen. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DSTPstep1>    ___ </A>
   |<B>001</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   System reference codes (SRCs) are displayed on workstations and =
sometimes
   on the 5494 operator panel LCD.  On a workstation, SRCs are composed =
of 3
   to 6 alphanumeric characters that blink and are located in the upper =
left
   or right corner, or the lower left corner of the screen.  The 5494
   displays  3- to 6-character SRCs on the right-hand side of the =
operator
   panel LCD.
<P>
   <B>Is</B> <B>an</B> <B>SRC</B> <B>displayed</B> <B>on</B> <B>any</B> =
<B>workstation</B><B>?</B>
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ12"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |
    |    |__=20
    |   |<B>002</B>|
    |   |___|
    |
    |   Go to <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTEP2">Step 004</A>.
    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ12>    |</A>
    |__=20
   |<B>003</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   Look up the SRC in <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">"SRCs" in topic 3.2</A> and perform =
the indicated action.
<HR>

<P>
<A name=3DSTPstep2>    ___ </A>
   |<B>004</B>|
   |___|
   (From step 002)
<P>
   Go to the 5494.
<P>
   - Message codes are composed of 3 numbers, sometimes followed by a =
dash
     and 2-digit qualifier, that are displayed on the left-hand side of =
the
     5494 LCD.
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Note:</B> If the LCD is <B>not</B> blank with a cursor in =
the=20
rightmost position, press <B>Esc</B> on the keypad to clear any =
requested=20
information that is not an error. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
   <B>Is</B> <B>a</B> <B>message</B> <B>code</B> <B>displayed</B> =
<B>on</B> <B>the</B> <B>left-hand</B> <B>side</B> <B>of</B> <B>the</B> =
<B>LCD?</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =

<P><A name=3DSTPstep8>___ </A>|<B>017</B>| |___|=20
<P>- Perform the following steps:=20
<P><PRE></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Turn the 5494 power <B>OFF</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>At the 4-port end of the twinaxial workstation attachment =
cable,=20
  swap the cable of the port to which the failing workstations are =
connected=20
  with the cable of another port. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Turn the 5494 power <B>ON</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Verify the twinaxial workstation attachment cable ports =
again by=20
  pressing <B>REQ</B>, typing <B>210</B>, and pressing <B>Enter</B>. Use =
the up=20
  and down arrows to scroll through the connections. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><B>Did</B> <B>the</B> <B>failing</B> <B>port</B>=20

in topic 5.7.2</A> and replace the host-twinaxial adapter. | <A =
name=3DSTPstep9><A=20

<P><A name=3DSTPstep9b>___ </A>|<B>022</B>| |___|=20
<P>- Make sure that:=20
<P><PRE></PRE>

  <LI><B></B>The twinaxial workstation attachment cable is connected =
securely to=20
  the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>

  twinaxial attachment cable. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>The cables are connected securely to the workstations. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><B>Did</B> <B>you</B> <B>find</B> <B>and</B> =
<B>correct</B>=20
<B>any</B> <B>cable-attachment</B> <B>problem?</B> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=

in topic 5.7.2</A> and replace the host-twinaxial adapter. | <A=20
name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ20>|</A> |__ |<B>024</B>| |___|=20
<P>Refer to the <CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>5494</CITE> <CITE>Remote</CITE>=20
<CITE>Control</CITE> <CITE>Unit</CITE> <CITE>User's</CITE> =
<CITE>Guide</CITE>=20
procedures for establishing communication and work with the customer to=20

workstation is=20
no longer failing.=20

code 001-01 should be displayed in approximately 5 seconds. Within 1 =

different message should be displayed on the operator panel.=20

   |<B>001</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   When a workstation begins receiving polls from the 5494:
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE></PRE><PRE></PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>The cursor moves from the upper right to the upper left side of =
the=20
  screen. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>A System Available indicator appears at the bottom of the screen. =
(The=20
  location and appearance of this indicator depend on the type of =
display you=20
  are using.) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><B>Does</B> <B>at</B> <B>least</B> <B>one</B>=20
<B>workstation</B> <B>have</B> <B>these</B> <B>indications?</B> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ30"><B>Yes</B></A>=20
<B>No</B> | | | |__ | |<B>002</B>| | |___| | | <B>Is</B> <B>a</B> =
<B>message</B>=20
<B>displayed</B> <B>on</B> <B>the</B> <B>5494</B> <B>LCD?</B> | <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ31"><B>Yes</B></A>=20
<B>No</B> | | | | | |__ | | |<B>003</B>| | | |___| | | | | Go to <A=20

<A=20
name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ30>|</A> |__ |<B>005</B>| |___|=20
<P>- Press the <B>Error</B> <B>Reset</B> key to clear any displayed SRC. =

<P>A failing workstation has one or more of the following conditions:=20
<P><PRE></PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>System Available indicator off. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <LI>Failure in free-key mode. (See <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRFREEKEY">"Free-Key=20
  Mode" in topic B.2</A> for instructions.) <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>An operator-reported keyboard, display, or printer problem. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>A printer displays an error code. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><B>Do</B> <B>any</B> <B>attached</B> =
<B>workstations</B>=20
<B>have</B> <B>one</B> <B>or</B> <B>more</B> <B>of</B> <B>these</B>=20
<B>conditions?</B> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ32"><B>Yes</B></A>=20
<B>No</B> | | | |__ | |<B>006</B>| | |___| | | - Go to <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#STPM2S60">Step=20
055</A>. | <A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ32>|</A> |__ |<B>007</B>| |___|=20
<P><B>Is</B> <B>the</B> <B>System</B> <B>Available</B> <B>indicator</B>=20
<B>continuously</B> <B>on</B> <B>at</B> <B>the</B> <B>failing</B>=20
<B>workstation?</B> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ33"><B>Yes</B></A>=20
<B>No</B> | | | |__ | |<B>008</B>| | |___| | | - Go to <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.2?DT=3D19961016091447#STPM2S123">Step=20
052</A>. | <A name=3DSTPm2s130><A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ33>|</A></A> |__ =

<TT>200||1"2"3=194"5"</TT> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

arrow=20
next to the 4 represents the status of the AS/400 system. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>If the link is active, " will be displayed.=20
  <LI>If it is down, =19 will be displayed. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->

<H3>2.1.4 MAP 0400: Diskette Drive Problem</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ66></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"36%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Symptom</B> <B>Explanation</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"63%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Conditions</B> <B>That</B> <B>Could</B> <B>Cause</B> <B>This</B> =
<B>Symptom</B>    </FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"36%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> A diskette error code is=20
 displayed in the LCD.   =20
                         =20
                         =20
                         =20
                         =20
                          </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"63%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =B0   The diskette is =
write-protected or     =20
     damaged.                               =20
                                            =20
 =B0   The diskette drive or signal cable is  =20
     failing.                               =20
                                            =20
 =B0   The planar is failing.                  =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DSTPddr1>    ___ </A>
   |<B>001</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   - Make sure the write-protect tab on the <B>backup</B> diskette is =
closed.
<P>
   - Insert the <B>backup</B> diskette and turn the 5494 power <B>ON</B> =
(<B>|</B>).
<P>
   <B>Did</B> <B>the</B> <B>Ready</B> <B>LED</B> <B>come</B> <B>on?</B>
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.4?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ67"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |
    |    |__=20
    |   |<B>002</B>|
    |   |___|
    |
    |   - Go to <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.4?DT=3D19961016091447#STPDDR2">Step 004</A>.
    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ67>    |</A>
    |__=20
   |<B>003</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   End of call.
<P>
   Inform the customer that the diskette is defective and recommend that =
a
   replacement diskette be ordered.
<HR>

<P>
<A name=3DSTPddr2>    ___ </A>
   |<B>004</B>|
   |___|
   (From step 002)
<P>
   - Turn the 5494 power <B>OFF</B> (<B>0</B>).
<P>
   - Remove the 5494 cover.  See <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">"Cover Removal and Replacement" =
in</A>
     <A =
