02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">topic 5.7.1</A>.
<P>
   - Turn the 5494 power <B>ON</B> (<B>|</B>).
<P>
   Power supply output should be within the following tolerances:
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ68></A>   + 5 test point to ground               + =
5.25 to + 4.82 VDC

</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3DHDRMAP0910>
<H3>2.1.5 MAP 0500: Twinaxial Cabling (Port =
Tester)</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE></PRE>This MAP directs you to locate cable and workstation =
problems using=20
the AS/400 System Port Tester. If you do not have access to a port =
tester, go=20
to<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.6?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0901">=20
"MAP 0600: Twinaxial Cabling (Resistance Measurements)" in</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.6?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0901">topic=20
2.1.6</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>You can use the IBM Workstation Controller Port Tester (IBM P/N =
94X2040)=20
to isolate cabling and port problems on the 5494. The port tester is =
shown in <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.5.2?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGC4PTA">Figure=20
6 in topic 2.1.5.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Attach the port tester directly to one of the following =
components: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>A twinaxial port or cable=20
  <LI>A twisted-pair port or cable=20
  <LI>The twinaxial adapter on an IBM Cabling System. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>The port tester monitors signals from the =
twinaxial ports on the=20
5494. Cables being checked must be connected to a 5494 twinaxial port. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A name=3DDGR><STRONG>DANGER</STRONG></A> <BR><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D80><!-- * -->
    =
________________________________________________________________________ =

   | <STRONG>Do</STRONG> <STRONG>not</STRONG> <STRONG>use</STRONG> =
<STRONG>the</STRONG> <STRONG>port</STRONG> <STRONG>tester</STRONG> =
<STRONG>during</STRONG> <STRONG>electrical</STRONG> =
<STRONG>storms.</STRONG>                   |
   =
|________________________________________________________________________=
|
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Note:</B> For a translation of this safety notice, see <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/A.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPA">Appendix=20
A, "Safety</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/A.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPA">Notices."</A>=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> Remove and connect cables carefully. You can =
damage=20
connectors if you use force. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.5.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>2.1.5.2 Twisted-Pair Test</A> </LI></UL>
<HR>

<H4>2.1.5.1 Twinaxial Test</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Move the selector switch to the left (1) position. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Attach the appropriate port tester twinaxial connector to =
the port=20
  or cable you are testing, or to a twinaxial adapter attached to the =
port or=20
  cable you are testing. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If the twinaxial plug is needed, remove the twinaxial =
cable=20
  from the twinaxial cable holders located on the side of the port =
tester. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Push and hold the test button for 15 seconds or until one =
of the=20
  following conditions occurs: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>Only the green light comes on. This indicates that the port or =
cable=20
    between the port tester and the 5494 is good. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>Only the yellow light comes on. This indicates that the wires in =
the=20
    cable are reversed somewhere between the port tester and the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>Neither the green nor yellow light comes on. This indicates that =
there=20
    is no signal on the cable between the port tester and the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This can also indicate that: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
    <UL>
      <LI>The selector switch is in the wrong position.=20
      <LI>The port tester is attached to the wrong port or cable.=20
      <LI>The attachment to the port or cable is not secure. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
    <LI>Both the green and yellow lights come on. This indicates that =
either the=20
    selector switch is in the self-test position or the port tester is =
not=20
    working correctly. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the port tester connector from the cable or port you =
tested.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>If the twinaxial plug was used, put the twinaxial cable =
back into=20
  the twinaxial cable holders. </LI></OL>
<HR>

<H4>2.1.5.2 Twisted-Pair Test</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Move the selector switch to the right (2) position. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Attach the appropriate port tester twisted-pair connector =
to the=20
  port or cable you are testing. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If you need the twisted-pair plug, remove it from the =

  twisted-pair cable compartment located at the bottom of the port =
tester. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Push and hold the test button for 15 seconds or until one =
of the=20
  following conditions occurs: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>Only the green light comes on. This indicates that the port or =
cable=20
    between the port tester and the control unit is good. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>Only the yellow light comes on. This indicates that the wires in =
the=20
    cable are reversed somewhere between the port tester and the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>Neither the green nor yellow light comes on. This indicates that =
there=20
    is no signal on the cable between the port tester and the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This can also indicate that: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
    <UL>
      <LI>The selector switch is in the wrong position.=20
      <LI>The port tester is attached to the wrong port or cable.=20
      <LI>The attachment to the port or cable is not secure. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
    <LI>Both the green and yellow lights come on. This indicates that =
either the=20
    selector switch is in the self-test position or the port tester is =
not=20
    working correctly. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the port tester connector from the cable or port you =
tested.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>If you used the twisted-pair plug, put the twisted-pair =
cable back=20
  into the twisted-pair cable compartment. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGC4PTA>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-22?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 22" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P22.gif"></A>          </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 6. Port Tester
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMAP0901>
<H3>2.1.6 MAP 0600: Twinaxial Cabling (Resistance =
Measurements)</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE></PRE>This MAP directs you to use resistance measurements to =
locate cable=20
and workstation problems. This technique works, but it is slow and =
tedious. If=20
you have access to an IBM Workstation Controller Port Tester, see <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0910">"MAP</A>=20
<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0910">0500:=20
Twinaxial Cabling (Port Tester)" in topic 2.1.5</A> for an improved =
method of=20
finding cable or workstation problems. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>To use this MAP in isolating a problem with the twinaxial cable or =
a=20
workstation attached to the 5494, perform the following actions: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Obtain copies of the IBM 5494 Remote Workstation Setup Worksheets. =

  <LI>Identify the failing workstations and the 5494 port used for =
attachment. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>If the System Available indicator is off =
at all attached=20
workstations, all workstations are failing. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If the System Available indicator is on at any attached =
workstation, use=20
the following procedure to identify the failing workstations: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Make sure that the power at all workstations is turned on and that =
the=20
  workstations are connected to the cabling system. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Confirm that the SRC 0081, indicating that too many workstations =
are=20
  attached, does not appear at any workstation position on the screen. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Compare the Remote Workstation Setup Worksheets with the =
information you=20
  gathered when verifying workstation connections to identify all =
failing=20
  workstations on all 5494 ports used. See <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.11?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRTADS">"Displaying=20
  the</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.11?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRTADS">Status=20
  of 5494 Devices Attached to Twinaxial Ports" in topic 6.2.11</A> for=20
  instructions. A workstation is failing if: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>Its power is turned on=20
    <LI>It is connected to the cabling system=20
    <LI>It is not shown on the operator panel when verifying workstation =

    connections. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><B>Note:</B> If more than one port is used, =
determine which ports=20
  have failing workstations attached. If more than one port has failing=20
  workstations attached, do the steps in this MAP, starting at <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.6?DT=3D19961016091447#STPTW01">Step=20
  001</A>, <B>once</B> <B>for</B> <B>each</B> <B>port</B>, with failing=20
  workstations attached. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><A name=3DSTPtw01>___ </A>|<B>001</B>| |___|=20
<P><B>Are</B> <B>all</B> <B>workstations</B> <B>attached</B> <B>to</B>=20
<B>this</B> <B>port</B> <B>failing?</B> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.6?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ71"><B>Yes</B></A>=20

maintenance or=20

  <LI>| | =B0 Cables are tightly and correctly connected. </LI></UL>| | =

   Perform the following steps at the workstations.  You will need the
   following items:
<P>

<UL>
  <LI>An ohmmeter=20
  <LI>Remote Workstation Setup Worksheets. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->

includes all of the=20
cables and accessories used to connect one or more workstations to a =

  shown in <A=20

  7</A>.) If any measurement is less than 5000 ohms, record the ohmmeter =

  connection that has the low resistance. <PRE></PRE><PRE =

    from socket 2 and check for the resistances as shown in | <A=20
    =

        <TD width=3D"83%" colSpan=3D3><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =

 &gt;5000 Ohms        </FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
    |
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
    |
    |
</PRE>
    <LI>| | =B0 If one or more resistance measurements are lower than =
the | normal=20
    range, reconnect the cable to socket 2. Repeat the | measurements at =
the=20
    next workstation until all measurements | are in the normal range or =
until=20
    you do the test at the | next-to-last workstation. |=20
    <LI>| | =B0 Answer <TT>YES</TT> to the following question as soon as =
all |=20
    measurements are in the normal range. | </LI></UL>| | </LI></OL>| | =
| <B>Are</B>=20
<B>all</B> <B>resistances</B> <B>in</B> <B>the</B> <B>normal</B> =
<B>range?</B> |=20
<A=20

<A=20
name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ74>|</A> |__ |<B>013</B>| |___| <PRE></PRE><PRE =

   - Attach a jumper to phase A to the shield at the twinaxial connector =
of
     the cable you disconnected in <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.6?DT=3D19961016091447#STPTW03">Step 007</A>.
<P>
   - At the 5494 end of the data path, set an ohmmeter to the 20k-ohm or
     higher scale.  Connect the positive lead to the shield and the =
negative
     lead to phase B.
<P>
   - Check for a resistance of more than 5000 ohms.
<P>
   <B>Is</B> <B>the</B> <B>resistance</B> <B>measurement</B> <B>more</B> =
<B>than</B> <B>5000</B> <B>ohms?</B>
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.6?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ77"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |
    |    |__=20
    |   |<B>014</B>|
    |   |___|
    |
    |   The phase leads are reversed in the data path, probably because =
of a
    |   cabling system problem.
    |
    |   - Report the problem to the customer and decide if you will =
continue
    |     to isolate the failure.
    |
    |   <B>Do</B> <B>you</B> <B>want</B> <B>to</B> <B>isolate</B> =
<B>the</B> <B>failure?</B>
    |   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.6?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ78"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |    |
    |    |    |__=20
    |    |   |<B>015</B>|
    |    |   |___|
    |    |
    |    |   - Reconnect all of the cables you disconnected.
    |    |
    |    |   End of call.
    |    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ78>    |    |</A>
    |    |__=20
    |   |<B>016</B>|
    |   |___|
    |
    |   - Leave the twinaxial cable to the last workstation =
disconnected.
    |
    |   Starting at the workstation nearest the 5494, perform the =
following
    |   steps at each workstation:
    |
    |   - Set an ohmmeter to the 20k-ohm or higher scale.
    |
    |   - Disconnect the twinaxial cable at socket 2 of the workstation.
    |
    |   - Connect the ohmmeter to the twinaxial cable disconnected from
    |     socket 2 as follows: the positive lead of the ohmmeter to the
    |     shield and the negative lead to phase B.
    |
    |   - Check for a resistance of more than 5000 ohms.
    |
    |   - If the resistance measurement is less than 5000 ohms, =
reconnect the
    |     cable to socket 2 and repeat the measurement at the next
    |     workstation until the measurement is more than 5000 ohms or =
until
    |     you have done the measurement at the next-to-last workstation.
    |
    |   - When the measurement is more than 5000 ohms, the workstation =
you
    |     just disconnected or the cable from it to the preceding =
workstation
    |     is the cause of the failure.  Use <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM3003">"Workstation Twinaxial =
Interface</A>
    |     <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM3003">Check" in topic E.2.5</A> to =
check the workstation.
    |
    |   - If the resistance is less than 5000 ohms at all workstations, =
the
    |     cable to the last workstation is failing.
    |  =

of
   the following conditions:

is set to=20
  the terminate position (position 1) or has an auto-terminating =
connector=20
  installed. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>

has only=20
  one socket and the terminating resistance is always present). =

</P></PRE></LI></UL>- Determine if the data path is terminated =
correctly.=20

<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMAP0920>
<H3>2.1.7 MAP 0700: IBM Cabling System (Resistance =
Measurements)</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE></PRE>This MAP directs you to use resistance measurements to =
locate cable=20
and workstation problems. This technique works, but it is slow and =
tedious. If=20
you have access to an IBM Workstation Controller Port Tester, see <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0910">"MAP</A>=20
<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMAP0910">0500:=20
Twinaxial Cabling (Port Tester)" in topic 2.1.5</A> for an improved =
method of=20
finding cable or workstation problems. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>To use this MAP when the IBM Cabling System is used to connect the =

workstations to the 5494, perform the following actions: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Obtain copies of the Remote Workstation Setup Worksheet.=20
  <LI>Identify the failing workstations and the control unit port used =
for=20
  attachment. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>If the System Available indicator is off at =
all attached=20
workstations, all workstations are failing. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If the System Available indicator is on at any attached =
workstation, use=20
the following procedure to identify the failing workstations: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Make sure that power is turned on at all workstations and that all =

  workstations are connected to the cabling system. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Confirm that the SRC 0081, indicating that too many workstations =
are=20
  attached, does not appear at any workstation position on the screen. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Compare the Remote Workstation Setup Worksheets with the =
information you=20
  gathered when verifying workstation connections to identify all =
failing=20
  workstations and the 5494 ports used. See <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.11?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRTADS">"Displaying=20
  the</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.11?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRTADS">Status=20
  of 5494 Devices Attached to Twinaxial Ports" in topic 6.2.11</A> for=20
  instructions. A workstation is failing if: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>Its power is turned on=20
    <LI>It is connected to the cabling system=20
    <LI>It is not shown on the operator panel when verifying workstation =

    connections. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><B>Note:</B> If more than one 5494 port is =
used, determine which=20
  ports have failing workstations attached. If more than one port has =
failing=20
  workstations attached, perform the steps in this MAP, starting with <A =

  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=

unit port. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
   - Connect the IMD, at the 5494 location, to the cabling system wall
     connector if it is not connected.

ohmmeter
     to phase A and phase B at the twinaxial connector of the IMD.

cable-through=20
  installed. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

</P></PRE></LI></UL></LI></UL>The failure is probably in the cabling =

<P><A name=3DSTPx2>___ </A>|<B>030</B>| |___| (From step 006)=20
<P>The data path must be terminated at the last workstation by one of =
the=20
following methods:=20
<P><PRE></PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>The last workstation is connected to the wall connector by a=20
  direct-connect cable with a terminator assembly installed in socket 2 =
and the=20
  terminator switch (if present) set to the non-terminated position =
(position=20
  2). You can use this method only with workstations that have =
cable-through=20
  installed. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>The last workstation is connected to the wall connector by an IMD =
and the=20
  workstation terminator switch (if present) is set to the terminated =
position=20
  (position 1). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL>- Determine if the data path is terminated =
correctly.=20
<P><B>Is</B> <B>the</B> <B>data</B> <B>path</B> <B>terminated</B>=20
<B>correctly?</B> <A=20

8</A>.)=20

   <B>Is</B> <B>the</B> <B>resistance</B> <B>measurement</B> <B>less</B> =

   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=

    |    |__=20
    |   |<B>046</B>|
    |   |___|

    |   Report to the customer that the cable drop from the distribution
    |   panel to the 5494 is failing.

<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ107>    |</A>
    |__=20
   |<B>047</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   - Leave the ohmmeter connected and disconnect the center connector of =
each
     Y, one at a time, starting with the Y nearest the 5494.
<P>
   - Check for a resistance of more than 5000 ohms after you disconnect =
each
     Y until you find a resistance of more than 5000 ohms, or until you =
have
     disconnected the center connector of all of the Ys.

   <B>Is</B> <B>the</B> <B>resistance</B> <B>measurement</B> <B>more</B> =
<B>than</B> <B>5000</B> <B>ohms</B> <B>after</B> <B>disconnecting</B> =
<B>the</B>
   <B>center</B> <B>connector</B> <B>of</B> <B>any</B> <B>Y?</B>
   <A =

    |

distribution
    |     panel to the last workstation is failing.
    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ108>    |</A>
    |__=20
   |<B>049</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   The failing cable drop is the one you disconnected just before you
   obtained an ohmmeter reading of more than 5000 ohms.
<P>
   - Check the workstation twinaxial interface of the workstation that =
is
     attached to the failing cable drop (see <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM3003">"Workstation Twinaxial =
Interface</A>
     <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM3003">Check" in topic E.2.5</A>).
<P>
   <B>Does</B> <B>the</B> <B>workstation</B> <B>twinaxial</B> =
<B>interface</B> <B>check</B> <B>out</B> <B>as</B> <B>good?</B>
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.7?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ109"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |
    |    |__=20
    |   |<B>050</B>|
    |   |___|
    |
    |   - Repair the workstation or report the problem to the customer =
for
    |     workstations that do not have IBM on-site service.
    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ109>    |</A>
    |__=20
   |<B>051</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   Either the cable drop from the distribution panel or the twinaxial Y =
is
   failing.
<P>
   To determine which is failing, check the twinaxial Y (see <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.6?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM3005">"IBM Cabling</A>
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.6?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM3005">System Tests" in topic =
E.2.6</A>).
<P>
   If the twinaxial Y functions correctly, then the cable drop from the
   distribution panel to the wall connector is failing.
<P>
   - Report the problem to the customer.

<A name=3DHDRSRC152>
<H3>2.1.8 MAP 0800: Performing Twinaxial Cable =
Diagnostics</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
    ___=20
   |<B>001</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   - Disconnect all twinaxial cables from the distribution cables.
<P>
   - Run the diagnostics with no connections.  See <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running Extended</A>
     <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic =
4.2</A>.
<P>
   <B>Did</B> <B>the</B> <B>diagnostics</B> <B>fail?</B>
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.8?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ110"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |
    |    |__=20
    |   |<B>002</B>|
    |   |___|
    |
    |   <B>Is</B> <B>the</B> <B>wiring</B> <B>twinaxial</B> =
<B>wiring?</B>
    |   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.8?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ111"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |    |
    |    |    |__=20
    |    |   |<B>003</B>|
    |    |   |___|
    |    |
    |    |   The wiring must be TTP wiring.
    |    |
    |    |   - Connect the distribution cable to the multiplexer.
    |    |
    |    |   - Disconnect all devices.
    |    |
    |    |   - Connect a TTP workstation balun (P/N 96X6187) to one =
port.
    |    |
    |    |   - Connect a terminator to the other end of the balun.
    |    |
    |    |   - Run the diagnostics again.
    |    |
    |    |   - If the diagnostics fail, isolate the wiring problem =
between
    |    |     the distribution cable and the multiplexer and follow the
    |    |     instructions in <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM3001">"Cable Signal Quality =
Check."</A>
    |    |
    |    |   - Connect the devices back one at a time to the =
multiplexer.
    |    |
    |    |   - Run the diagnostics again.
    |    |
    |    |   <B>Did</B> <B>the</B> <B>diagnostics</B> <B>run</B> =
<B>successfully?</B>
    |    |   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.8?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ112"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |    |    |
    |    |    |    |__=20
    |    |    |   |<B>004</B>|
    |    |    |   |___|
    |    |    |
    |    |    |   - Isolate the wiring problem to the device.  Connect =
the
    |    |    |     balun to the TTP port and follow the instructions in
    |    |    |     <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM3001">"Cable Signal Quality =
Check."</A>
    |    |    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ112>    |    |    |</A>
    |    |    |__=20
    |    |   |<B>005</B>|
    |    |   |___|
    |    |
    |    |   - Connect multiple devices to the multiplexer.
    |    |
    |    |   - Run the diagnostics again.
    |    |
    |    |   <B>Did</B> <B>the</B> <B>diagnostics</B> <B>run</B> =
<B>successfully?</B>
    |    |   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.8?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ113"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |    |    |
    |    |    |    |__=20
    |    |    |   |<B>006</B>|
    |    |    |   |___|
    |    |    |
    |    |    |   - Replace the multiplexer with an IBM 5299.
    |    |    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ113>    |    |    |</A>
    |    |    |__=20
    |    |   |<B>007</B>|
    |    |   |___|
    |    |
    |    |   - There is no problem.  End of call.
    |    |  =
_________________________________________________________________
    |    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ111>    |    |</A>
    |    |__=20
    |   |<B>008</B>|
    |   |___|
    |
    |   - Connect the twinaxial devices one at a time.
    |
    |   - Check the C1 screen for error.
    |
    |   <B>Was</B> <B>there</B> <B>an</B> <B>error?</B>
    |   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/2.1.8?DT=3D19961016091447#STPSTPUNIQ114"><B>Yes</B></A>  <B>No</B>
    |    |    |
    |    |    |__=20
    |    |   |<B>009</B>|
    |    |   |___|
    |    |
    |    |   - The controller is OK.
    |    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ114>    |    |</A>
    |    |__=20
    |   |<B>010</B>|
    |   |___|
    |
    |   - Isolate the problem in the twinaxial connection by using the
    |     procedure in <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM3001">"Cable Signal Quality =
Check."</A>
    |  =
______________________________________________________________________
    |
<A name=3DSTPSTPUNIQ110>    |</A>
    |__=20
   |<B>011</B>|
   |___|
<P>
   - Replace the adapter at location <B>n</B>.

<HR>
<A name=3DHDRAPPD>
<H1>3.0 Topic 3. 5494 Message Codes and System Reference Codes =
(SRCs)</H1></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This topic contains the 5494 message codes and system =
reference codes=20
(SRCs). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Both message codes and SRCs are displayed on the 5494 operator =
panel LCD.=20
  The message codes are displayed on the left-hand side of the LCD and =
SRCs are=20
  displayed on the right-hand side of the LCD. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Message codes are not displayed on a workstation screen. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>SRCs are displayed on a workstation screen as 4 to 6 blinking =
characters=20
  that are located in the upper-left corner or the lower-left corner of =
the=20
  screen. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL></OL></LI></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>3.1 Message Codes</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>3.2 SRCs</A> </LI></UL>
<UL></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMESSAGE>
<H2>3.1 Message Codes</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><A name=3D"MSG 000">
<HR>
</A><B>000</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Cause:</B> Indicates that the Req key has been pressed. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Type the 3-digit request code, and then =
press=20
<B>Enter</B>. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDROPCMD">"Concurrent=20
Mode from the Operator Panel (Online)" in topic 6.2</A> for the 3-digit =
request=20
codes. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 001-01"><HR>
</A>
   <B>001-01</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> Performing POST. This test runs automatically =
each time=20
the 5494 power is turned on, or the 5494 is restarted. During this test, =
a=20
flashing asterisk (*) is displayed on the right-hand side of the LCD. =
This test=20
usually lasts about 1 minute and is followed by an IPL. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> None. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"MSG 001-02"><HR>
</A>
   <B>001-02</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> Loading extended diagnostics from the system =
diskette.=20
This takes about 30 seconds. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> None. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"MSG 002-01"><HR>
</A>
   <B>002-01</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> 5494 failure. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Look up the SRC displayed on the =
right-hand side=20
of the LCD. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">"SRCs"=20
in topic 3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 002-02"><HR>
</A>
   <B>002-02</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> An error has been detected during POST. This may =
be due=20
to the installation or removal of an adapter. Extended diagnostics can =
resolve=20
the problem or provide more information. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Record the SRC displayed on the =
right-hand side=20
of the LCD. Then, press <B>Enter</B> to run extended diagnostics. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 002-03"><HR>
</A>
   <B>002-03</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The 5494 operator panel cannot communicate with =
the 5494=20
planar. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Look up the SRC displayed on the =
right-hand side=20
of the LCD. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">"SRCs"=20
in topic 3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 002-04"><HR>
</A>
   <B>002-04</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> An error has occurred during POST, but the 5494 =
can=20
perform some functions. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Record this message code and the SRC =
displayed on=20
the right-hand side of the LCD, and then press <B>Enter</B> to continue. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 002-05"><HR>
</A>
   <B>002-05</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> An error has occurred. At this time, three keys =
are=20
active on the keypad and can be used to change the IPL mode. The default =
is 0,=20
which will load extended diagnostics. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> If the SRC displayed on this previous =
screen does=20
not identify the cause of the problem, press <B>Enter</B> to load =
extended=20
diagnostics. Then, select option 2 from the main menu to test all 5494 =
hardware.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| <B>Note:</B> At times, it is possible to operate the 5494 =
after a=20
POST <BR>| error. For example, if you experienced a 152 error code, you =
can=20
<BR>| select "1" on the 002-05 panel and press <B>Enter</B>. The 5494 =
will <BR>|=20
attempt to operate while the customer arranges to get the cabling <BR>|=20
repaired. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 002-06"><HR>
</A>
   <B>002-06</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> An unexpected critical error has occurred. This =
type of=20
error is usually intermittent. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Look up the SRC that is displayed on the=20
right-hand side of the LCD. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">"SRCs"=20
in topic 3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 002-07"><HR>
</A>
   <B>002-07</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> An error has occurred while loading from the =
diskette. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Enter</B> to try the operation =
again. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If the error reoccurs, insert the backup copy of the 5494 System =
Diskette,=20
and press <B>Enter</B> to try again. If the backup diskette loads =
successfully,=20
order a new system diskette to replace the damaged one. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To order a replacement diskette in the U.S., call 1-800-334-1089. =
To order=20
a replacement diskette outside the U.S., contact your local IBM branch =
office.=20
Have the 5494 serial number available. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<A name=3D"MSG 002-08"><HR>
</A>
   <B>002-08</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The installed system diskette can be damaged. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Insert the backup copy of the 5494 System =

Diskette and press <B>Enter</B> to try again. If the backup diskette =
loads=20
successfully, order a new system diskette to replace the damaged one. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To order a replacement diskette in the U.S., call 1-800-334-1089. =
To order=20
a replacement diskette outside the U.S., contact your local IBM branch =
office.=20
Have the 5494 serial number available. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<A name=3D"MSG 002-09"><HR>
</A>
   <B>002-09</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> An unexpected critical software error has =
occurred. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Look up the SRC reported by the customer. =
See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">"SRCs"=20
in</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">topic=20
3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 003-01"><HR>
</A>
   <B>003-01</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> A problem has been detected. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Insert the 5494 System Diskette and press =

<B>Enter</B> to run extended diagnostics. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 003-02"><HR>
</A>
   <B>003-02</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Insert the system diskette, pull the =
5494=20
keyboard out, and: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Type <B>0</B> and press <B>Enter</B> to run extended diagnostics.=20
  <LI>Type <B>1</B> and press <B>Enter</B> to begin normal operation.=20
  <LI>Type <B>2</B> and press <B>Enter</B> to start system =
configuration. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><A name=3D"MSG 003-03">
<HR>
</A><B>003-03</B>=20
<P><PRE></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The installed diskette is not recognized as =
the system=20
diskette. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Insert the system diskette and press =
<B>Enter</B>=20
to continue. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If the diskette is the system diskette, remove it and insert the =
backup=20
copy. Then, press <B>Enter</B> to continue. Remember to order a =
replacement=20
system diskette if you just installed your backup copy. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To order a replacement diskette within in the U.S., call =
1-800-334-1089.=20
To order a replacement diskette outside the U.S., contact your local IBM =
branch=20
office. Have the 5494 serial number available. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 003-04"><HR>
</A>
   <B>003-04</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The diskette in the diskette drive is not =
recognized as=20
the 5494 System Diskette. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Insert the 5494 System Diskette and press =

<B>Enter</B>. If the system diskette was in the drive during this error, =
remove=20
it, insert the backup copy, and: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Type <B>0</B> and press <B>Enter</B> to run extended diagnostics.=20
  <LI>Type <B>1</B> and press <B>Enter</B> to begin normal operation =
(default).=20
  <LI>Type <B>2</B> and press <B>Enter</B> to start system =
configuration. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><A name=3D"MSG 010-01">
<HR>
</A><B>010-01</B>=20
<P><PRE></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The 5494 setup information has been =
corrupted or no=20
longer matches the installed adapters. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Enter</B> to run the 5494 setup =
program.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 010-04"><HR>
</A>
   <B>010-04</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> Have any adapters been added, removed, or moved =
to a new=20
slot in the 5494? <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Type <B>1</B> and then press <B>Enter</B> for <B>yes</B>.=20
  <LI>Type <B>0</B> and then press <B>Enter</B> for <B>no</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><A name=3D"MSG 010-05">
<HR>
</A><B>010-05</B>=20
<P><PRE></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The 5494 contains a defective adapter. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Look up the SRC displayed on the =
right-hand side=20
of the LCD. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">"SRCs"=20
in topic 3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 010-06"><HR>
</A>
   <B>010-06</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The 5494 clock must be set because the date, the =
time,=20
or both are incorrect. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Enter</B> to continue. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 010-07"><HR>
</A>
   <B>010-07</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The 5494 clock is not working correctly. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> Errors recorded in the 5494 error log can be missing=20
time-stamp information. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Enter</B> to attempt to set the =
clock=20
for use until the 5494 power is turned off. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 010-08"><HR>
</A>
   <B>010-08</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The 5494 setup information has been corrupted or =
no=20
longer matches the installed adapters. This may be due to the =
installation or=20
removal of an adapter. It may also be caused by IPLing a new release of=20
microcode that supports an installed adapter that was not supported by =
the=20
previous level of microcode. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Enter</B> to run the 5494 setup =
program.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 010-09"><HR>
</A>
   <B>010-09</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Enter</B> to go to the =
extended=20
diagnostics main menu. Then, type <B>2</B> and press <B>Enter</B> to =
perform a=20
more detailed test of the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 020-01"><HR>
</A>
   <B>020-01</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> Extended diagnostics main menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> See the following table for a description =
of the=20
functions available on the extended diagnostics main menu. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To select from the following functions, press the <B>up</B> and=20
<B>down</B> <B>arrows</B> and <B>Enter</B>, or type the number and press =

<B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ115></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"16%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Number</B>    </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"83%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Function</B>                                                   =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"16%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 1        =20
          =20
          =20
           </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"83%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> View 5494 features            =
                            =20
                                                           =20
 Displays the installed adapters and amount of available   =20
 storage.                                                   =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"16%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 2        =20
          =20
          =20
          =20
           </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"83%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Test all 5494 hardware        =
                            =20
                                                           =20
 Runs extended diagnostics tests on all hardware.  If the  =20
 5494 contains an Ethernet adapter start the test from the =20
 CE main menu.  Press <B>Alt+PF1</B> to access the CE main menu.   =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"16%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 3        =20
          =20
          =20
           </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"83%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Set date and time             =
                            =20
                                                           =20
 Allows date and time on internal clock to be changed or   =20
 viewed.                                                    =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"16%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 4        =20
          =20
          =20
          =20
          =20
          =20
          =20
           </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"83%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Run setup                     =
                            =20
                                                           =20
 Initializes the internal descriptions of the installed    =20
 adapters.  If the 5494 contains a Token-Ring adapter, the =20
 Token-Ring data rate can be set or changed using the run  =20
 setup option.  Similarly, if the 5494 contains an Ethernet=20
 adapter, the media type can be selected or changed using  =20
 the run setup option.                                      =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Press <B>Esc</B> to exit extended diagnostics and restart the =
5494. Press=20
<B>Alt+PF1</B> to access the CE main menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 020-02"><HR>
</A>
   <B>020-02</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> All 5494 tests have completed. No errors were =
detected. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Enter</B> to restart the 5494. =
Press=20
<B>Esc</B> to return to the main menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<A name=3D"MSG 020-03"><HR>
</A>
   <B>020-03</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The system diskette installed in the diskette =
drive=20
could be damaged. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Look up the SRC that is displayed on the=20
right-hand side of the LCD. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">"SRCs"=20
in topic 3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 020-04"><HR>
</A>
   <B>020-04</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Insert the system diskette, and then =
press=20
<B>Enter</B> to continue. Press <B>Esc</B> to return to the extended =
diagnostics=20

<A name=3D"MSG 030-02"><HR>
</A>
   <B>030-02</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> Extended diagnostics test selection menu. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> The right-hand side of the LCD displays =
the=20
numbers 1 through 7 that correspond to the tests that can be selected. =
The=20
following numbers that correspond to the available tests are: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
          ________________________=20
         |           1 2 3 4 5 6 7|
         |___________ _ _ _ _ _ _ |
                     | | | | | | |
                     | | | | | | Ethernet adapter (if installed)
                     | | | | | Token-Ring adapter (if installed)
                     | | | | Host-twinaxial adapter
                     | | | Operator panel
                     | | Diskette drive
                     | Storage
                     Planar
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE></PRE>Active keys: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>1 to 7 toggle the test selection between on or off. Press the =
number to=20
  toggle between select and not select. The "-" indicates that the test =
is not=20
  selected to run. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B>Esc</B> to return to the previous menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B>Enter</B> to go to the test options menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><A name=3D"MSG 030-03">
<HR>
</A><B>030-03</B>=20

width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> To select from the following options, =
press the=20
<B>up</B> or <B>down</B> <B>arrow</B> key and <B>Enter</B>, or type the =
number=20
and press <B>Enter</B>. Enter one of the following options: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>1</B>=20
  <DD>Run all selected tests once (default).=20
  <DT><B>2</B>=20
  <DD>Run all selected tests until an error is detected.=20
  <DT><B>3</B>=20
  <DD>Run all selected tests until Req is pressed. Any detected errors =
will be=20
  logged in the 5494 error log. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>Active keys: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
<UL>

  <LI><B>Esc</B> to return to the CE main menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->

   <B>031-01</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The planar test is running. Do not turn the =
power=20

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Pressing Req will stop the test. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> During some portions of the planar test, =
communication with=20
the operator panel is not available. Therefore, you need to press Req =
several=20
times if you wish to stop the test. After you press Req, it can take =
several=20
seconds before the test terminates. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =

   <B>033-02</B>

</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Remove the system diskette and verify =

press=20
<B>Enter</B> to continue. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

   <B>033-03</B>

</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> Set the system diskette to write-protected. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Remove the system diskette and push the =
tab on=20
the diskette to the bottom of the slot so that the area above the tab is =
open.=20
Reinsert the diskette in the diskette drive and press <B>Enter</B> to =
continue. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 033-04"><HR>
</A>
   <B>033-04</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> Set the system diskette to <B>not</B> =
write-protected. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Remove the system diskette. Slide the=20
write-protect tab to the write position. (The tab is pushed to the top =
of the=20
slot and the opening in the slot is covered by the tab.) Reinsert the =
diskette=20
in the diskette drive and press <B>Enter</B> to continue. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 033-05"><HR>
</A>
   <B>033-05</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> An error has been detected while testing the =
system=20
diskette and the diskette drive. The problem can be a defective system =
diskette.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Replace the installed system diskette =
with a=20
backup copy of the system diskette, and then press <B>Enter</B> to run =
the=20
diskette test again. Remember to order a replacement diskette if the =
problem is=20
with the system diskette. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To order a replacement diskette in the U.S., call 1-800-334-1089. =
To order=20
a replacement diskette outside the U.S., contact your local IBM branch =
office.=20
Have the 5494 serial number available. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>If this error occurs after replacing the system diskette with the =
backup,=20
the diskette drive must be replaced. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>

  <LI>The LCD is blank.=20
  <LI>The LCD displays the numbers 0 through 9, and the letters A =
through F. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

width=3D132><!-- * -->

  <LI>Watch the LCD to determine if the sequence is correct.=20
  <LI>If the pattern displayed is correct, type <B>1</B>. If the pattern =
is=20
  <B>not</B> correct, type <B>0</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =

</A>
   <B>050-02</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> One or more entries in the 5494 error log do not =
have a=20
valid time stamp. Asterisks (*) will be substituted for an incorrect =
date and=20
time. The problem is probably due to an error that occurred with the =
5494 clock=20
when the error was logged. This problem does not prevent normal 5494 =
operation=20
except that no time or date will be recorded for this error log entry. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Enter</B> to display the error =
most=20
recently entered in the 5494 error log. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSPOT1">"How=20
to View the Error Log from Extended</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSPOT1">Diagnostics"=20
in topic 3.1.1</A> for instructions. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->

<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =

<HR>
<A name=3DMSG><A name=3DHDRSPOT1>
<H3>3.1.1 How to View the Error Log from Extended =
Diagnostics</H3></A></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To access the information stored in the 5494 error log, =
imagine that=20
the log is like a sheet of paper with one line used for each log entry. =
The most=20
recent entry is located at the bottom of the paper. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>At the top of the paper is an overlay with a clear window through =
which=20
you can view a small portion of each error log entry at a time. You can =
move the=20
overlay to the left or the right to view different information about a =
single=20
entry, or up and down to view different error log entries. Consider the=20
right-hand side of the LCD as the window. The left-hand side of the LCD =
contains=20
a message code that indicates what you are seeing through the window. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ118></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"100%" colSpan=3D5><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Table 7. Format =
of the 5494 Error Log                                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
               =20
 <B>Entry</B> <B>Number</B>    </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
               =20
 <B>Date</B>            </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
               =20
 <B>Time</B>            </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
               =20
 <B>SRC</B> <B>(Slot)</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"19%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Optional</B>      =20
 <B>Status</B> <B>Bytes</B>   </FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> (42/42)         =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> dd mmm          =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> hh:mm:ss        =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> cccccc(s)       =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"19%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 1 xx  2 xx ... =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> ...             =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> ...             =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> ...             =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> ...             =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"19%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> ... ...        =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 3/42            =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> dd mmm          =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> hh:mm:ss        =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> cccccc(s)       =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"19%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 1 xx  2 xx     =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 2/42            =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> dd mmm          =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> hh:mm:ss        =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> cccccc(s)       =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"19%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 1 xx  2 xx     =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 1/42            =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> dd mmm          =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> hh:mm:ss        =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"20%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <B><U>cccccc(s)</B></U>       =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"19%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 1 xx  2 xx     =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The message codes 051-xx indicate the fields of information =
displayed on=20
the 5494 LCD. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The LCD initially shows the SRC for the last entry in the 5494 =
error log=20
(<B><U>cccccc(s)</B></U> in the example). Use the arrow keys to move the =
window=20
to other entries and fields. A beep is sounded when the end of the error =
log has=20
been reached. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
   <B>Notes:</B>
<P>
</P></PRE>
<DD>1. For hardware SRCs E00xxx, look up the last 3 digits in<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">=20
"SRCs" in</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">topic=20
3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DD>2. Four-digit SRCs will display as 6-digit SRCs with 2 leading zeros =

(example 000052). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>In addition, you can use: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>PF1</B>=20
  <DD>To display momentarily the count field for the entry currently =
displayed.=20
  When the same error occurs more than once, a count is incremented =
instead of=20
  creating a new error log entry. The date and time of the error log =
entry is=20
  that of the last occurrence. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>PF2</B>=20
  <DD>To find the first entry for the current date being displayed. If =
the first=20
  entry for the current date is already being displayed, the first entry =
for the=20
  previous date will be displayed. In either case the date field will be =

  displayed. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><B>Alt+4</B>=20
  <DD>To enable display of additional status bytes associated with each =
error=20
  log entry. This information can be required by level 1 and 2 support=20
  personnel. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE><A name=3D"MSG 051-xx">
<HR>
</A><B>051-xx</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Cause:</B> The message codes 051-01 through 051-05 indicate =
which of=20
several fields of the 5494 error log is being displayed on the =
right-hand side=20
of the LCD. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL><B>Message</B> <B>Displays</B>=20
  <DT>051-01=20
  <DD>The error count=20
  <DT>051-02=20
  <DD>The date=20
  <DT>051-03=20
  <DD>The time=20
  <DT>051-04=20
  <DD>The SRC (see notes)=20
  <DT>051-05=20
  <DD>Optional status byte information <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Use the <B>left</B> =
and <B>right</B>=20
<B>arrows</B> to move between fields. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
         <B>Notes:</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><A name=3DLISrdw1>
<DD>1. For hardware SRCs E00xxx, look up the last 3 digits in<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">=20
"SRCs" in</A></A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">topic=20
3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DLISrdw2></PRE>
<DD>2. Four-digit SRCs will display as 6-digit SRCs with 2 leading</A> =
zeros=20
(for example, 000052). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
<A name=3D"MSG 052-01"><HR>
</A>
   <B>052-01</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The 5494 error log does not contain any entries. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Esc</B> to return to the main =
menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 052-02"><HR>
</A>
   <B>052-02</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The 5494 error log contents have been corrupted. =
A test=20
of the log has been run and no hardware failure was detected. The reason =
for the=20
problem cannot be detected. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The log has been reinitialized and now contains no errors. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Esc</B> to return to the main =
menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 052-03"><HR>
</A>
   <B>052-03</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The storage used to store the 5494 error log is=20
defective. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Look up the SRC displayed on the =
right-hand side=20
of the LCD. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">"SRCs"=20
in topic 3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> You can continue to use the 5494, but error logging=20
information can be unreliable. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 060-01"><HR>
</A>
   <B>060-01</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The 2 numbers displayed on the right-hand side =
of the=20
LCD indicate the number of storage corrections made to the SIMMs =
installed in=20
the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>If you have just replaced a SIMM in the 5494, change the counters =
to zero=20
  by pressing <B>Clear</B>. Then, press <B>Esc</B> to return to the main =
menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>If you have not just replaced a SIMM, press <B>Esc</B> to return =
to the=20
  main menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><A name=3D"MSG 099-01">
<HR>
</A><B>099-01</B>=20
<P><PRE></PRE><B>Cause:</B> A system reset request is in progress. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Complete the reset request sequence or =
press=20
<B>Esc</B> to cancel the request. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 099-02"><HR>
</A>
   <B>099-02</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> The system reset request is complete. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> This restarts the 5494 and interrupts all =
current=20
activity. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> Notify the users connected to this 5494 that =
their=20
sessions will be interrupted. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Press <B>Enter</B> to continue. Press <B>Esc</B> to cancel the =
request. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 099-03"><HR>
</A>
   <B>099-03</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> A reset is in progress. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> None. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"MSG 199"><HR>
</A>
   <B>199</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> A hardware failure has occurred. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Look up the SRC displayed on the =
right-hand side=20
of the LCD and perform the indicated action. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSRC">"SRCs"=20
in topic 3.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 200"><HR>
</A>
   <B>200</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> Request code for displaying 5494 status =
information. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSTUS">"Displaying=20
5494 Online Status Information" in</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSTUS">topic=20
6.2.1</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 201 through 220"><HR>
</A>
   <B>201</B> <B>through</B> <B>220</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> Codes displayed as a result of a request for=20
information. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Esc</B> to clear the information =
from=20
the LCD. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>While data with these message codes is displayed, normal errors =
that occur=20
will not display. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 230"><HR>
</A>

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>CE</B> <B>Action:</B> Press <B>Enter</B> to activate or =
<B>ESC</B> to=20
clear. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

</P></PRE><B>Cause:</B> A failure in the operational code has been =
