                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                =20
                 </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <B>1.</B>  Press <B>5</B> and =
<B>Enter</B>.                              =20
                                                     =20
 <B>2.</B>  Message code 030-02 is displayed on the         =20
     left-hand side of the LCD and 12345 is displayed=20
     on the right-hand side.  If the 5494 contains a =20
     Token-Ring adapter, 123456 is displayed; if the =20
     5494 contains an Ethernet adapter, 12345 7 is   =20
     displayed.                                      =20
                                                     =20
     <B>Note:</B>  The Token-Ring adapter and Ethernet      =20
     adapter cannot be installed together in a 5494. =20
     See <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMESSAGE">"Message Codes" in topic 3.1</A> =
to determine   =20
     the next action.                                =20
                                                     =20
 <B>3.</B>  If no problem is found, message code 030-04 will=20
     be displayed.  Press <B>Esc</B> to return to the CE    =20
     main menu, and then see "View the 5494 Error    =20
     Log" in topic <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#SPTVIEWEL">4.2</A> and display the 5494 error =
   =20
     log.                                            =20
                                                     =20
     If any other message code is displayed, see     =20
     <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMESSAGE">"Message Codes" in topic 3.1</A> =
to determine the   =20
     meaning of message codes displayed while testing=20
     the 5494 hardware.  Press <B>Esc</B> to exit this      =20
     information and return to the CE main menu.      =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"24%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <B>View</B> <B>the</B> =
<B>5494</B>  =20

<A name=3DHDRVER>
<H2>4.3 Verifying 5494 Operation</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To verify 5494 operation: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>First, see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRNPR">"5494=20
  Normal Power-On Sequence" in topic 4.3.1 </A>to determine if the =
internal=20
  hardware of the 5494 is operating correctly. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Then, after verifying normal power-on, refer to the=20
  <CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>5494</CITE> <CITE>Remote</CITE> =
<CITE>Control</CITE>=20
  <CITE>Unit</CITE> <CITE>User's</CITE> <CITE>Guide</CITE> to establish =
the link=20
  to the AS/400 system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Finally, see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRVWC">"Verifying=20
  Workstation Connection" in topic 4.3.2</A> to verify that all =
connected and=20
  powered-on workstations are communicating with the AS/400 system. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>4.3.1 5494 Normal Power-On Sequence</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>4.3.2 Verifying Workstation Connection</A>=20
  <OL></OL></LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRNPR>
<H3>4.3.1 5494 Normal Power-On Sequence</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>During the power-on sequence, the code tests all major parts =
of the=20
5494 and loads the operational code from the system diskette. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The following information describes how the 5494 should function =
during=20
normal power-on. This description assumes that the 5494 configuration =
was=20
checked and is correct. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRVJC">"Verifying=20
the 5494 Configuration" in</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRVJC">topic=20
4.4</A>, if necessary. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Make sure that the 5494 system diskette is in the diskette =
drive. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Turn the 5494 power <B>OFF</B> (<B>0</B>) and then back =
<B>ON</B>=20
  (<B>|</B>). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Verify the following: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <OL type=3Da>
    <LI><B></B>All LEDs come on for 1 second and go off for 1 second, =
and then=20
    only the Test Mode LED comes on. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>The message code 001-01 is displayed on the left-hand =
side of the=20
    LCD, indicating that the 5494 is performing a test of all its =
internal=20
    components. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>During this test, a flashing asterisk is displayed on the =
right-hand=20
    side of the LCD. This testing of internal components normally takes =
about 1=20
    minute, and is followed by an IPL of the 5494 operational code that =
is on=20
    the system diskette. The IPL takes about 20 seconds. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If the system diskette is not in the diskette drive, =
the=20
    message code 003-02, indicating that the diskette must be in the =
diskette=20
    drive, will be displayed. If this message is displayed, insert the =
system=20
    diskette and press <B>Enter</B> to continue. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>The current date and time as determined by the internal =
clock are=20
    displayed next. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>The Test Mode LED goes off. The operational code =
initializes. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>The Ready LED is turned on indicating that initialization =
is=20
    complete and the 5494 is ready to establish communication with the =
AS/400=20
    system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>On all 5250 workstations, a System Available indicator =
appears.=20
    The cursor will move from the upper right-hand side of the screen to =
the=20
    upper left-hand side. Each NWS will be in free-key mode (see <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRFREEKEY">"Free-Key=20
    Mode" in topic B.2</A> for details). </LI></OL></LI></OL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRVWC>
<H3>4.3.2 Verifying Workstation Connection</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This section describes how to determine if your workstation is =

attached correctly through a 5250 or LAN connection. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3.2.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>4.3.2.1 Before You Begin Verification</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3.2.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>4.3.2.2 5250 Connection</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3.2.3?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>4.3.2.3 LAN (Token-Ring or Ethernet) Connection</A> =
</LI></UL>
<HR>

<H4>4.3.2.1 Before You Begin Verification</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Before you begin verification, go to the operator panel and =
perform=20
the following steps: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Make sure that the 5494 power push button is set to =
<B>ON</B> and=20
  the Ready LED is lit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Make sure that all workstations for which you want to =
verify the=20
  connection are on. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>If you want to verify one or more PWSs, go to step <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3.2.1?DT=3D19961016091447#LISNX4">4</A>.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If not, see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.3.2.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCON52">"5250=20
  Connection" in topic 4.3.2.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3DLISnx4></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Establish a link to your AS/400 system. For instructions on =

  link</A> establishment, see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRHTS">"How=20
  to Start Communication with the AS/400 System"</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRHTS">in=20
  topic B.1.1</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>For PWSs, have the customer attempt to communicate with the =
AS/400=20
  system. Wait for an appropriate message that the PWS is attempting=20
  communications such as a logon message or "WAITING FOR ADAPTER TO =
OPEN"=20
  message. </LI></OL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRCON52>
<H4>4.3.2.2 5250 Connection</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To verify a workstation connection using the 5250 connection, =
do the=20
following: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Press <B>Req</B>, type <B>210</B> on the keypad, and then =
press=20
  <B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>One LCD panel is displayed for each workstation that is =
communicating=20
  with the 5494 using the 5250 connection. The LCD displays the port and =
station=20
  address in the following format: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ120></A></PRE>
  <TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"100%"><PRE><FONT =
size=3D2> <TT>210-id=BAwwww</TT>  <TT>mmm</TT>    =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>where: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT><B>id</B>=20
    <DD>is the port and station address. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <DT><B>wwww</B>=20
    <DD>is the device type. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <DT><B>mmm</B>=20
    <DD>is the model. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>An example is: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ121></A></PRE>
  <TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"100%"><PRE><FONT =
size=3D2> <TT>210-23=BA3477</TT>  <TT>0FC</TT>    =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This panel shows that this workstation is on port 2, station 3, =
and is a=20
  3477 Model 0FC. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> The device type is obtained from the workstation or=20
  printer. Printers return a group designation and the device type =
displayed may=20
  not be the actual printer device type but rather another printer =
device type=20
  that has the same capabilities. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Use the <B>down</B> <B>arrow</B> to scroll to a preceding =
entry and=20
  the <B>up</B> <B>arrow</B> to scroll to a following entry. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If <TT>210=BA************</TT> is displayed, you have =
reached=20
  the end of the list of 5250 workstations or, if it is the only panel, =
no 5250=20
  workstations are in contact with the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To refresh the LCD display with current information, press =
<B>Req</B>,=20
  type <B>210</B>, and then press <B>Enter</B>. When you finish viewing =
the LCD=20
  display, press <B>Esc</B> to clear the panel. Error messages are not =
displayed=20
  while requested information is on the LCD panel. </LI></OL>
<HR>

<H4>4.3.2.3 LAN (Token-Ring or Ethernet) Connection</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To verify a workstation connection using the LAN connection, =
do the=20
following: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Press <B>Req</B>, type <B>211</B>, and then press =
<B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>One LCD panel is displayed for each workstation that is =
communicating=20
  with the 5494 using the LAN connection. The LCD displays the LAN =
address of=20
  the workstation in the following format: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ122></A></PRE>
  <TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"100%"><PRE><FONT =
size=3D2> <TT>211=BAaaaaaaaaaaaa</TT>    =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>where <I>aaaaaaaaaaaa</I> is the LAN address. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If <TT>211=BA************</TT> is displayed, you have =
reached=20
  the end of the list of LAN workstations or, if it is the only panel, =
no LAN=20
  workstations are in contact with the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Use the <B>down</B> <B>arrow</B> to scroll to a preceding =
entry and=20
  the <B>up</B> <B>arrow</B> to scroll to a following entry. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To refresh the LCD display with current information, press =
<B>Req</B>,=20
  type <B>211</B>, and then press <B>Enter</B>. When you finish viewing =
the LCD=20
  display, press <B>Esc</B> to clear the LCD. Error messages are not =
displayed=20
  while requested information is on the LCD. </LI></OL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRVJC>
<H2>4.4 Verifying the 5494 Configuration</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To verify the 5494 configuration, perform the following steps: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Get a copy of the customer's 5494 configuration worksheets. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>See <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM2013">Topic=20
  6, "Concurrent Mode from the Operator Panel or Utility</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM2013">Program,"</A>=20
  and compare the 5494 configuration information to the configuration=20
  worksheets. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>If you find differences in the configuration and the =
configuration=20
  worksheets, have the customer determine which is correct. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>If the configuration is incorrect, refer to the =
<CITE>IBM</CITE>=20
  <CITE>5494</CITE> <CITE>Remote</CITE> <CITE>Control</CITE> =
<CITE>Unit</CITE>=20
  <CITE>User's</CITE> <CITE>Guide</CITE> and work with the customer to =
correct=20
  the configuration. </LI></OL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMIM0231>
<H2>4.5 Testing the DC Power Supply Voltage =
Level</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Use the following procedure to check voltage levels on the =
power=20
supply: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A name=3DDGR><STRONG>DANGER</STRONG></A> <BR><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D80><!-- * -->
    =
________________________________________________________________________ =

   | <STRONG>Line</STRONG> <STRONG>voltage</STRONG> <STRONG>is</STRONG> =
<STRONG>always</STRONG> <STRONG>present</STRONG> <STRONG>at</STRONG> =
<STRONG>the</STRONG> <STRONG>power</STRONG> <STRONG>supply</STRONG> =
<STRONG>when</STRONG> <STRONG>the</STRONG> <STRONG>ac</STRONG> =
<STRONG>line</STRONG>    |
   | <STRONG>voltage</STRONG> <STRONG>LED</STRONG> <STRONG>is</STRONG> =
<STRONG>on.</STRONG>  <STRONG>Disconnect</STRONG> <STRONG>the</STRONG> =
<STRONG>power</STRONG> <STRONG>cord</STRONG> <STRONG>from</STRONG> =
<STRONG>the</STRONG> <STRONG>customer's</STRONG> <STRONG>ac</STRONG>   |
   | <STRONG>supply</STRONG> <STRONG>before</STRONG> =
<STRONG>disassembling</STRONG> <STRONG>the</STRONG> =
<STRONG>5494</STRONG> <STRONG>power</STRONG> <STRONG>supply.</STRONG>    =
                 |
   =
|________________________________________________________________________=
|
<P>
</P></PRE><A name=3DDGR><STRONG>DANGER</STRONG></A> <BR><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D80><!-- * -->
    =
________________________________________________________________________ =

   | <STRONG>Do</STRONG> <STRONG>not</STRONG> <STRONG>connect</STRONG> =
<STRONG>ac</STRONG> <STRONG>voltage</STRONG> <STRONG>to</STRONG> =
<STRONG>the</STRONG> <STRONG>power</STRONG> <STRONG>supply</STRONG> =
<STRONG>when</STRONG> <STRONG>it</STRONG> <STRONG>is</STRONG> =
<STRONG>removed</STRONG> <STRONG>from</STRONG>  |
   | <STRONG>the</STRONG> <STRONG>control</STRONG> =
<STRONG>unit.</STRONG>  <STRONG>Severe</STRONG> =
<STRONG>electrical</STRONG> <STRONG>shock</STRONG> =
<STRONG>could</STRONG> <STRONG>result.</STRONG>  <STRONG>Safe</STRONG>   =
      |
   | <STRONG>grounding</STRONG> <STRONG>of</STRONG> <STRONG>the</STRONG> =
<STRONG>power</STRONG> <STRONG>supply</STRONG> <STRONG>is</STRONG> =
<STRONG>ensured</STRONG> <STRONG>only</STRONG> <STRONG>when</STRONG> =
<STRONG>the</STRONG> <STRONG>power</STRONG> <STRONG>supply</STRONG> =
<STRONG>is</STRONG> |
   | <STRONG>securely</STRONG> <STRONG>fastened</STRONG> =
<STRONG>in</STRONG> <STRONG>the</STRONG> <STRONG>control</STRONG> =
<STRONG>unit.</STRONG>                                 |
   =
|________________________________________________________________________=
|
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Note:</B> For translations of these safety notices, see <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/A.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPA">Appendix=20
A, "Safety</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/A.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPA">Notices."</A>=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> Remove the diskette from the 5494 before doing =
this=20
procedure. Reinsert the diskette after the voltage problem is corrected. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Turn the 5494 power <B>OFF</B> (<B>0</B>) and remove the =
cover. See=20
  <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">"Cover=20
  Removal</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">and=20
  Replacement" in topic 5.7.1</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Set the multimeter for resistance measurements and measure =
from the=20
  planar ground to the chassis ground. If this resistance is 0.1 ohm or =
less,=20
  make sure that the planar grounding screws are secure. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Reconnect the power cord. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Turn the 5494 power <B>ON</B> (<B>|</B>) and wait about 5 =
minutes=20
  before you do the next step. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Set the multimeter for dc voltage measurements and probe =
the power=20
  test points on the planar indicated in <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.5?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLDCTAB">Table=20
  10</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>You may need to pull the connector slightly away from the pins so =
that=20
  you can access the test points. The power good signal has an internal =
pull-up=20
  resistor. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLDCTAB></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"100%" colSpan=3D3><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Table 10. DC =

  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"19%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =

    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"17%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =

    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"62%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =

<A name=3DHDRMIM0232>
<H2>4.6 Testing the DC Power Supply Ripple Level</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The peak-to-peak output ripple should be less than 4% of the=20
respective dc voltages when measured with an oscilloscope. Use the =
values in the=20
"Volts Peak-to-Peak" column of <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.6?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLMIT22">Table=20
11</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>When an oscilloscope is not available, you can observe the ripple =
voltage=20
by using the 8060 A/AA digital multimeter as follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Set the ac/dc switch to ac. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Set the range switch to 200 mv. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Set the correct switch combination for V/db measurements. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Connect one of the meter leads to the chassis ground and =
the other=20
  lead to the appropriate planar test point. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Read the measured value on the multimeter. If the OL symbol =
appears=20
  on the multimeter display, the input is higher than the range =
selected. Select=20
  a higher range for measurement. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Use the values in the "Volts RMS" column of <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.6?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLMIT22">Table=20
  11</A> to determine if you have an acceptable value. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLMIT22></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"100%" colSpan=3D3><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Table 11. Ripple =
Level Check                                                           =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"33%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
                           =20
 <B>Power</B> <B>Supply</B> <B>Voltage</B>        </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"33%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Acceptable</B> <B>Ripple</B> <B>Level</B>    =20
 <B>(Volts</B> <B>Peak-to-Peak)</B>        </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"32%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Acceptable</B> <B>Ripple</B> <B>Level</B>   =20
 <B>(Volts</B> <B>RMS)</B>                </FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"33%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> + 12 Vdc                    =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"33%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Less than 80 mv             =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"32%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Less than 28 mv            =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"33%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> +  5 Vdc                    =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"33%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Less than 50 mv             =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"32%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Less than 18 mv            =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"33%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> - 12 Vdc                    =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"33%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Less than 100 mv            =
</FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"32%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Less than 35 mv            =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>

<HR>

<H2>5.1 Information About Removal and Replacement</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This section tells you how to remove and replace field =
replaceable=20
units (FRUs) in the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A name=3DDGR><STRONG>DANGER</STRONG></A> <BR><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D80><!-- * -->
    =
________________________________________________________________________ =

   | <STRONG>Never</STRONG> <STRONG>work</STRONG> <STRONG>on</STRONG> =
<STRONG>equipment,</STRONG> <STRONG>or</STRONG> <STRONG>connect</STRONG> =
<STRONG>or</STRONG> <STRONG>disconnect</STRONG> <STRONG>signal</STRONG> =
<STRONG>cables</STRONG> <STRONG>during</STRONG> |
   | <STRONG>periods</STRONG> <STRONG>of</STRONG> =
<STRONG>lightning</STRONG> <STRONG>activity.</STRONG>                    =
                     |
   =
|________________________________________________________________________=
|
<P>
<A name=3DCAU>   <B>CAUTION:</B></A>
<BR>
   <B>Before</B> <B>removing</B> <B>any</B> <B>FRU,</B> <B>set</B> =
<B>the</B> <B>power</B> <B>OFF</B> <B>at</B> <B>the</B> <B>control</B> =
<B>unit,</B> <B>unplug</B> <B>all</B>
   <B>power</B> <B>cords</B> <B>from</B> <B>electrical</B> =
<B>outlets,</B> <B>and</B> <B>disconnect</B> <B>any</B> =
<B>interconnecting</B>
   <B>cables.</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Note:</B> For translations of this safety notice, see <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/A.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPA">Appendix=20
A, "Safety</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/A.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPA">Notices."</A>=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Remove the 5494 system diskette from the diskette drive before =
beginning=20
any removal and replacement procedures. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>The arrows in the removal and replacement procedures show the =
direction of=20
movement to remove a FRU, turn a screw, or to press a tab to release the =
FRU.=20
The arrows are marked in numeric order to show the correct sequence of =
removal. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>When other FRUs must be removed prior to removing the failing FRU, =
they=20
are listed at the beginning of the procedure. Go to the removal =
procedure for=20
each FRU listed, remove the FRU, and then continue with the removal of =
the=20
failing FRU. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To replace a FRU, reverse the removal procedure and follow any =
notes that=20
pertain to replacement. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRLOC">"Locations"=20
in topic 5.2</A> for internal cable connection and arrangement =
information. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The planar, adapters, SIMM, and host-twinaxial adapter are =
sensitive to,=20
and can be damaged by, electrostatic discharge. Establish personal =
grounding by=20
touching a ground point with one hand before touching these units. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> An electrostatic discharge (ESD) kit (IBM P/N =
6428316)=20
and wrist strap (IBM P/N 6405959) must be used to establish personal =
grounding=20
whenever you handle electrostatic discharge-sensitive FRUs.=20
<HR>

<H3>5.2.5 Planar</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3DHDRRRCO>
<H3>5.7.1 Cover Removal and Replacement</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><A name=3DCAU><B>CAUTION:</B></A> <BR><B>Before</B> =
<B>removing</B>=20
<B>any</B> <B>FRU,</B> <B>switch</B> <B>the</B> <B>power</B> <B>OFF</B>=20
<B>at</B> <B>the</B> <B>control</B> <B>unit,</B> <B>unplug</B> =
<B>all</B>=20
<B>power</B> <B>cords</B> <B>from</B> <B>electrical</B> <B>outlets,</B>=20
<B>and</B> <B>disconnect</B> <B>any</B> <B>interconnecting</B> =
<B>cables.</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> Notice the adapters to which the cables are =
connected. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> Before removing the cover, remove the diskette =
from the=20
diskette drive. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Make sure that the keypad on the front of the 5494 is =
inside the=20
  5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Loosen the 2 thumbscrews on the back panel. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the cover by sliding it forward approximately 50 mm =
(2 in.),=20
  and then lifting it. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Reverse the procedure to replace the cover. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>After you have completed the removal and replacement =
procedures, go=20
  to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
  Extended Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A> and test all 5494 =
hardware. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-35?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 35" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P35.gif"></A>         =20
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRRREC>
<H3>5.7.2 Twinaxial Adapter and Twinaxial Expansion Adapter Removal and=20
Replacement</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><B>Attention:</B> The Twinaxial adapter and the Twinaxial =
Expansion=20
Adapter are sensitive to electrostatic discharge. Be sure to use an=20
electrostatic discharge (ESD) kit and wrist strap while performing this=20
procedure. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> The Twinaxial Adapter located in the lower slot =
number=20
supports ports 0--3. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the cover (see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">"Cover=20
  Removal and Replacement" in topic 5.7.1</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Loosen the external thumbscrew. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Hold the 2 blue supports to lift the host-twinaxial adapter =
up and=20
  out of the adapter slot. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Reverse the procedure to replace the host-twinaxial =
adapter. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>When a Twinaxial Expansion Adapter is installed, repeat =
this=20
  procedure. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>After you have completed the removal and replacement =
procedures, go=20
  to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
  Extended Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A> and test all 5494 =
hardware. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-36?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 36" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P36.gif"></A>         =20
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRRRTR>
<H3>5.7.3 Token-Ring Adapter Removal and =
Replacement</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><B>Attention:</B> The Token-Ring adapter is sensitive to =
electrostatic=20
discharge. Be sure to use an ESD kit and wrist strap while performing =
this=20
procedure. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the cover (see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">"Cover=20
  Removal and Replacement" in topic 5.7.1</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Loosen the external thumbscrew. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Hold the 2 blue supports to lift the Token-Ring adapter up =
and out=20
  of the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Reverse the procedure to replace the Token-Ring adapter. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>After you have completed the removal and replacement =
procedures, go=20
  to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
  Extended Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A> and test all 5494 =
hardware. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-37?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 37" =

91447.P37.gif"></A>         =20
</PRE>

<A name=3DHDRRRSS>
<H3>5.7.5 Power Push Button and Speaker Assembly Removal and=20
Replacement</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the cover (see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">"Cover=20
  Removal and Replacement" in topic 5.7.1</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Disconnect the speaker cable from the planar (see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">"Internal=20
  Cables" in</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">topic=20
  5.2.4</A>). Notice the slot through which the cable connects to the =
planar. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>While holding the assembly, remove the screw. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Lift the assembly out of the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Reverse the procedure to replace the power push button and =
speaker=20
  assembly. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>After you have completed the removal and replacement =
procedures, go=20
  to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
  Extended Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A> and test all 5494 =
hardware. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=

</PRE>

<A name=3DHDRRRDD>
<H3>5.7.6 Diskette Drive Removal and Replacement</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><B>Note:</B> You must install only diskette drives designed =
for this=20
system. Use of diskette drives not designed for this system could cause=20
intermittent problems. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE>
<P>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the cover (see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">"Cover=20
  Removal and Replacement" in topic 5.7.1</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Disconnect the diskette drive cable from the planar (see <A =

  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">"Internal</A>=20
  <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">Cables"=20
  in topic 5.2.4</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the diskette drive by lifting up and holding the =
release=20
  latch while sliding the diskette drive out. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Reverse the procedure to replace the diskette drive. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>After you have completed the removal and replacement =
procedures, go=20
  to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
  Extended Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A> and test all 5494 =
hardware. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-40?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 40" =

<A name=3DHDRRRPK>
<H3>5.7.7 Operator Panel Removal and Replacement</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the cover (see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">"Cover=20
  Removal and Replacement" in topic 5.7.1</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Disconnect the cable attached to the planar (see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">"Internal=20
  Cables" in</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">topic=20
  5.2.4</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DLISftp></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Two clips must be disengaged to remove the operator panel. =
Place=20
  the</A> blade of a screwdriver under the panel to disengage the left =
clip and=20
  pry up gently; at the same time, with your thumb under the panel, pull =
the=20
  left side forward slightly to keep the clip from re-engaging. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Repeat step <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.7?DT=3D19961016091447#LISFTP">3=20
  </A>for the right clip, and push the panel out through the front of =
the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Reverse the procedure to replace the operator panel. Be =
sure that=20
  the replacement operator panel includes the correct keypad overlay. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>After you have completed the removal and replacement =
procedures, go=20
  to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
  Extended Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A> and test all 5494 =
hardware. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-41?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 41" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P41.gif"></A>         =20

</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the cover (see <A=20
  =

the SIMM. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| <B></B>Lift the failing SIMM out of the slot. <PRE></PRE><PRE =

width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| <B>Attention:</B> If there is only one SIMM installed, be =
sure to=20
  install the <BR>| replacement SIMM in <B>slot</B> <B>1</B>. =

</P></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>After you have completed the removal and replacement =

  to <A=20
  =

hardware. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->

<A name=3DHDRRRPS>
<H3>5.7.9 Power Supply Removal and Replacement</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the cover (see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">"Cover=20
  Removal and Replacement" in topic 5.7.1</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the 3 screws from the power supply. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Disconnect the 2 cables from the planar board (see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">"Internal=20
  Cables"</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">in=20
  topic 5.2.4</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Release the back of the power supply from the opening for =
the fan=20
  on the back of the 5494 and lift the power supply. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Rotate the power supply up 90=B1 to release the support =
bracket. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> Hold the power supply carefully to avoid damage =
to the=20
  planar. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Reverse the procedure to replace the power supply. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
       <B>Notes:</B>
<P>
</P></PRE>
  <LI>When reinstalling the power supply, replace and partially tighten =
each=20
  screw. When you have replaced all 3 screws, tighten them fully. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Support brackets are not provided with replacement power supplies. =
Use the=20
  support bracket from the defective power supply when installing the=20
  replacement. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>After you have completed the removal and replacement =
procedures, go=20
  to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
  Extended Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A> and test all 5494 =
hardware. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-43?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 43" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P43.gif"></A>         =20

<A name=3DHDRRRPC>
<H3>5.7.10 Planar Removal and Replacement</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><B>Note:</B> When a new planar is installed, you must run the =
extended=20
diagnostics to correct or initialize conditions that occur the first =
time the=20
planar receives power. Step <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.10?DT=3D19961016091447#LISSTP8">7a=20
</A>in this procedure explains how to set up the planar for correct =
operation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the following components in the order listed: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL type=3Da>
    <LI><B></B>Cover (see <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRCO">"Cover=20
    Removal and Replacement" in topic 5.7.1</A>) <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>Twinaxial adapter, and Twinaxial Expansion adapter if =
applicable=20
    (see <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRREC">"Twinaxial=20
    Adapter and Twinaxial Expansion Adapter Removal</A> <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRREC">and=20
    Replacement" in topic 5.7.2</A>) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>Token-Ring adapter, if applicable (see <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRTR">"Token-Ring=20
    Adapter Removal</A> <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRTR">and=20
    Replacement" in topic 5.7.3</A>) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>Ethernet adapter, if applicable (see <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRENETRR">"Ethernet=20
    Adapter Removal and</A> <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRENETRR">Replacement"=20
    in topic 5.7.4</A>) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>SIMM (see <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.8?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRSM">"SIMM=20
    Removal and Replacement" in topic 5.7.8</A>) <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>Power supply (see <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.9?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRPS">"Power=20
    Supply Removal and Replacement" in</A> <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.7.9?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRRPS">topic=20
    5.7.9</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Disconnect the 3 internal cables from the planar. See <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">"Internal</A>=20
  <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/5.2.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRINTCAB">Cables"=20
  in topic 5.2.4</A> to locate the cables. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the 6 screws from the planar. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Check that the adapter slot thumbscrews are loosened so =
that the=20
  planar will not hit them. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Push the planar toward the front of the 5494, tilt the back =
edge=20
  up, and then lift the planar out. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Reverse the procedure to replace the planar. Be sure to =
remove the=20
  SIMM from the defective planar and install it in <B>slot</B> <B>1</B> =
on the=20
  replacement. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> To prevent bending the planar, first replace and =
partially=20
  tighten each screw. When you have replaced all 6 screws, tighten them =
fully. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>After you have completed the removal and replacement =
procedures,=20
  see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
  Extended Diagnostics (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> When using a planar from another 5494, you must copy=20
  configuration information from the system diskette onto the planar. =
See <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.23?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCPYCNFG">"Copying=20
  5494 Configuration or Filter Files from Diskette" in</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.23?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCPYCNFG">topic=20
  6.2.23</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Complete the following steps: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <OL type=3Da><A name=3DLISstp8>
    <LI><B></B>Run setup.</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>When a new planar is installed and powered on for the first time, =
SRC=20
    120 is usually displayed. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <UL>
      <LI>If SRC 120 is displayed: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
      <OL type=3D1>
        <LI>The message codes displayed on the left-hand side of the LCD =
direct=20
        you to load the extended diagnostics. Setup automatically is =
run. You=20
        are asked if any adapters have been added, removed, or moved to =
a=20
        different slot in the 5494. Answer <B>YES</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If a Token-Ring adapter is installed, you are asked to select the=20
        data rate that the customer is using for the ring; if an =
Ethernet=20
        adapter is installed, you are asked to select the media type =
that the=20
        customer is using for the LAN. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
        <LI>When setup has completed, a message code on the LCD is =
displayed to=20
        indicate that you are at the extended diagnostics main menu. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>From the main menu, select option <B>3</B> to set the date and=20
        time. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>
      <LI>If SRC 120 is not displayed: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
      <OL type=3D1>
        <LI>Load the extended diagnostics. See <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">"Running=20
        Extended</A> <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRRUNNING">Diagnostics=20
        (Offline)" in topic 4.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
        <LI>From the extended diagnostics main menu, select option =
<B>3</B> to=20
        set the date and time. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
        <LI>If you need to set the data rate that the customer is using =
for a=20
        Token-Ring network or to select the media type that the customer =
is=20
        using for an Ethernet Network, select option <B>4</B> to run =
setup. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
    <LI><B></B>Perform a detailed test of the 5494 hardware by selecting =
option=20
    2 from the extended diagnostics main menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-44?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 44" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P44.gif"></A>         =20
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMIM2013>
<H1>6.0 Topic 6. Concurrent Mode from the Operator Panel or Utility=20
Program</H1></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>6.1 Introduction</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>6.2 Concurrent Mode from the Operator Panel (Online)</A> =

  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.3?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>6.3 Concurrent Mode Using the 5494 Utility Program</A>=20
<BR></LI></UL>
<HR>

<H2>6.1 Introduction</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Concurrent mode formats 5494 internal information for display =
at: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>The LCD on the operator panel <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <LI>A PS/2 workstation or PC running the 5494 Utility Program (PWS) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> The Utility Program panels that are displayed for=20
  concurrent mode are in English only. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
  <LI>A 5250 workstation attached to the 5494 through twinaxial cabling =
(NWS). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>Using the concurrent mode, you can =
display: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Configuration information=20
  <LI>AS/400 system communication status=20
  <LI>Information about devices connected to the 5494 through twinaxial=20
  connectors=20
  <LI>Information about devices connected to the 5494 through a LAN=20
  <LI>Status of the LAN=20
  <LI>Available storage (not available on the operator panel LCD)=20
  <LI>Trace information (not available on the operator panel LCD)=20
  <LI>Code corrections applied to the 5494 (not available on the =
operator panel=20
  LCD). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>To run concurrent mode from the operator =
panel, see <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDROPCMD">"Concurrent=20
Mode from</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDROPCMD">the=20
Operator Panel (Online)" in topic 6.2</A>. To run concurrent mode from =
the 5494=20
Utility Program, go to <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCMD">"Concurrent=20
Mode Using the 5494 Utility</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCMD">Program"=20
in topic 6.3</A>. To run concurrent mode from an NWS, see<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRDWSCONM">=20
Topic 7,</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRDWSCONM">"Concurrent=20
Mode from an NWS (Online)."</A>=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDROPCMD>
<H2>6.2 Concurrent Mode from the Operator Panel =
(Online)</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>You can use the operator panel of the 5494 to obtain =
information about=20
the current status of the 5494. This information is provided while the =
5494 is=20
operating (the Ready LED is on). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>You can request information when the operator panel is blank, when =
an SRC=20
is displayed, or when previous information is displayed. Basic operation =
of the=20
panel is as follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Press <B>Req</B>.=20
  <LI>Key in the 3-digit request code for the information you desire.=20
  <LI>Press <B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>If you press a request code that is not =
valid, the operator panel=20
displays: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
       <SAMP>999||************</SAMP>
<P>
   Press <B>Esc</B> to clear.
<P>
</P></PRE>Some information requires more than one panel for display. For =

example, the latest error log entries require more than one panel. For =
these=20
panels, use the left and right arrow keys to view additional information =
about a=20
particular entry. To see the next entry, press the <B>up</B> =
<B>arrow</B>. To=20
see the previous entry, press the <B>down</B> <B>arrow</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To leave the information panel, press <B>Esc</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
   <B>Notes:</B>
<P>
</P></PRE>
<DD>1. It is recommended that you return to the normal operator panel =
after=20
viewing data. If an SRC must be displayed at a later time, it will not =
overwrite=20
the information currently displayed on the panel. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DD>2. Information on the panel is not refreshed unless the same request =
is made=20
again. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLMIMX">Table=20
13</A> is a summary of concurrent mode requests with the request codes. =

<A name=3DHDRSTUS>
<H3>6.2.1 Displaying 5494 Online Status =
Information</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To display 5494 status information, press <B>Req</B>, type =
<B>200</B>,=20
and press <B>Enter</B>. Press <B>Esc</B> to exit. The following =
information is=20
displayed: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ124></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>5494</B> <B>Displays</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Explanation</B>                                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>200||1"2"3=194"5"</TT>    =

                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20

<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=
2/" width=3D0>|                    =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=
2/" width=3D0>|                    =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=
2/" width=3D0>|                    =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=
2/" width=3D0>|                    =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=
2/" width=3D0>|                     </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>200</TT>         Request =
code entered by user                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>1</TT>           Represents status of ALS communication          =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>"</TT>           Arrow (up or down) that indicates whether ALS   =20
             communication to the 5494 is active or inactive =20
                                                             =20
                 " =3D ALS communication is active             =20
                 =19 =3D ALS communication is inactive           =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>2</TT>           Represents status of devices attached to the    =20
             5494 by a twinaxial connection                  =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>"</TT>           Arrow (up or down) indicates whether workstation=20
             communication to the 5494 is taking place       =20
                                                             =20
                 " =3D One or more workstations are active     =20
                 =19 =3D No workstation is active                =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>3</TT>           Represents status of workstations attached to   =20
             the 5494 by way of LAN                          =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>=19</TT>           Arrow (up or down) indicates whether workstation =

             communication to the 5494 is taking place       =20
                                                             =20
                 " =3D One or more workstations are active     =20
                 =19 =3D No workstation is active                =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>4</TT>           Indicates whether the 5494 has successfully     =20
             contacted the target AS/400 system.             =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>"</TT>           Arrow (up or down)                              =20
                                                             =20
                 " =3D Yes                                     =20
                 =19 =3D No                                      =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>5</TT>           Indicates whether the 5494 has successfully     =20
             established the LU 6.2 controller session with  =20
             the target AS/400 system.                       =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>"</TT>           Arrow (up or down)                              =20
                                                             =20
                 " =3D Yes                                     =20
                 =19 =3D No                                      =20
                                                             =20
 <B>Notes:</B>                                                      =20
                                                             =20
 1.  This display is not automatically refreshed if status   =20
     changes.  To refresh status, press <B>Req</B>, type <B>200</B>, and =
  =20
     press <B>Enter</B>.                                            =20
                                                             =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=
2/" width=3D0>|  2.  If the 5494 is configured for concurrent host       =
    =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=

    =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=
2/" width=3D0>|      configuration information, see <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.16?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSLMUP">"Displaying 5494 Host</A>    =20

topic 6.2.16</A> for status    =20

2/" width=3D0>|      information on all configured AS/400 systems.       =
     </FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3DHDRCONFG>
<H3>6.2.2 Displaying 5494 Configuration =
Information</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To display 5494 configuration information, press <B>Req</B>, =
type=20
<B>201</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. Press <B>Esc</B> to exit. The =
following=20
information is displayed. Use the arrow keys to move from panel to =
panel. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ125></A>    _____________________ =
__________________________________________________________________=20
   | <B>5494</B> <B>Displays</B>       | <B>Explanation</B>              =
                                        |
    _____________________ =
__________________________________________________________________=20
   | <TT>201-01||</TT> <TT>ssd</TT>  <TT>c</TT>  <TT>a</TT>  | =
<TT>201</TT>         Request code entered by user                        =
 |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>01</TT>          Panel 1 of 5494 =
configuration information            |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>ss</TT>          Storage size (mb)        =
                            |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>d</TT>           5494 Clock               =
                            |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     |                 A =3D Set the 5494 clock from =
the primary AS/400   |
   |                     |                 system clock                  =
                   |
   |                     |                 C =3D 5494 clock set at the =
controller only        |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>c</TT>           Communications mode      =
                            |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     |                 0 =3D SDLC                    =
                     |
   |                     |                 1 =3D X.25                    =
                     |
   |                     |                 2 =3D X.21 switched           =
                     |
   |                     |                 3 =3D X.21 leased             =
                     |
   |                     |                 4 =3D Token-Ring              =
                     |
   |                     |                 5 =3D Ethernet                =
                     |
   |                     |                 6 =3D Frame Relay             =
                     |
   |                     |                 7 =3D Frame Relay with FR-TR =
Bridge                |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>a</TT>           Customer may configure =
one to four AS/400 system     |
   |                     |             connections.  This field is the =
number of the        |
   |                     |             configured AS/400 system =
connection that is          |
   |                     |             currently selected (1-4).         =
                   |
    _____________________ =
__________________________________________________________________=20
   | <TT>201-02||ccx</TT> <TT>ii</TT> <TT>aa</TT>   | <TT>201</TT>       =
  Request code entered by user                         |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>02</TT>          Panel 2 of 5494 =
configuration information            |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>cc</TT>          Logical connection retry =
counter  (00-FF)            |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>x</TT>           Arrow (up or down) =
indicates retry status            |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     |                 " =3D Configured for =
continuous re-tries at        |
   |                     |                       10-minute intervals =
after the initial      |
   |                     |                       re-try count is =
exhausted.                 |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     |                 =19 =3D Not configured for =
continuous retries.       |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>ii</TT>          Logical connection retry =
interval (00-1C)            |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>aa</TT>          SDLC or LLC station =
address (not displayed for       |
   |                     |             token-ring, Ethernet, or frame =
relay)                |

   | <TT>201-14||iu</TT> <TT>c</TT> <TT>ppp</TT>    | <TT>201</TT>       =
  Request code entered by user                         |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>14</TT>          Panel 14 of 5494 =
configuration information           |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>i</TT>           Start the controller =
session with the AS/400 system: |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     |                 0 =3D When the first NWS or =
PWS is powered on      |
   |                     |                 1 =3D Immediately after the =
5494 is powered on     |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>u</TT>           When an indication is =
received from the AS/400       |
   |                     |             system that there are no NWS =
sessions:               |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     |                 0 =3D Terminate the =
controller session unless      |
   |                     |                       there is an active PWS =
session, or         |
   |                     |                       there is an active =
controller session      |
   |                     |                       with another host.      =
                   |
   |                     |                 1 =3D Do not terminate the =
controller session.     |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>c</TT>           Concurrent host =
attachment:                          |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     |                 0 =3D Not configured for =
concurrent host           |
   |                     |                       attachment (the =
information above for      |
   |                     |                       parameters <TT>i</TT> =
and <TT>u</TT> refer to the            |
   |                     |                       currently selected =
host)                   |
   |                     |                 1 =3D Configured for =
concurrent host               |
   |                     |                       attachment (the =
information above for      |
   |                     |                       parameters <TT>i</TT> =
and <TT>u</TT> refer to the            |
   |                     |                       primary host)           =
                   |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     | <TT>ppp</TT>         If configured for =
concurrent host attachment, this   |
   |                     |             is the printer timeout value =
which represents the    |
   |                     |             number of seconds a 5494 waits =
before accepting a    |
   |                     |             print job from a different host.  =
                   |
   |                     |                                               =
                   |
   |                     |             <B>Note:</B>  If set to zero, =
printer sharing is disabled.  |
    _____________________ =

<HR>
<A name=3DHDRUCN>
<H3>6.2.3 Displaying AS/400 System Connection Communication =
Configuration=20
Information</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>You can use the operator panel to display configuration =
information=20
about the communication network that is used for the AS/400 system =
connection.=20
The format of the response is according to the communication mode (SDLC, =
X.25,=20
X.21 switched, Token Ring, Ethernet, or frame relay), as shown in the =
following=20
table. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To display AS/400 system connection configuration information, =
Press=20
<B>Req</B>, type <B>202</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. Use the arrow keys =
to move=20
from panel to panel. Press <B>Esc</B> to exit. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ126></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"50%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
SDLC                               </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"49%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
See <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.3?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLTSDLC">Table 14</A>                      =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"50%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> X.21 Leased                   =
     </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"49%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> See <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.3?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLTSDLC">Table 14</A>                      =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"50%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> X.21 Switched                 =
     </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"49%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> See <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.3?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLSTOS">Table 16</A>                      =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"50%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> X.25                          =
     </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"49%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> See <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.3?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLTSTF">Table 15</A>                      =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"50%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Token Ring                    =
     </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"49%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> See <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.3?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLTTR">Table 17</A>                      =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
