<HR>
<A name=3DHDRTSE>
<H3>6.2.4 Displaying the 5494 Error Log</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>You can use the operator panel to display the last 13 errors =
entered=20
in the 5494 error log. The most recent error entered is displayed first. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Use the up and down arrow keys to scroll through the entries. Use =
the left=20
and right arrow keys to display more information about the entry being=20
displayed. To view the second error in the log, press the <B>up</B> =
<B>arrow</B>=20
key. The end of the list is denoted by a row of asterisks. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> To view <B>all</B> <B>errors</B> in the 5494 Error =
Log, use=20
the View 5494 Error Log function of extended diagnostics (see "View the =
5494=20
Error Log" in topic <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#SPT6">4.2=20
</A>for instructions), or use concurrent mode from an NWS or a PWS. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To display the contents of the error log, press <B>Req</B>, type=20
<B>203</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. Press <B>Esc</B> to exit. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ127></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>5494</B> <B>Displays</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Explanation</B>                                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>203||ss</TT> =
<TT>eeeeee</TT> <TT>&gt;</TT>  =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>203</TT>           =
Request code entered by user                  =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>ss</TT>            Workstation identifier                        =20
                                                             =20
               <B>Note:</B>  00 may represent the 5494              =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>eeeeee</TT>        Six-digit SRC                                 =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>&gt;</TT>             More information to be viewed by pressing the =
=20
               right arrow                                   =20
                                                             =20
               <B>Notes:</B>                                        =20
                                                             =20
               1.  A 3-digit hardware SRC displays as a      =20
                   6-digit SRC with leading E00 (for example,=20
                   E00117).                                  =20
                                                             =20
               2.  A 4-digit SRC displays as a 6-digit SRC   =20
                   with 2 leading zeros (for example,        =20
                   000052).                                  =20
                                                             =20
               3.  A 12-digit code SRC displays as a 6-digit =20
                   SRC beginning with FF and 6 digits of     =20
                   sense data (for example, FF1234567890).    =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>203||&lt;mmdd</TT> =
<TT>hhmm&gt;</TT>  =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>203</TT>           =
Request code entered by user                  =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>&lt;</TT>             Return to panel with SRC by pressing the left =
=20
               arrow                                         =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>mmdd</TT>          Month and day error logged                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>hhmm</TT>          Hour and minute error logged                  =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>&gt;</TT>             Sense information may be viewed by pressing   =
=20
               the right arrow                                =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<TT>203||&lt;ssssssxxyy&gt;</TT> =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20

                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>

                                                             =20
 <TT>&lt;</TT>             Return to panel with date and time by =
pressing=20
               the left arrow                                =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>ssssss</TT>        For SRCs beginning with FF, this is the       =20
               remaining 6 digits of the 12-digit SRC        =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>ssssssxx</TT>      Sense data for a 6-digit SRC except LAN errors=20
                                                             =20
 <TT>ssssssxxyy</TT>    Sense data for a 4-digit SRC or the first 5   =20
               bytes of sense data for LAN errors            =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>&gt;</TT>             Remaining sense bytes for LAN errors may be   =
=20
               viewed by pressing the right arrow             =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>

    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>203</TT>           =
Request code entered by user                  =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>&lt;</TT>             Return to panel with first 5 bytes of sense   =
=20
               data by pressing the left arrow               =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>ss</TT>            Indicates sixth byte of sense data for LAN    =20
               errors                                        =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>xx</TT>            Indicates seventh byte of sense data for LAN  =20
               errors (if present)                           =20
                                                             =20
               <B>Note:</B>  If no additional sense data is         =20
               available, <VAR>ssxx</VAR> is blank.                      =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>

 <TT>************</TT>  Indicates end of the error log entries.  The  =20

</P></PRE>You can use the operator panel to display the TAC and timeout =
error=20
counters logged for each port. Use the up and down arrow keys to scroll =
through=20
the entries. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To display the contents of the error log, press <B>Req</B>, type=20
<B>204</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. Press <B>Esc</B> to exit. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>

<TT>time</TT> =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>204</TT>         Request =
code entered by user                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>pp</TT>          Port for which the errors are displayed (00-07) =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>tacs</TT>        Four-digit hexadecimal count of TAC errors      =20
                                                             =20

<A name=3DHDRCSC>
<H3>6.2.6 Displaying 5494 Communication and Statistical =
Counters</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>You can use the concurrent mode on the operator panel to =
display the=20
<I>nonzero</I> communication counters and the statistical counters. (See =
<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSAND3">"Communication=20
Error and Statistical Counters" in topic B.10.1</A> for an explanation =
of these=20
counters.) Use the up and down arrow keys to scroll through the entries. =
The=20
format of the response is according to the communication mode (SDLC, =
X.21, X.25,=20
Token Ring, Ethernet, or frame relay), as shown in the following table. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To display the contents, press <B>Req</B>, type <B>205</B>, and =
press=20
<B>Enter</B>. Press <B>Esc</B> to exit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->

    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>205</TT>             =
Request code entered by user                =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>id</TT>              Either the communication counter ID (from 60=20
                 to 6D) or statistical counter ID (6E or 6F) =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>cc</TT> or <TT>ccssssss</TT>  The 1-byte count in hexadecimal for a =
      =20
                 particular communication counter, or 4-byte =20
                 count in hexadecimal for a particular       =20
                 statistical counter                         =20
                                                             =20
                 <B>Note:</B>  If the communication counter is equal=20
                 to zero, it is not displayed.                =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"100%" colSpan=3D2><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Table 21. Token =
Ring                                                              =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>

<A name=3DHDRSTBYTE>
<H3>6.2.7 Displaying the 5494 Communication State =
Byte</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To display the communication state byte, press <B>Req</B>, =
type=20
<B>206</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. Press <B>Esc</B> to exit. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>State byte information varies depending on communication type. =

             1 =3D adapter open                                 =

<A name=3DHDRTADS>
<H3>6.2.11 Displaying the Status of 5494 Devices Attached to Twinaxial=20
Ports</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To display the identifying information of all devices that are =

attached and responding to polls from the 5494 at the twinaxial ports, =
press=20
<B>Req</B>, type <B>210</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. Press <B>Esc</B> to =
exit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ139></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>5494</B> <B>Displays</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Explanation</B>                                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>210-id||wwww</TT> =
<TT>mmm</TT>  =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>210</TT>            =
Request code entered by user                 =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>id</TT>             Port/station address of the device           =20
                                                             =20
                The first digit is the port address (0-7) and=20
                the second digit is the station address      =20
                (0-6).                                       =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>wwww</TT>           Device type                                  =20
                                                             =20
                <B>Note:</B>  The device type is obtained from the  =20
                workstation or printer.  Printers return a   =20
                group designation; the device type displayed =20
                may not be the actual printer device type but=20
                rather another printer device type that has  =20
                the same capabilities.                       =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>mmm</TT>            Device model                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>210||************</TT> =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>210</TT>            =
Request code entered by user                 =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>************</TT>   Indicates the end of the active devices.  The=20
                next entry displayed is the first entry if   =20
                the up arrow is pressed.                     =20
                                                             =20
                <B>Note:</B>  This panel also displays if none of   =20
                the devices attached to the 5494 are turned  =20
                on.                                           =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRTRADS>
<H3>6.2.12 Displaying the Status of 5494 LAN Gateway =
Devices</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To display the Token-Ring or Ethernet address of the devices =
that are=20
<BR>| attached to the 5494 by a LAN and are currently in session with =
the <BR>|=20
AS/400, press <B>Req</B>, type <B>211</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. Press =

<B>Esc</B> to exit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Use the <B>up</B> and <B>down</B> <B>arrow</B> keys to scroll =
through the=20
entries. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ140></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>5494</B> <B>Displays</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Explanation</B>                                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>211||aaaaaaaaaaaa</TT> =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>211</TT>            =
Request code entered by user                 =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>aaaaaaaaaaaa</TT>   Address of a device attached by way of Token =20
                Ring or Ethernet                              =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>211||************</TT> =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>211</TT>            =
Request code entered by user                 =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>************</TT>   Indicates the end of the active devices.  The=20
                next entry displayed is the first entry if   =20
                the up arrow is pressed.                     =20
                                                             =20
                <B>Note:</B>  This panel also displays if none of   =20
                the devices attached to the 5494 are turned  =20
                on.                                           =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3DHDRDDATE>
<H3>6.2.13 Displaying 5494 Date and Time</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To display the date and time set on the 5494, press =
<B>Req</B>, type=20
<B>212</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. Press <B>Esc</B> to exit. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Use the up and down arrow keys to scroll through the panels. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ141></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>5494</B> <B>Displays</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Explanation</B>                                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>212-01||</TT> =
<TT>yy-mm-dd</TT> =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>212</TT>         Request =
code entered by user                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>01</TT>          Panel 1 -- displays 5494 date                   =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>yy-mm-dd</TT>    Year-month-day                                   =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>212-02||</TT> =
<TT>hh:</TT><TT>mm:</TT><TT>ss</TT> =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>212</TT>         Request =
code entered by user                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>02</TT>          Panel 2 -- displays 5494 time                   =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>hh:</TT><TT>mm:</TT><TT>ss</TT>    Hour (24-hour =
clock):minutes:seconds             =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<HR>
<A name=3DHDRDATE>
<H3>6.2.14 Setting 5494 Date</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To set the date on the 5494, press <B>Req</B>, type =
<B>213</B>, and=20
press <B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The panel displays the date currently set in the 5494. Type the =
new date=20
(format yy-mm-dd) over the date displayed, and press <B>Enter</B>. The =
valid=20
ranges are: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>For year:=20
  <UL>
    <LI>91-99 for the years 1991-1999=20
    <LI>00-50 for the years 2000-2050 </LI></UL>
  <LI>For month: 01-12=20
  <LI>For day:=20
  <UL>
    <LI>01-29 for February (29 is valid during leap year only)=20
    <LI>01-30 for months with 30 days=20
    <LI>01-31 for months with 31 days. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE></LI></UL></LI></UL>If the date is valid, the screen clears and =
the date=20
is saved. If the date is not valid, the 5494 beeps once and the cursor =
is=20
positioned under the left digit of the value that is not valid. Key in a =
valid=20
date, and press <B>Enter</B>. If you want to cancel the request to =
change, press=20
<B>Esc</B>. The format of the panel is:=20
<P><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ142></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>5494</B> <B>Displays</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Explanation</B>                                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>213-01||</TT> =
<TT>yy-mm-dd</TT> =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>213</TT>         Request =
code entered by user                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>01</TT>          Panel 1 of 1                                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>yy</TT>          Year                                            =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>mm</TT>          Month                                           =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>dd</TT>          Day                                              =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRTIME>
<H3>6.2.15 Setting 5494 Time</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To set the time on the 5494, press <B>Req</B>, type =
<B>214</B>, and=20
press <B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The panel displays the time currently set in the 5494. Type the =
new time=20
(format hh:mm:ss) over the time displayed, and press <B>Enter</B>. The =
valid=20
ranges are: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>For hour: 00-23=20
  <LI>For minutes: 00-59=20
  <LI>For seconds: 00-59 <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL>If the time is valid, the screen clears and the time is =
saved.=20
If the time is incorrect, the 5494 beeps once and the cursor is =
positioned under=20
the left digit of the incorrect value. Key in a valid time and press=20
<B>Enter</B>. If you want to cancel the request to change, press =
<B>Esc</B>.=20
<P><PRE></PRE>The format of the panel is as follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ143></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>5494</B> <B>Displays</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Explanation</B>                                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>214-01||</TT> =
<TT>hh:</TT><TT>mm:</TT><TT>ss</TT> =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>214</TT>         Request =
code entered by user                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>01</TT>          Panel 1 of 1                                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>hh</TT>          Hour                                            =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>mm</TT>          Minute                                          =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>ss</TT>          Second                                           =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<P>

</P></PRE>This request provides controller session status and =
configuration=20
<BR>| information for each configured host. The status is useful if =
configured=20
<BR>| for concurrent host attachment. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE><BR>| To request the host status and configuration information, =
press=20
<B>Req</B>, type <B>215</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. The following =
information=20
is displayed. Use the up and down arrow keys to move from panel to =
panel. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ144></A></PRE>

    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Explanation</B>                                                  =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>

    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> <TT>215-11|</TT> <TT>p</TT> =

code entered by user                    =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>11</TT>          Host designation and panel number.  This field  =20
             is set to 11, 21, 31, or 41 for the alternate   =20
             hosts (H1, H2, H3, or H4), if configured.       =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>p</TT>           0 =3D This is an alternate host.                   =

             1 =3D This is the primary host.                   =20
             2 =3D This is the alternate alert host.           =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>3</TT>           If an up or down arrow appears after the 3, then=20
             this host is the data link control host and the =20
             arrow indicates the status of the physical link.=20
                                                             =20
 <TT>"</TT>           Arrow (up or down)                              =20
                                                             =20
                 " =3D ALS has been contacted                  =20
                 =19 =3D ALS has not been contacted              =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>4</TT>           Indicates whether the 5494 has successfully     =20
             contacted this AS/400 system:                   =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>"</TT>           Arrow (up or down)                              =20
                                                             =20
                 " =3D AS/400 has been contacted               =20
                 =19 =3D AS/400 has not been contacted           =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>5</TT>           Indicates whether the 5494 has an LU 6.2        =20
             controller session with this AS/400 system.     =20
                                                             =20
 <TT>"</TT>           Arrow (up or down)                              =20
                                                             =20
                 " =3D Controller session is active            =20
                 =19 =3D Controller session is not active         =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>

                 is the host to which we send alerts there is=20
                 an active controller session with another   =20
                 host.                                       =20

<HR>
<A name=3DHDRDISFRTR>
<H3>| 6.2.18 Displaying Frame Relay Token-Ring Bridge =
Counters</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><BR>| There are two requests to display the FR-TR bridge =
counters: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>| To display the FR-TR bridge counters for the token-ring port, =
press=20
  <BR>| <B>Req</B>, type <B>217</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| To display the FR-TR bridge counters for the frame relay port, =
press=20
  <BR>| <B>Req</B>, type <B>218</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><BR>| Use the up and down arrow keys to =
scroll through the entries.=20
Press <B>Esc</B> <BR>| to exit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| <B>Note:</B> If any counter is followed by a "+", it has =
wrapped. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ146></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT =
size=3D2><IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =

2/" width=3D0>|  <B>5494</B> <B>Displays</B>      </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT =

src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=

            </FONT></PRE></TH></TR>

<HR>
<A name=3DHDRRESFRTR>
<H3>| 6.2.19 Resetting Bridge Counters</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><BR>| There are two requests to reset the FR-TR bridge =
counters to=20
zero. To <BR>| reset the FR-TR bridge counters for the token-ring port, =
press=20
<B>Req</B>, type <BR>| <B>219</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| To reset the FR-TR bridge counters for the frame relay port, =
press=20
<B>Req</B>, <BR>| type <B>220</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| The operator panel returns to displaying a blank panel or =
any=20
current <BR>| error messages after the operation is complete.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRRESTART>
<H3>6.2.20 Restarting LAN Communication</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To restart the Token-Ring or Ethernet adapter in the 5494 =
after it has=20
been halted, press <B>Req</B>, type <B>230</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. =
The=20
panel displays message code 460 and SRC 540011, indicating that the =
restart is=20
in progress. If this request is received when the LAN is not halted, it =
is=20
ignored.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRTSTMODE>
<H3>6.2.21 Enabling Workstation Concurrent Mode</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To enable workstation concurrent mode so that concurrent mode=20
information can be accessed from an attached workstation, press =
<B>Req</B>, type=20
<B>290</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. The test mode LED comes on. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> Concurrent mode information may also be accessed =
without=20
enabling workstation concurrent mode by using the 5494 Utility Program =
and a=20
previously configured password.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDREXTMODE>
<H3>6.2.22 Disabling Workstation Concurrent Mode</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To disable workstation concurrent mode, press <B>Req</B>, type =

<B>291</B>, and press <B>Enter</B>. The test mode LED goes off.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRCPYCNFG>
<H3>| 6.2.23 Copying 5494 Configuration or Filter Files from =
Diskette</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.23.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>6.2.23.1 Configuration Data</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.23.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>6.2.23.2 Bridge Filter File</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.23.3?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>6.2.23.3 Placing the 5494 in Configuration Mode</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.23.4?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>6.2.23.4 Copying from Diskette</A> <BR></LI></UL>
<HR>

<H4>| 6.2.23.1 Configuration Data</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<BR>
<BR> |  You can copy a configuration file to 5494 storage.  You can copy =
a backup
<BR> | configuration file created with the 5494 Utility Program to the =
5494
<BR> | System Diskette only.  In either case, the 5494 must be in =
configuration
<BR> | mode.
<P>
</P></PRE><BR>| <B>Note:</B> A backup configuration is used when a =
network fails=20
and the <BR>| customer requires a different configuration (replacing =
token-ring=20
with <BR>| SDLC for example) to continue operations. Using the backup=20
configuration <BR>| requires only that the 5494 be powered <B>ON</B> =
with the=20
5494 System Diskette <BR>| that contains the configuration. The backup=20
configuration is used from <BR>| the system diskette in place of the one =
in 5494=20
permanent storage.=20
<HR>

<H4>| 6.2.23.2 Bridge Filter File</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<BR>
<BR> |  You can copy a filter file to the 5494 System Diskette.  Or, you =
can copy
<BR> | from the 5494 System Diskette to another diskette.  When you copy =
a filter
<BR> | file, the 5494 can be in normal mode or configuration mode.
<P>
</P></PRE><BR>| <B>Note:</B> The 5494 is unable to create files. If you =
want to=20
copy the bridge <BR>| filter file from the 5494 System Diskette to =
another=20
diskette, a file with <BR>| the name (5494FILT.DAT) must already exist =
on the=20
second diskette. The <BR>| 5494 will overwrite the file during the copy=20
operation.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRCM>
<H4>6.2.23.3 Placing the 5494 in Configuration =
Mode</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The 5494 must be in configuration mode before you can copy the =

configuration data from diskette. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Remove the system diskette from the diskette drive. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Press the 5494 power push button to turn the 5494 <B>ON</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>When the message <TT>003-02</TT> appears on the panel, insert the =
system=20
  diskette. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>To change the choice to 2, type <B>2</B> and press <B>Enter</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>When the Ready LED comes on, the test light will also be on, =
indicating=20
  that the 5494 is in configuration mode. </LI></OL>
<HR>

<H4>| 6.2.23.4 Copying from Diskette</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><BR>| To copy configration data, press <B>Req</B>, type =
<B>300</B>,=20
and press <B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| To copy a bridge filter file, press <B>Req</B>, type =
<B>320</B>, and=20
press <B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| The following messages are displayed on the LCD as the 5494 =
copies=20
the <BR>| data. Follow the directions listed. To cancel the request, =
press=20
<B>Esc</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

retry the       =20

            </FONT></PRE></TD></TR>

<A name=3DHDRCMD>
<H2>6.3 Concurrent Mode Using the 5494 Utility =
Program</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>You can use the 5494 Utility Program on a PC or PS/2 computer =
to=20
access concurrent mode information. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE><BR>| <B>Note:</B> When you upgrade your 5494 with the Release 3.2 =
system=20
diskette, it <BR>| is required that you update your 5494 Utility Program =
to=20
Release 3.2. Refer to the <CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>5494</CITE> =
<CITE>Remote</CITE>=20
<CITE>Control</CITE> <CITE>Unit</CITE> <CITE>User's</CITE> =
<CITE>Guide</CITE>=20
for instructions on how to install or update the 5494 Utility Program. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To use the 5494 Utility Program for concurrent mode, you need the=20
following items: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ148></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Operating</B> <B>System</B>  =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TH>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
                                                            =20
 <B>Requirements</B>                                                 =
</FONT></PRE></TH></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2><IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =

                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2><IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=

    =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=
2/" width=3D0>|  Client Access/400 Version 3 Release 1 or higher         =
    =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=
2/" width=3D0>|                                                          =
    =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =

configuration   =20
<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =

<IMG height=3D0 alt=3DRevision =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v400=

between   =20
 the 5494 and the Utility Program.                           =20
                                                             =20
 A LAN or twinaxial connection between the 5494 and the PC or=20
 PS/2 computer running the 5494 Utility Program              =20
                                                             =20
 The Utility Program already installed on the PWS fixed disk. =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"25%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> OS/2              =20
                   =20
                   =20
                   =20
                    </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"75%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> A Communications Manager =
configuration file created for the =20
 5494 Utility Program                                        =20
                                                             =20
 A LAN or twinaxial connection between the 5494 and the PC or=20
 PS/2 computer that is running the 5494 Utility Program       =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The 5494 Utility Program has a remote access function that allows =
it to=20
communicate with any 5494 within the APPN network. The instructions that =
follow=20
assume you are using a PWS that is attached to the 5494. For =
instructions on=20
using the 5494 Utility Program remote access function, refer to the=20
<CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>5494</CITE> <CITE>Remote</CITE> =
<CITE>Control</CITE>=20
<CITE>Unit</CITE> <CITE>User's</CITE> <CITE>Guide</CITE>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>To use the 5494 Utility Program to access concurrent mode, follow =
these=20
steps: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Are you planning to use the password defined during =
configuration=20
  to access concurrent diagnostics? <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI><B>Yes</B>-- Go to step <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.3?DT=3D19961016091447#LISS03">3</A>.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B>No</B>-- Continue with step <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.3?DT=3D19961016091447#LISS02">2</A>.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><A name=3DLISs02><PRE></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>On the 5494 keypad, press <B>Req</B>, type <B>290</B>, and =
press=20
  <B>Enter</B>.</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DLISs03></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Determine the operating system that is installed on the PC =
or=20
  PS/2</A> computer that will be running the Utility Program. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>If the operating system is DOS, go to step <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.3?DT=3D19961016091447#LISTYPE">6</A>.=20

    <LI>If the operating system is OS/2, continue with step <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.3?DT=3D19961016091447#LISOS2">4</A>.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><A name=3DLISos2><PRE></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Activate Communications Manager with the configuration file =
that=20
  was</A> configured to run the 5494 Utility Program. This was specified =
when=20
  the 5494 Utility Program was installed. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Start up the OS/2 Full Screen. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DLIStype></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Type <B>c:</B> (where <B>c:</B> represents the PWS fixed =
disk on=20
  which the Utility</A> Program is installed) and then press =
<B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If the Utility program has been installed on a fixed =
disk=20
  other than c, replace the drive letter with the letter of the fixed =
disk. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Type <B>cd\5494up</B>, and then press <B>Enter</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Type <B>5494up</B>, and then press <B>Enter</B>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Press <B>Enter</B> to clear the IBM logo. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>On the Utility Program main menu, select Concurrent =
Diagnostics.=20
  Enter the password if required. Follow the menu options provided by =
the=20
  program. If you need assistance while using the Utility Program, refer =
to the=20
  program's online help. </LI></OL>

<HR>

<H2>7.1 Introduction</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This method of accessing concurrent mode formats 5494 internal =

information for display at an attached NWS. When you start concurrent =
mode=20
correctly, customer applications continue to operate normally at every=20
workstation except the one you are using. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Lines 1 through 5 and part of line 24 of each concurrent mode =
screen=20
contain the configuration information. The contents of these fields are =
defined=20
in <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRGPHEAD">"Common=20
Data Fields" in topic 7.2</A>. The contents and format of data in lines =
7=20
through 23 vary, depending on which screen you select. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL><B>Screen</B> <B>Displays</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT>C1=20
  <DD>The contents of the twinaxial interface error counters and the =
error log=20
  buffer. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT>C2=20
  <DD>The contents of the communication and statistical counters, =
communication=20
  state byte, SNA state byte, and, if concurrent host attachment is =
configured,=20
  the status of all AS/400 systems. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <DT>C3=20
  <DD>128 consecutive bytes of data from the 5494 storage. You can =
select any=20
  starting address from 00 0000 to 10 FFFF for any virtual group. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT>C4=20
  <DD>The contents of the 5494 trace buffer and is used to start and =
stop=20
  traces. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT>C5=20
  <DD>Keyboard code information for all possible workstation addresses. =
In=20
  addition, the screen presents the vital product data for each =
workstation that=20
  is turned on and responding to polls from the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT>C6=20
  <DD>The 5494 error log. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT>C7=20
  <DD>Identifies all code corrections that currently reside in the 5494 =
storage.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT>C8=20
  <DD>The status of the LAN Gateway, including error counters and =
Token-Ring=20
  routing information. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT>C9=20
  <DD>If using the LAN or frame-relay AS/400 configuration, C9 displays =
the=20
  status of the AS/400 system. If using a LAN Gateway configuration, C9 =
also=20
  displays the status of the active LAN workstations. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><BR>| CA=20
  <DD>If the 5494 is configured for concurrent host attachment, CA <BR>| =

  displays both the configured host and the active host for each <BR>| =
possible=20
  shared session for each NWS address. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
  <DT><BR>| CB=20
  <DD>If the 5494 is configured for frame relay token-ring bridge, CB =
<BR>|=20
  displays bridge configuration information and bridge counters. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL></OL>
  <UL></UL></DD></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.1.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>7.1.1 Using Concurrent Mode at an NWS</A>=20
  <DL></DL></LI></UL>
<HR>

<H3>7.1.1 Using Concurrent Mode at an NWS</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><A name=3DSPTSPOT3>Do the following to start concurrent =
mode:</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> It is important to enter concurrent mode =
correctly, as=20
described in the following procedure. If not, <B>all</B> <B>sessions</B> =

<B>can</B> <B>be</B> <B>destroyed</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> Concurrent mode cannot be entered when the 5494 is in =

configuration mode. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Is the 5494 operational, the 5494 Ready LED lit, and the =
Test Mode=20
  LED off? <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>If the 5494 is already operational, go to step <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#LISATKP">3</A>.=20

    <LI>If it is not, continue with step <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#LISMKSURE">2</A>.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><B>Note:</B> It is not necessary to turn the =
5494 power <B>OFF</B>=20
  (<B>0</B>) and back <B>ON</B> (<B>|</B>) to enter concurrent mode. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DLISmksure></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Make sure the 5494 system diskette is in the diskette =
drive, and=20
  then</A> turn the 5494 power <B>ON</B> (<B>|</B>). Wait for the Ready =
LED to=20
  come on. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DLISatkp></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>At the 5494 keypad, press <B>Req</B>, type <B>290</B>, and =
press=20
  <B>Enter</B>. The Test</A> Mode LED comes on. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Select an attached workstation. Use an NWS or a PWS running =
5250=20
  emulation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>End any job in progress, log off the application, and vary off =
(end the=20
  AS/400 system session) that workstation. If it is not convenient to =
vary off=20
  the workstation, wait at least 1 minute after logging off the =
application to=20
  continue with this procedure. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>At the workstation, enter the Test Request key sequence =
(see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/D.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM2003">Appendix=20
  D, "Key Sequences"</A>). Press the <B>C</B> key. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>A diagnostic display screen appears containing a screen number =
(C1) in=20
  the lower left-hand corner of the display. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DLIScurso></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>The cursor is located under the screen number field. Change =
the</A>=20
  number to the desired screen number by using the Up Arrow or Down =
Arrow key. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DLISprent></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Press <B>Enter</B> to display the screen.</A> =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The status information on the screen is updated each time you =
press=20
  <B>Enter</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Repeat step <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#LISCURSO">6</A>=20
  and step <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.1.1?DT=3D19961016091447#LISPRENT">7=20
  </A>to select another display screen. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Restart the session by pressing <B>Error</B> <B>Reset</B> =
twice.=20
  Turn the workstation power switch <B>OFF</B> (<B>0</B>). Wait 30 =
seconds, and=20
  then turn the workstation power switch <B>ON</B> (<B>|</B>). If =
necessary,=20
  vary on the display at the AS/400 system. If the 5494 is online, a =
sign-on=20
  screen should appear within a few seconds. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>To exit concurrent mode and turn off the Test Mode LED, =
press=20
  <B>Req</B>, type <B>291</B>, and press <B>Enter</B> at the 5494 =
operator=20
  panel. </LI></OL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRGPHEAD>
<H2>7.2 Common Data Fields</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Display lines 1 through 5 and part of line 24 of each =
concurrent mode=20
screen contain the same data fields.<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.2?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGGPH">=20
Figure 13</A> shows the format of these fields. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGGPH>    =
_________________________________________________________________________=
_________ </A>
   |                                                                     =
             |
   | <B>A</B>  AAA  BB  CC  DD  (communication-mode-dependent fields)    =
                    |
   | <B>B</B>  NN PP U VVVVV QQQQQQQQ.QQQQQQQQ RRRRRRRR.RRRRRRRR =
SSSSSSSS.SSSSSSSS TTTTTTTT  |
 | | <B>C</B>  F.F  G.G  II  KK  WW-WWWWW  ZZZZ  ZZZZ  ZZZZ  ZZZZ  J L M =
  NNN  O            |
   | <B>D</B>      MM  XX  YY  ZZ  111111111111  22  33 44 55 66 77 88 =
9999                  |
   |      =
---------------------------------------------------------------          =
   |
   |    .                                                                =
.            |
   |    .                                                                =
.            |
   |                                                                     =
             |
<P>
<P>
   |                                                                     =
             |
   |    .                                                                =
.            |
   |    .                                                                =
.            |
   |                                                                     =
             |
   |                                                                     =
             |
   | <B>E</B>  C<I>X</I>                                                 =
     <B>F</B> P P                 |
   |                                                                     =
             |
   =
|________________________________________________________________________=
__________|
<P>
<P>
   Figure 13. Data Fields Supplied on All Concurrent Mode Screens
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
   <B>Notes:</B>
<P>
</P></PRE>
<DD>1. Screen-specific information is displayed in lines 6 through 23. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DD>2. Fields <B>B</B> through <B>F</B> are explained beginning in topic =
<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.2?DT=3D19961016091447#SPTNETWK">7.2</A>.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>A</B>=20
  <DD><B>Communication</B> <B>Parameters</B> <B>(Line</B> <B>1)</B> =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>The contents of this line depend on the =
communication mode used. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The contents of each field in all communication modes are defined =
as=20
follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Field AAA is the storage size in megabytes. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field BB is the number of ports and is set to 04 or 08. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field CC is one of the following communication modes: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>00
    <DD>=3D SDLC=20
    <DT>01
    <DD>=3D X.25=20
    <DT>02
    <DD>=3D X.21 switched=20
    <DT>03
    <DD>=3D X.21 leased=20
    <DT>04
    <DD>=3D Token-Ring upstream=20
    <DT>05
    <DD>=3D Ethernet upstream=20
    <DT>06
    <DD>=3D Frame Relay <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field DD is the current AS/400 system (01-04) selected. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>The remaining fields are different for =
each communication mode. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The definition of each bit or subfield is shown in the table for =
the=20
communication mode you are using. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLTBLUNIQ149></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"50%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =

    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"49%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =

</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><A name=3DSPTNETWK><B>B</B>=20
  <DD><B>Network</B> <B>Configuration</B></A> <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>This line contains network configuration =
information. The contents of=20
each field on this line are defined as follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Field NN is the logical connection retry counter. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field PP is the logical connection retry interval. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field U is the continuous retry field. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>Do not activate continuous retries after retry count expires=20
    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>Activate continuous retries at 10-minute intervals after retry =
count=20
    expires <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field VVVVV is the 5494 ID configured by the user or * if none is=20
  configured. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field QQQQQQQQ.QQQQQQQQ is the network qualified logical unit (LU) =
name=20
  for the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field RRRRRRRR.RRRRRRRR is the network qualified control point =
(CP) name=20
  for the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field SSSSSSSS.SSSSSSSS is the network qualified LU for the active =
AS/400=20
  system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field TTTTTTTT is the mode name. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>C</B>=20
  <DD><B>5494</B> <B>Specifications</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>This line contains 5494 hardware and code =
specifications. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Field F.F is the release number of the ROS. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field G.G is the release number of the system diskette. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field II is the data level of the correction file. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field KK is the communication cable type ID. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>00
    <DD>=3D X.21=20
    <DT>01
    <DD>=3D V.35=20
    <DT>10
    <DD>=3D EIA 232D=20
    <DT>11
    <DD>=3D No cable attached or cable attached is not valid. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If Token Ring or Ethernet is used for AS/400 system=20
    communication, this panel will show 11 (no cable attached). =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field WW-WWWWW is the 5494 serial number. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field ZZZZ ZZZZ ZZZZ ZZZZ is the IDs of the adapters in the 5494 =
(slots=20
  01-04). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>FFFF =3D=20
    <DD>No adapter in the slot=20
    <DT>E00F =3D=20
    <DD>Token-Ring adapter=20
    <DT>FEE6 =3D=20
    <DD>Ethernet adapter=20
    <DT>8FF6 =3D=20
    <DD>host-twinaxial adapter. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field J is the controller session initiation with the AS/400 =
system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>Start the controller session when the first NWS or PWS powers on =

    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>Start the controller session immediately. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field L is the controller session termination with the AS/400 =
system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>Terminates the controller session when an indication is received =
from=20
    the AS/400 system that there are no active NWS or PWS sessions.=20
    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>Do not terminate the controller session when the AS/400 system =
indicates=20
    no sessions are active. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field M is the concurrent host attachment. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>Concurrent host attachment is not configured.=20
    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>Concurrent host attachment is configured. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field NNN is the concurrent host attachment printer timeout in =
seconds. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If configured for concurrent host attachment, this is the printer=20
  timeout value which represents the number of seconds a 5494 waits =
before=20
  accepting a print job from a different host. Zero indicates printer =
sharing is=20
  disabled. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| Field O is the AS/400 date and time field. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT><BR>| 0 =3D
    <DD>Do not set the 5494 date and time to the primary AS/400 date and =
<BR>|=20
    time.=20
    <DT><BR>| 1 =3D
    <DD>Set the 5494 date and time to the primary AS/400 date and time. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>D</B>=20
  <DD><B>Workstation</B> <B>Information</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>This line contains information about =
workstations that are attached=20
using twinaxial and LAN cabling. It also contains LAN Gateway =
information,=20
defined as follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Field MM is the maximum number of workstations supported with the =
current=20
  configuration. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field XX is the LAN Gateway status. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>00
    <DD>=3D Not configured=20
    <DT>01
    <DD>=3D Token Ring configured=20
    <DT>02
    <DD>=3D IEEE 802.3 Ethernet configured=20
    <DT>03
    <DD>=3D DIX Version 2.0 Ethernet configured <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE><B>Note:</B> The following fields display if =
a LAN Gateway is=20
  configured. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field YY is the LAN Gateway status. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>00
    <DD>=3D Closed (inactive)=20
    <DT>01
    <DD>=3D Open (active). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field ZZ is the LAN speed. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>04
    <DD>=3D 4 Mbps (Token Ring)=20
    <DT>10
    <DD>=3D 10 Mbps (Ethernet)=20
    <DT>16
    <DD>=3D 16 Mbps (Token Ring). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field 111111111111 is the address of the 5494 on the LAN Gateway =
(as=20
  transmitted). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field 22 is the 5494 LAN Gateway SAP. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field 33 is the LAN Gateway response timer (T1) in seconds. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field 44 is the LAN Gateway inactivity timer (Ti) in seconds. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field 55 is the LAN Gateway receiver acknowledgment timer (T2) in=20
  milliseconds. (T2). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field 66 is the LAN Gateway retry count (N2). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field 77 is the LAN Gateway maximum out (TW). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field 88 is the LAN Gateway maximum in (N3). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field 9999 is the Ethernet media type: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>10b2
    <DD>=3D 10BASE2=20
    <DT>10b5
    <DD>=3D 10BASE5=20
    <DT>10bt=20
    <DD>=3D 10BASE-T <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE><B>Note:</B> Field 9999 does not display for =
Token Ring. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><B>Note:</B> The fields on the previous =
topics are from the=20
configuration information. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>E</B>=20
  <DD><B>Screen</B> <B>Selection</B> <B>Field</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>This field allows you to select which =
concurrent mode screen the 5494=20
displays. When you first enter concurrent mode, screen C1 appears on the =
display=20
station with the cursor positioned below the second character of this =
field.=20
Press <B>Enter</B> to display the data on this screen. To select a =
different=20
screen, use the Cursor Up or Cursor Down key to change the screen number =
and=20
then press <B>Enter</B>. If you do not change the value of the screen =
selection=20
field, the 5494 updates all fields in the current screen each time you =
press the=20
Enter key. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>F</B>=20
  <DD><B>Printer</B> <B>Selection</B> <B>Field</B> <B>for</B> =
<B>Concurrent</B>=20
  <B>Mode</B> <B>Screen</B> <B>Printing</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>This field contains the port (0-7) and =
station (0-6) address of the=20
printer selected for the copy to printer function for concurrent mode =
screen=20
printing. The default value of this field is determined by the value =
selected=20
for the P field during CSU. If no printer was selected at that time, '- =
-'=20
appears on the screen. In either case, you can use the Cursor Up or =
Cursor Down=20
key to change the printer address contained in this field. However, if =
you press=20
the Print key with no printer selected, the 5494 uses the first printer=20
available (not in session) as the workstations are polled to print out =
the=20
contents of the concurrent mode screen currently being displayed.=20
<HR>

<H2>7.3 C1 Screen</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The C1 screen displays the contents of the error log buffer =
and the=20
twinaxial interface error counters. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.3?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGSCN4">Figure=20
15</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGSCN4>    =
_________________________________________________________________________=
_________ </A>
   |                                                                     =
             |
   |     AAA  BB  CC  DD  (communication-mode-dependent fields)          =

<P>
<P>
   Figure 15. C1 Screen
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>A</B> <B>B</B>=20
  <DD><B>Error</B> <B>Log</B> <B>Buffer</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>The error log buffer section of the C1 =
screen lists all errors=20
currently stored in the 5494 error log buffer. The oldest entry is the =
first=20
entry in the first column. The error log buffer section is divided into =
two=20
blocks by a dashed line. All entries above the dashed line (<B>A</B>) =
have been=20
sent to the AS/400 system. All entries below the dashed line (<B>B</B>) =
have not=20
been sent to the AS/400 system. Entries are sent to the AS/400 system =
when the=20
5494 is varied off or error counters overflow. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Each entry consists of three fields, described as follows: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Field LL is a 1-byte logical session ID that indicates the session =
in=20
  which the error was detected. A value of 00 indicates the 5494 for =
some SRCs. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> For SRCs 42xxxx, 43xxxx, and 44xxxx, the high two =
bits of=20
  the LL field indicate which AS/400 system experienced the error: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>00 =3D H1, 40 =3D H2, 80 =3D H3, and C0 =3D H4. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>Field EEEE is a 2-byte SRC. The first digit of 2-byte SRCs is 0. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field FFFF FF is a 3-byte SRC. The first digit of 3-byte SRCs is =
not 0. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Field SSSSSSSSSS is the sense byte field. The number of sense =
bytes=20
  displayed in this field depends on the SRC. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>C</B>=20
  <DD><B>Twinaxial</B> <B>Interface</B> <B>Error</B> <B>Counters</B> =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>This section of the C1 screen displays =
the contents of two different=20
sets of error counters. The fields indicated by AAAA contain the =
transmit=20
activity check (TAC) error counters. The fields indicated by BBBB =
contain the=20
parity-timeout error counters. Separate counters are displayed for each =
port as=20
follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
       <SAMP>Port</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP>   <SAMP>Port</SAMP> =
<SAMP>1</SAMP>   <SAMP>Port</SAMP> <SAMP>2</SAMP>   <SAMP>Port</SAMP> =
<SAMP>3</SAMP>
<P>
<BR>
      <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP>  =
<SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP>  =
<SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP>  =
<SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP>
<P>
<BR>
       <SAMP>Port</SAMP> <SAMP>4</SAMP>   <SAMP>Port</SAMP> =
<SAMP>5</SAMP>   <SAMP>Port</SAMP> <SAMP>6</SAMP>   <SAMP>Port</SAMP> =
<SAMP>7</SAMP>
<P>
<BR>
      <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP>  =
<SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP>  =
<SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP>  =
<SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP> <SAMP>0</SAMP>
</P></PRE>

<DL>
  <DT><B>A</B>=20
  <DD><B>Communication</B> <B>and</B> <B>Statistical</B> <B>Counters</B> =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>This section of the C2 screen displays =
the contents of communication=20
and statistical counters. The counters identified by AA are 1-byte =
communication=20
counters (60 through 6D). The counters identified by BBBBBBBB are 4-byte =

statistical counters (6E and 6F). See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.9?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSDLCCNT">"Communication</A>=20
<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.9?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSDLCCNT">Error=20
Counters (60 through 6D)" in topic B.9</A> and <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSTATCNT">"Statistical=20
Counters (6E</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSTATCNT">and=20
6F)" in topic B.10</A> for more information on these counters. =

    <TD width=3D"17%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> 5          </FONT></PRE></TD>

                            </FONT></PRE></TD></TR>

network ready                       </FONT></PRE></TD></TR>

     active or <B>on</B> signal; a 1 indicates an inactive or <B>off</B> =

</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><A name=3DSPTC2CHA><BR>| <B>G</B>=20
  <DD><B>Host</B> <B>Configuration</B> <B>Information</B> <B>and</B>=20
  <B>Attachment</B> <B>Status</B></A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>This section of the C2 screen contains =
configuration and status <BR>|=20
information for the four possible hosts that can be configured on the =
<BR>|=20
5494. The status information is useful when configured for concurrent =
<BR>| host=20
attachment. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL><B>Field</B> <B>Definition</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <DT>H1-H4=20
  <DD>This field represents the numbers of the configurable <BR>| hosts. =
The H1=20
  through H4 field appears on the screen. However, information appears =
in the=20
  fields following the H1-H4 field only if that host is configured. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT>P=20
  <DD>This field identifies the host status: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>Alternate host=20
    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>Primary host=20
    <DT>2 =3D
    <DD>Alternate host currently receiving alerts while the primary is =
not=20
    active. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <DT>X=20
  <DD>This field indicates the status of the link. This field is set to =
1 for=20
  only one host. The 5494 attempts to activate <BR>| the primary host =
first. If=20
  unsuccessful and configured for <BR>| concurrent host attachment, it =
then=20
  attempts to activate the alternate hosts one at a time. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>The first ALS has been contacted. It may now be possible to link =
to the=20
    other hosts through this ALS.=20
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>This is not the first ALS contacted. If all hosts have this =
field set to=20
    0, there is currently no active link. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <DT>A=20
  <DD>This field indicates the host communication status: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>This AS/400 system has not been contacted.=20
    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>This AS/400 system has been contacted. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <DT>S=20
  <DD>This field indicates the controller session status: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>No controller session is active with this host.=20
    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>The controller session is active with this host. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <DT>J=20
  <DD>This field indicates the controller session initiation for this =
host: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>Start the controller session when the first NWS (or PWS if this =
is the=20
    primary host) powers on.=20
    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>Start the controller session immediately without waiting for an =
active=20
    NWS. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <DT>L=20
  <DD>This field indicates the controller session termination for this =
host: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>0 =3D
    <DD>Terminate the controller session when an indication is received =
from the=20
    AS/400 system that there are no active NWS sessions.=20
    <DT>1 =3D
    <DD>Do not terminate the controller session when the AS/400 system =
indicates=20
    no sessions are active. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> The controller session to the host which receives =
5494=20
    alerts is not ended until no NWSs or PWSs are in session with any =
host. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <DT>UUUUUUUU=20
  <DD>This field identifies the LU name for this host. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><BR>| VVVVVVVV=20
  <DD>This field identifies the network ID for this host. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><BR>| WWWWWWWW=20
  <DD>This field identifies the 5494 network ID for this host. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><BR>| XXXXXXXX=20
  <DD>This field identifies the mode name for this host. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->

  <DD><B>Token-Ring</B> <B>Communication</B> <B>and</B> =

<DL><B>Field</B> <B>Definition</B>=20
  <DT>EEEEEEEE=20
  <DD>The line error count.=20
  <DT>FFFFFFFF=20
  <DD>The burst error count.=20
  <DT>GGGGGGGG=20
  <DD>The abort delimiter.=20
  <DT>HHHHHHHH=20
  <DD>The receive congestion count.=20
  <DT>IIIIIIII=20
  <DD>The frequency error count.=20
  <DT>JJJJJJJJ=20
  <DD>The interval error count.=20
  <DT>KKKKKKKK=20
  <DD>The access control (a/c) error count.=20
  <DT>LLLLLLLL=20
  <DD>The lost frame count.=20
  <DT>MMMMMMMM=20
  <DD>The frame copy error count.=20
  <DT>NNNNNNNN=20
  <DD>The token error count.=20
  <DT>QQ=20
  <DD>Contains the numeric overflow from the fields that precede it. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
<DL>
  <DT><B>B</B>=20
  <DD>Information about routing to the active AS/400 system. =
