<H2>B.7 Configuration Data Description</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The following descriptions of configuration data are for =
remote and=20
local stations. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.7.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>B.7.1 Remote Stations</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.7.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>B.7.2 Local Stations</A> </LI></UL>
<HR>

<H3>B.7.1 Remote Stations</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The following are descriptions of the configuration data for =
remote=20
stations: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI><B>Line</B> is the communication line number that this workstation =
is on. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B>Station</B> <B>Addr</B> is the address for the 5494. The =
station=20
  address permits the data communication system to address a specific =
remote=20
  control unit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B>LSID</B> (logical station identification) permits the data=20
  communication system to communicate to the 5494 which specific =
workstation the=20
  system wants to communicate with. The network address for a =
workstation is the=20
  last 6 bits of the LSID. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B>Logical</B> <B>ID</B> is the name the data communication system =
uses to=20
  address a specific workstation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B>Description</B> is the type of device being addressed. =
</LI></UL>
<HR>

<H3>B.7.2 Local Stations</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The following are descriptions of the configuration data for =
local=20
workstations: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI><B>Device</B> <B>Addr</B> is the address of the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B>Unit</B> <B>Addr</B> is the address of the workstations =
assigned to the=20
  5494. The first digit is the physical port or cable number, and the =
second=20
  digit is the station address. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B>Logical</B> <B>ID</B> is the name the data communication system =
uses to=20
  address the workstations assigned to the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B>Description</B> is the type of device being addressed. =
</LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRELOGBUF>
<H2>B.8 Error Log Buffer</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The error log buffer is a 128-byte buffer in dynamic RAM =
(DRAM) where=20
SRCs from attached workstations and some selected 5494 SRCs are =
accumulated and=20
then sent to the AS/400 system for storage. The error log buffer retains =
entries=20
that have been sent to the AS/400 system until they are overwritten. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.8.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>B.8.1 Error Log Buffer Information</A> </LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRELGINFO>
<H3>B.8.1 Error Log Buffer Information</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Error log entries in the error log buffer have the following =
format: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>LSID,<VAR>XXYY</VAR>,S0,S1,S2,S3,S4 <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>where: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL>
  <DT>LSID
  <DD>=3D logical session ID <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> For 42xxxx, 43xxxx, and 44xxxx error codes, the LSID =
is in=20
  the low six bits of the field and the high two bits identify the =
AS/400 system=20
  experiencing the error: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>00 =3D H1, 40 =3D H2, 80 =3D H3, and C0 =3D H4. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
  <DT><VAR>XXYY</VAR>
  <DD>=3D SRC (See <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPD">Topic=20
  3, "5494 Message Codes and System Reference Codes</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/3.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPD">(SRCs).")</A>=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><VAR>XX</VAR> =3D
  <DD>device type <BR>00 =3D 5494 <BR>01 =3D display station <BR>02 =3D =
printer <BR>03=20
  =3D could not determine if printer or display station <BR>10-99 =3D =
5494 (6-digit=20
  SRC) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <DT><VAR>YY</VAR> =3D
  <DD>error detail <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>S0 through S4 sense bytes <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>SRCs 0040 through 0045, 0047, 0048, and 0050 through 0053 have no =
sense=20
  bytes. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>SRCs 0046 through 0054 have 4 sense bytes. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>SRCs 0070 through 0098 have 5 sense bytes. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>SRCs 01xx and 02xx have 5 sense bytes. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>X.21, X.25, SNA, LAN, Frame Relay, and =
V.25 bis SRCs are 6-digit=20
codes and appear in fields <VAR>XXYY</VAR> and S0. <VAR>XX</VAR> is =
equal to or=20
greater than 10 in all 6 digit codes.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRSDLCCNT>
<H2>B.9 Communication Error Counters (60 through =
6D)</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>SDLC errors that can be corrected and recovered are counted, =
and the=20
cumulative total is stored in the 5494. When any counter reaches 255, or =
when=20
the AS/400 system requests maintenance statistics, each counter that has =
a value=20
more than zero has its contents converted to an SRC. The code is sent to =
the=20
AS/400 system as a 5494 error log entry (0060 - 006D). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> These SRCs never appear in the 5494 error log or on =
any=20
workstation. The counters are reset when the contents are formatted into =
an SRC.=20
These counters give an indication of communication interface line =
quality and=20
recovery activity within the 5494. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSAND3">"Communication=20
Error and Statistical Counters" in topic B.10.1</A> for an explanation =
of each=20
communication error counter. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.6?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCSC">"Displaying=20
5494</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.6?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCSC">Communication=20
and Statistical Counters" in topic 6.2.6</A> for instructions on =
displaying the=20
communication error counters at the 5494 operator panel. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRC2SCRN">"C2=20
Screen" in topic 7.4</A> for instructions on displaying the =
communication error=20
counters on the C2 concurrent mode screen at an NWS.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRSTATCNT>
<H2>B.10 Statistical Counters (6E and 6F)</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The 5494 has two statistical counters that contain 4 bytes =
each. These=20
counters are used to count the number of valid Information frames =
received and=20
transmitted. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> These counters never appear in the 5494 error log or =
on any=20
workstation. The contents of these counters are formatted into SRCs 006E =
and=20
006F and sent to the AS/400 system when the communication counters are =
sent. The=20
counters are reset when the contents are formatted into an SRC. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRSAND3">"Communication=20
Error and Statistical Counters" in topic B.10.1</A> for an explanation =
of each=20
statistical counter. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.6?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCSC">"Displaying=20
5494</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.6?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRCSC">Communication=20
and Statistical Counters" in topic 6.2.6</A> for instructions on =
displaying the=20
statistical counters at the 5494 operator panel. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRC2SCRN">"C2</A>=20
<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.4?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRC2SCRN">Screen"=20
in topic 7.4</A> for instructions on displaying the statistical counters =
on the=20
C2 concurrent mode screen at an NWS. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.10.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>B.10.1 Communication Error and Statistical Counters</A> =
</LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRSAND3>
<H3>B.10.1 Communication Error and Statistical =
Counters</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><A name=3D"MSG 60">
<HR>
</A><B>60</B> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Test Frames In Error (SDLC/X.21) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>When the 5494 is configured to use either SDLC or X.21 protocols, =
this=20
counter maintains a cumulative record of test frames received with CRC =
errors. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>RNR Sent (X.25) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>When the 5494 is configured to communicate over an X.25 network, =
this=20
counter maintains a cumulative record of RNR commands sent. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 61"><HR>
</A>
   <B>61</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Test Frames Without Error (SDLC/X.21) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>When the 5494 is configured to use either SDLC or X.21 link-level=20
protocols, this counter maintains a cumulative record of valid test =
frames=20
received. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>RNR Received (X.25) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>When the 5494 is configured to operate in conjunction with an X.25 =

network, this counter maintains a cumulative record of RNR commands =
received. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 62"><HR>
</A>
   <B>62</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Communication Underrun <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments during transmit operations when the =
communication=20
adapter fails to supply the next character to the transmit buffer in =
time for=20
that character to be sent out on the line. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 63"><HR>
</A>
   <B>63</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Communication Adapter Overrun =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments during receive operations when the link =
adapter=20
fails to transfer 1 byte of data to storage before the next character is =

received from the line. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 64"><HR>
</A>
   <B>64</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Data Carrier Detect Lost (EIA, V.24/V.28, =
or V.35)=20
or I Signal Lost (X.21) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments if the signal is lost for 2 bit-times =
during a=20
receive operation and an error is detected in the newly received data =
frame. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 65"><HR>
</A>
   <B>65</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> RFS Signal Lost (EIA, V.24/V.28, or V.35) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments if the RFS signal becomes inactive for 2 =
bit-times=20
during a transmit operation, and the host system response indicates that =
an=20
error was detected. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 66"><HR>
</A>
   <B>66</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> DSR Signal Lost (EIA, V.24/V.28, or V.35) =
or DCE=20
Is Not Ready (X.21) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments if the line becomes inactive for more than =
2=20
bit-times during leased operation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"MSG 67"><HR>
</A>
   <B>67</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Frame Sequence Error Counter (SDLC/X.21) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments when a frame sequence error (Ns and Nr do =
not=20
match) is detected. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>REJ Command Sent (X.25 only) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>The counter increments each time the 5494 transmits a REJECT =
command. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 68"><HR>
</A>
   <B>68</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Transmit Retry (SDLC/X.21) <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments each time one or more frames must be =
retransmitted=20
due to a frame sequence error. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>REJ Command Received (X.25 only) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>The counter increments each time the 5494 receives a REJECT =
command from=20
the host system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 69"><HR>
</A>
   <B>69</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Frame Check Sequence (FCS) Error Counter =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments when the FCS character sent with a newly =
received=20
frame does not match the character calculated by the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 6A"><HR>
</A>
   <B>6A</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Frame Aborts Counter <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments each time the 5494 receives an abort =
frame. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 6B"><HR>
</A>
   <B>6B</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Reserved <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<A name=3D"MSG 6C"><HR>
</A>
   <B>6C</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> T1 Timeout (X.25 only) <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments if an acknowledgment frame is not received =
within=20
a selected retry interval (T1 timeout). The 5494 then retries the =
operation.=20
After a selected number of retries, a 0053 SRC is posted in the error =
log. Both=20
the retry interval and the number of retries are selected in CSU field =
7. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>SHM Call Collision (X.21) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments each time a call collision occurs during =
SHM=20
operation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 6D"><HR>
</A>
   <B>6D</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> IPDU Retransmission (X.25 only) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments each time an ELLC inter-network protocol =
data unit=20
(IPDU) is retransmitted. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>IA5 Parity Error (X.21) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments each time a parity error is detected in an =
IA5=20
code received from the X.21 network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"MSG 6E"><HR>
</A>
   <B>6E</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Transmitted I Frames <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments for each I frame transmitted to the host =
system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"MSG 6F"><HR>
</A>
   <B>6F</B>
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Explanation:</B> Received I Frames <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This counter increments for each valid I frame received from the =
host=20
system.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DMSG><A name=3DHDRXXXX>
<H2>B.11 Using System Service Tools</H2></A></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>To access the AS/400 system error log utility: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Sign on to the AS/400 system and access the AS/400 system =
main=20
  menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>At the main menu, select the problem handling option. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Select the system service tools (SST) option from the=20
  problem-handling menu options. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> You must be authorized to use this option. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Select the start a service tool option. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This option displays service tools that you can start from the SST =
menu.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Select the error log utility option. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This option lets you display or print errors that the system has=20
  detected. The error log utility formats and gives a summary of system =
error=20
  log information. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Select the display or print error log option. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Select communication for the error log, and then enter the =
dates of=20
  the errors you want displayed. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>For the report type, select the option for displaying a =
summary of=20
  the error log. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>On the Display Summary of Communications Entries screen, to =
display=20
  or print the errors logged by the 5494, select option <B>5</B> for the =

  resource <TT>*NONE/5X94</TT>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Select option <B>5</B> on both the summary of line entries =
screen=20
  and summary of controller entries screen for the resource (controller, =

  display, or printer) of which you want to display errors. A partial =
report for=20
  the resource is displayed. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>To display a detailed report for the reference codes shown =
on the=20
  partial report screen, select option <B>5</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The reference code field is the first 4 digits of the 5494 SRC. =
The=20
  error code field contains the following information: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>For communication error and statistical counters, the error code =
field=20
    contains the count. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>For 6-digit SRCs, the error code field contains the last 2 =
digits of the=20
    SRC and any additional available sense data. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>For all other SRCs, the error code field contains any available =
sense=20
    data. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>(Refer to <CITE>AS/400</CITE> =
<CITE>Service</CITE> <CITE>Guide</CITE>=20
<CITE>-</CITE> <CITE>9402</CITE> for more details, if necessary.)=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMIM2190>
<H2>B.12 ERAP Description</H2></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Use the ERAP option on the Prime Option Menu of the online =
tests to=20
display or print the errors that are logged in the AS/400 system for the =

attached workstations and printers. See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM2014">"Online=20
Tests" in topic B.3</A>. A description of the data fields is given in =
the=20
following sections. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.13.1?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRERAP2">"ERAP=20
Table for Attached Workstations" in topic B.13.1</A> shows the error log =
for=20
attached workstations.<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.13.2?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRERAP3">=20
"ERAP Table for Printers" in topic B.13.2</A> shows the error log for =
attached=20
printers. Printouts from other AS/400 systems contain the same =
information, but=20
the arrangement of the data is usually different.=20
<HR>

<H2>B.13 Error Recording Analysis Procedure (ERAP)</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The following describes the ERAP options: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>If you select the end option, the ERAP function ends. If you =
select the=20
  End option and press <B>Enter</B>, the screen returns to the Sign On =
menu. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>If you select the All option, the ERAP tables appear one at a time =
for all=20
  devices on the line. When the error history table for the first device =
appears=20
  and you press <B>Enter</B>, the I/O counter table for the second =
device=20
  appears. This sequence repeats until the error history table for the =
last=20
  device on the line appears. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>If you select the displays option or the option for printers, you =
must=20
  also select a specific device. The I/O counter table, the error =
counter table,=20
  and the error history table appear for the selected device only. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL></OL></LI></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =

  target=3D_top>B.13.1 ERAP Table for Attached Workstations</A>=20
  <LI><A=20

  target=3D_top>B.13.2 ERAP Table for Printers</A> </LI></UL>

<H2>C.1 Equipment Required for a Data Communication =
System</H2><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>A typical data communication system consists of the following =
major=20
components: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>An AS/400 system=20
  <LI>A 5494 Remote Control Unit=20
  <LI>Workstations=20
  <LI>A communication network, including modems or data =
circuit-terminating=20
  equipment (DCE), and possibly a Token-Ring or Ethernet network. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>This appendix describes the AS/400 systems, =
workstations, modems and=20
DCEs, other devices, and network types supported by the 5494. If you =
need=20
further information about data communication, refer to =
<CITE>Introduction</CITE>=20
<CITE>to</CITE> <CITE>Data</CITE> <CITE>Communications</CITE>, =
SR28-0263, and to=20
the <CITE>AS/400</CITE> <CITE>Communications</CITE> <CITE>Network</CITE> =

<CITE>Planning</CITE> <CITE>Guide,</CITE> GC41-9861. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>

<UL></UL>

<H3>C.1.1 AS/400 Systems Programming Support</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>For all 5494 releases, OS/400 Version 2 Release 1 Modification =
1 or=20
higher is required. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><BR>| If you are using the Twinaxial Expansion Kit, OS/400 Version =
2=20
Release 3 <BR>| or later is required for 56-device support. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>For full function of the 5494 Release 3.0, OS/400 Version 3 =
Release 1 or=20
higher is required. This AS/400 release includes support for automatic=20
configuration of the RWS controller and attached devices, shared =
addressing,=20
5250 fax and image, and 5250 video delivery.=20
<HR>

<P>

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3DHDRMODEM3>
<H3>C.1.5 Modems and DCEs</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>If you are communicating with your AS/400 system through an =
analog=20
communication network, the 5494 and the AS/400 system are attached to =
the=20
communication line through modems. The transmitting modem converts the =
digital=20
signals to analog signals and transmits these signals over the =
communication=20
line. The receiving modem converts the analog signals back to digital =
signals.=20
The transmitting modem and the receiving modem must be compatible. For =
example,=20
the modems must transmit data at the same speed and use the same =
modulation=20
methods. The 5494 supports the following IBM modems: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>IBM 3833 Model 1=20
  <LI>IBM 3834 Model 1=20
  <LI>IBM 3863 Models 1 and 2=20
  <LI>IBM 3864 Models 1 and 2=20
  <LI>IBM 3865 Models 1 and 2=20
  <LI>IBM 3868 Models 1, 2, 3, and 4=20
  <LI>IBM 3872 Model 1=20
  <LI>IBM 3874=20
  <LI>IBM 3875=20
  <LI>IBM 5811 Models 10, 18, 20, and 28=20
  <LI>IBM 5812 Models 10 and 18=20
  <LI>IBM 5821 Model 10=20
  <LI>IBM 5822 Model 10=20
  <LI>IBM 5842 Model 1=20
  <LI>IBM 5853 Model 1=20
  <LI>IBM 5858=20
  <LI>IBM 5865 Models 1, 2, and 3=20
  <LI>IBM 5866 Models 1, 2, and 3=20
  <LI>IBM 5868 Models 51, 52, 61, and 62=20
  <LI>IBM 7855 Model 10=20
  <LI>IBM 7861=20
  <LI>IBM 7868. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>If your network is an X.21 Public Data =
Network or an X.25 Packet=20
Switched Public Data Network, your 5494 and the AS/400 system are =
attached to=20
the network through DCEs. The network may provide you with DCEs. If not, =
your=20
network supplier should give you information for ordering this =
equipment.=20
Contact your network supplier for more information.=20
<HR>

<H3>C.1.6 Networks</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The 5494 using the EIA 232D (CCITT V.24/V.28) communication =
cable can=20
attach to the following types of networks: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Public or private, leased or switched, point-to-point or =
multipoint,=20
  analog lines using a modem <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Dataphone Digital Service (DDS) using a Data Service Unit (DSU) =
with an=20
  EIA 232D interface <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>X.21 Circuit-Switched or Leased-Circuit Data Networks using an =
X.21 bis=20
  (V.24/V.28) DCE <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>X.25 Packet-Switched Data Networks using an X.21 bis (V.24/V.28) =
DCE <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>SNA Subarea Network or an APPN network. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| Integrated Services Digital Network via attached Terminal =
Adapter <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>The 5494 using the CCITT X.21 =
communication cable can attach to the=20
following types of networks: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>X.21 Circuit-Switched Data Networks using an X.21 DCE =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>X.21 Leased-Circuit Data Networks using an X.21 DCE =
(point-to-point or=20
  multipoint) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>X.25 Packet-Switched Data Networks using an X.21 DCE =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Frame-Relay Networks using an X.21 DCE <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| Integrated Services Digital Network via attached Terminal =
Adapter <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>T1 Leased-Circuit using a fractional T1 multiplexer =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>SNA Subarea Network or an APPN network. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>The 5494 using the CCITT V.35 =
communication cable can attach to the=20
following types of networks: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>DDS using a DSU with a V.35 interface <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Point-to-point leased line <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Broadband analog networks <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Point-to-point high-speed private line using limited-distance =
modems <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>X.21 Circuit-Switched or Leased-Circuit Data Networks using an =
X.21 bis=20
  (V.35) DCE <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>X.25 Packet-Switched Data Networks using an X.21 bis (V.35) DCE =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Frame-Relay Network using a V.35 interface <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>T1 Leased-Circuit using a fractional T1 multiplexer. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>SNA Subarea Network or an APPN network. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>| Integrated Services Digital Network via attached Terminal =
Adapter <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>The 5494 with a Token-Ring adapter =
installed, communicates with the=20
ring at a speed of either 4 Mbps or 16 Mbps. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The 5494 with an Ethernet adapter installed, communicates with =
IEEE 802.3=20
or DIX Version 2.0 frame formats and attaches to the Ethernet network =
using=20
10BASE2, 10BASE5, or 10BASE-T media.=20
<HR>

<H3>C.1.7 Ethernet Cabling</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The 5494 Ethernet Upgrade Kit does not contain an Ethernet =
cable. The=20
customer must provide one of the following: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>A category 3, 4, or 5 cable with RJ-45 connectors for use with the =

  telephone twisted-pair (10BASE-T) media. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The maximum length of twisted-pair cable between the concentrator =
and=20
  the 5494 is 328 feet (100 meters). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <LI>An RG-58 standard coaxial cable (IEEE standard 802.3 10BASE2) with =
bayonet=20
  connectors (BNCs) for use with thin-coaxial media. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The maximum length of thin coaxial cable between repeaters is =
606.8 feet=20
  (185 meters). The minimum length of thin coaxial cable between =
repeaters is=20
  19.5 inches (0.5 meters). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> A BNC T-type connector is shipped with the 5494 =
Ethernet=20
  Upgrade Kit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>A shielded twisted-pair drop cable with 10BASE5 attachment unit =
interface=20
  (AUI) connectors for use with Ethernet networks that have external=20
  transceivers. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The maximum length of drop cable between transceivers is 165 feet =
(50=20
  meters). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> An IBM Mini AUI-to-AUI Adapter cable (P/N 59G9004) is =
also=20
  required. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>For more information about Ethernet =
cabling, refer to the=20
<CITE>IBM</CITE> <CITE>LAN</CITE> <CITE>Cabling</CITE> =
<CITE>System</CITE>=20
<CITE>Planning</CITE> <CITE>and</CITE> <CITE>Installation</CITE>=20
<CITE>Guide</CITE>.=20
<HR>

<H1>D.0 Appendix D. Key Sequences</H1></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The key sequences in this topic are operations that permit you =
to do=20
the following tests and procedures: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>The configuration procedures in <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/B.3?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRMIM2014">"Online=20
  Tests"</A>=20
  <LI>The NWS concurrent screens in <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRDWSCONM">Topic=20
  7, "Concurrent Mode from an NWS</A> <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/7.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRDWSCONM">(Online)."</A>=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>The keys involved in the operations vary, =
depending on the type of=20
workstation attached to the control unit and on the operation. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/D.1?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGWRIKA">Figure=20
35 in topic D.1</A> through <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/D.7?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGITDEKA">Figure=20
41 in topic D.7</A> show keyboards supported by the 5494. Go to the =
figure for=20
the type of keyboard your workstation uses. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The key sequence function keys are shaded in the figures. The =
actual=20
keytop characters on your keyboard may not be the same as the ones shown =
in the=20
figure due to language differences. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>

<H3>E.1.1 EIA Interface Tester</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>You can use this EIA interface tester (IBM P/N 453637) to =
examine=20
individual signal lines of an EIA 232D interface.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRBILLIE1>
<H3>E.1.2 Port Tester</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>You can use this IBM Workstation Controller Port Tester (IBM =
P/N=20
94X2040) to isolate cabling and port problems on the 5494. The port =
tester is=20
shown in <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.1.2.2?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGC4PT1">Figure=20
42 in topic E.1.2.2</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Attach the port tester directly to one of the following: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>A twinaxial 5494 port or cable=20
  <LI>A twisted-pair 5494 port or cable=20
  <LI>The twinaxial adapter on an IBM Cabling System. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>The port tester monitors signals from the =
twinaxial ports on the=20
5494. Cables being checked must be connected to a 5494 twinaxial port. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A name=3DDGR><STRONG>DANGER</STRONG></A> <BR><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D80><!-- * -->
    =
________________________________________________________________________ =

   | <STRONG>Do</STRONG> <STRONG>not</STRONG> <STRONG>use</STRONG> =
<STRONG>the</STRONG> <STRONG>port</STRONG> <STRONG>tester</STRONG> =
<STRONG>during</STRONG> <STRONG>electrical</STRONG> =
<STRONG>storms.</STRONG>                   |
   =
|________________________________________________________________________=
|
<P>
</P></PRE><B>Note:</B> For translations of this safety notice, see <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/A.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPA">Appendix=20
A, "Safety</A> <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/A.0?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRAPPA">Notices."</A>=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Attention:</B> Remove and reconnect cables carefully. You may =
damage=20
connectors if you use force. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>

02/E.1.2.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20

  target=3D_top>E.1.2.2 Twisted-Pair Test</A> </LI></UL>
<HR>

<H4>E.1.2.1 Twinaxial Test</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Move the Selector switch to the left (1) position. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Attach the appropriate port tester twinaxial connector to =
the port=20
  or cable you are testing, or to a twinaxial adapter attached to the =
port or=20
  cable you are testing. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If the twinaxial plug is needed, remove the twinaxial =
cable=20
  from the twinaxial cable holders located on the side of the port =
tester. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Press and hold the test button for 15 seconds or until one =
of the=20
  following occurs: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>Only the green light comes on. This indicates that the port or =
cable=20
    between the port tester and the control unit is good. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>Only the yellow light comes on. This indicates that the wires in =
the=20
    cable are reversed somewhere between the port tester and the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>Neither the green nor yellow light comes on. This indicates that =
there=20
    is no signal on the cable between the port tester and the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This can also indicate that: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
    <UL>
      <LI>The Selector switch is in the wrong position.=20
      <LI>The port tester is attached to the wrong port or cable.=20
      <LI>The attachment to the port or cable is not secure. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
    <LI>Both the green and yellow lights come on. This indicates that =
either the=20
    selector switch is in the self-test position or the port tester is =
not=20
    working correctly. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the port tester connector from the cable or port you =
tested.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>If the twinaxial plug was used, put the twinaxial cable =
back into=20
  the twinaxial cable holders. </LI></OL>
<HR>

<H4>E.1.2.2 Twisted-Pair Test</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Move the Selector switch to the right (2) position. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Attach the appropriate port tester twisted-pair connector =
to the=20
  port or cable you are testing. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If you need the twisted-pair plug, remove it from the =

  twisted-pair cable compartment located at the bottom of the port =
tester. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Push and hold the test button for 15 seconds or until one =
of the=20
  following occurs: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>Only the green light comes on. This indicates that the port or =
cable=20
    between the port tester and the 5494 is good. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>Only the yellow light comes on. This indicates that the wires in =
the=20
    cable are reversed somewhere between the port tester and the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>Neither the green nor yellow light comes on. This indicates that =
there=20
    is no signal on the cable between the port tester and the 5494. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>This can also indicate that: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
    <UL>
      <LI>The selector switch is in the wrong position.=20
      <LI>The port tester is attached to the wrong port or cable.=20
      <LI>The attachment to the port or cable is not secure. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
    <LI>Both the green and yellow lights come on. This indicates that =
either the=20
    selector switch is in the self-test position or the port tester is =
not=20
    working correctly. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Remove the port tester connector from the cable or port you =
tested.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>If you used the twisted-pair plug, put the twisted-pair =
cable back=20
  into the twisted-pair cable compartment. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGC4PT1>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-98?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 98" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P98.gif"></A>          </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 42. Port Tester
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

reliability=20
and serviceability. Some of these changes affect the application of =
maintenance=20
procedures. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<HR>

<H3>E.2.1 Communication Cables</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<BR>
   When the 5494 detects a problem with the communications cables for =
X.21,
   V.35, and EIA 232D protocols, it can automatically wrap the transmit =
and
   receive signals.  <I>There</I> <I>are</I> <I>no</I> <I>switches</I> =
<I>to</I> <I>set</I> <I>to</I> <I>initiate</I> <I>a</I> <I>wrap</I>.
   Partial termination for the transmit and receive circuits is located
   within the cable; the remaining termination is located on the
   host-twinaxial adapter.
</PRE>
<HR>

<H3>E.2.2 Twinaxial Ports</H3><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The 5494 does not detect shorts on the twinaxial cable, but it =
does=20
report TAC errors when it detects that the driver or receiver circuits =
have=20
failed. Concurrent mode may be used to view the TAC error count logged =
for each=20
port. For more information about viewing TAC error counts, see <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/6.2.5?DT=3D19961016091447#HDRTAC">"Displaying=20
5494 TAC and Timeout Error Counters" in topic 6.2.5</A>.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMIM3001>
<H3>E.2.3 Cable Signal Quality Check</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The purpose of the cable signal quality check is to determine =
if and=20
where there is a failure in the cable, cable connectors, or an attached=20
workstation. The types of failures can be opens, shorts, poor =
connections, or=20
impedance mismatches. You must use an oscilloscope to do this check. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> The customer installs and maintains the cables. Use =
the=20
following precautions: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>Do not use this test to check the quality of work done on the =
cables by a=20
  contractor or a customer. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>If the cable installation is still under contractor warranty, or =
if a=20
  third party is responsible for the quality of the installation, use =
extra care=20
  so that quality of the product or workmanship of the cable is not =
degraded. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Use this test as a problem determination aid only when instructed =
to do so=20
  by maintenance procedures, after you have followed all maintenance =
procedures,=20
  or if the customer could not determine the problem. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Do not use this test for communication facilities owned or =
supplied by a=20
  common carrier, such as telephone lines. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE>You can also use the test to check cables =
installed on other products=20
for use on IBM systems. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>

<UL>

02/E.2.3.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>E.2.3.1 Testing with the Oscilloscope</A>=20

  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.7?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>E.2.3.7 Oscilloscope Settings</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>E.2.3.8 Adjusting the Oscilloscope for the Correct =
Display</A>=20
  </LI></UL>
<HR>

<H4>E.2.3.1 Testing with the Oscilloscope</H4><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This test transmits a signal down the line using the square =
wave from=20
the B-gate output on the oscilloscope. You can check cables of any =
length, in=20
sections of a maximum of 1525 m (5000 ft). This setup, shown in <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.1?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI38">Figure=20
43</A>, uses the <BR>Tektronix** 453 oscilloscope; however, you can use =
other=20
oscilloscopes with the same oscilloscope setup. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>For more information, refer to <CITE>Basic</CITE>=20
<CITE>Oscilloscope</CITE> <CITE>Operation</CITE>, SR28-0465. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI38>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-99?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 99" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P99.gif"></A>          </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 43. Oscilloscope Setup for Testing Cables
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.1?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI39">Figure=20
44</A> shows an oscilloscope display of a transmitted signal for a =
normal cable=20
condition and the change to that signal caused by a shorted or open =
cable. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI39>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-100?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 100" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P100.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 44. Oscilloscope Trace for Open or Shorted Cable
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRNORMCAB>
<H4>E.2.3.2 Normal Cable</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>If the cable is terminated by the correct load impedance (110 =
Ohms),=20
all the energy of the transmitted signal is absorbed by the terminating=20
impedance.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRSHRTCAB>
<H4>E.2.3.3 Shorted Cable</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>If there is a cable failure that changes the impedance of the =
cable, a=20
part of the signal is reflected back to the signal source. If the cable =
failure=20
causes the impedance to be lower than normal, the reflected signal is =
out of=20
phase and causes a reduction of the signal.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDROPENCAB>
<H4>E.2.3.4 Open Cable</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>If the failure causes the impedance of the cable to be greater =
than=20
normal, the reflected signal is in phase and causes an increase in the =
amplitude=20
of the signal.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMEASDIS>
<H4>E.2.3.5 Measuring Distance</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The reflected energy is delayed by the time (t) it takes for =
the=20
transmitted signal to travel to and from the termination or the fault. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>By measuring the time from the start of the B-gate pulse to the =
start of=20
the change caused by the reflected signal, you can determine the =
distance to the=20
cable fault or cable end. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>After you determine the fault, you can determine the distance from =
the=20
cable end to the fault by using the following formulas: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>For twinaxial (solid poly) cable: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<UL>
  <DL>
    <DT>Df
    <DD>=3D t (=B5s) =D7 324.7 ft/=B5s=20
    <DT>Dm
    <DD>=3D t (=B5s) =D7 99 m/=B5s <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL></UL><PRE></PRE>For twinaxial (Teflon**) cable: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<UL>
  <DL>
    <DT>Df
    <DD>=3D t (=B5s) =D7 344.5 ft/=B5s=20
    <DT>Dm
    <DD>=3D t (=B5s) =D7 105.0 m/=B5s <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL></UL><PRE></PRE>For IBM Cabling System cable: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE>
<UL>
  <DL>
    <DT>Df
    <DD>=3D t (=B5s) =D7 366.7 ft/=B5s=20
    <DT>Dm
    <DD>=3D t (=B5s) =D7 111.8 m/=B5s <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
    <DT><I>where:</I>=20
    <DD><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>
  <DL>
    <DT>Df
    <DD>is the distance to the fault in feet.=20
    <DT>Dm
    <DD>is the distance to the fault in meters.=20
    <DT>=B5s
    <DD>is microseconds.=20
    <DT>t=20
    <DD>is the time in microseconds from the start of the B-gate pulse =
to the=20
    start of the reflected signal. To find t, multiply the number of =
scope=20
    divisions by the B-sweep time/div. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<P>
</P></PRE></DD></DL></UL><PRE></PRE><B>Note:</B> Pulse rise time =
increases on long cables. Measure from=20
the point where the reflected pulse just starts to change, as indicated =
by the=20
arrows in<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.5?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI40">=20
Figure 45</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI40>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-101?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 101" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P101.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 45. Pulse Rise Time
<P>
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><I>An</I> <I>Example</I> <I>of</I> <I>Measuring</I> =
<I>Distance</I>: The=20
example in <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.5?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI41">Figure=20
46</A> is for a solid poly cable, using the preceding formula for =
measuring=20
distance, with the B time/div set to 0.2 microseconds and the number of=20
oscilloscope divisions at 6. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI41>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-102?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 102" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P102.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 46. Measuring Distance Using an Oscilloscope
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DL>
  <DT>t=20
  <DD>- 6 divisions =D7 0.2 =B5s =3D 1.2 =B5s=20
  <DT>Df
  <DD>- 1.2 =B5s =D7 324.7 ft =3D 390 ft=20
  <DT>Dm
  <DD>- 1.2 =B5s =D7 99 m =3D 119 m <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE></DD></DL><PRE></PRE>The fault is indicated by the direction of =
the signal change (up for=20
an open, down for a short). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> If the station protectors are installed, the B-gate =
pulse may=20
cause the diodes to fire and generate a glitch on the displayed =
waveform.=20
<HR>
<A name=3DHDROSCSET>
<H4>E.2.3.6 Oscilloscope Setup and Extra Parts =
Needed</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Use an X1 probe (you can use X10 probes by changing the =
vertical input=20
setting) and the following extra parts: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>One coaxial cable with a BNC end and alligator clips (IBM P/N =
1650790); or=20
  a BNC-to-banana plug adapter and multimeter leads <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>One resistor equal to the impedance of the cable (110- Ohms =
resistor); or=20
  resistor assembly (IBM P/N 7362344) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <LI>One BNC T-connector (IBM P/N 1650789) <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>One probe tip-to-BNC adapter (IBM P/N 453199). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>Use <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.6?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI42">Figure=20
48</A> and do the following steps in order: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Connect the T-connector to the B-gate on the side panel of =
the=20
  oscilloscope. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Use the probe tip adapter to connect the channel 1 probe to =
one=20
  side of the T-connector. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Connect the cable to be tested on the other side of the=20
  T-connector. If needed, use the coaxial cable with alligator clips or =
the=20
  BNC-to-banana plug adapter with CE meter leads. Connect the two =
alligator=20
  clips to the two leads of the cable to check the phase B and A lines =
of the=20
  cable, or to one phase line and the cable shield to check the shield=20
  continuity. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>You can connect the other end of the cable to be tested to =
the=20
  workstation if the cable is terminated. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>When checking shield continuity, you should connect the =
remote end=20
  of the cable to a workstation, or you should terminate it as shown in =
<A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.6?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI43">Figure=20
  47</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI43>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-103?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 103" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P103.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 47. Terminating a Cable
<P>
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI42>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-104?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 104" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P104.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 48. Oscilloscope Setup
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDROSCSTG>
<H4>E.2.3.7 Oscilloscope Settings</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Set the oscilloscope as follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Mode to Channel 1=20
  <LI>Trigger to Channel 1 Only=20
  <LI>Volt/Div to 0.2 V (initial setting)=20
  <LI>Input to ac. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>Set A triggering as follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Level to full counterclockwise=20
  <LI>A-Sweep Length to Full=20
  <LI>Horiz Display to Delayed Sweep (B)=20
  <LI>B-Sweep Mode to B Starts after Delay Time=20
  <LI>A-Sweep Mode to Auto Trig=20
  <LI>Delay-Time Multiplier dial fully clockwise (9.5). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>Set A- and B-time/division as follows: =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>A to 10 microseconds=20
  <LI>Pull to unlock=20
  <LI>B to 0.1 microseconds. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>Then, adjust as follows: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Adjust the A triggering level for a stable display. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Adjust the Delay Time to set the rise time of the B-gate pulse =
(left edge)=20
  at the left side of the oscilloscope. </LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDROSCADJ>
<H4>E.2.3.8 Adjusting the Oscilloscope for the Correct =
Display</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>If no reflection is displayed (as shown in <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI44">Figure=20
49</A>), you may be looking at the first good part of a long cable with =
the=20
fault; that is, a cable longer than 100 m (328 ft). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI44>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-105?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 105" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P105.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 49. No Reflection
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>If multiple reflections are displayed (as shown in <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI45">Figure=20
50</A>), the fault is less than 50 m (164 ft) from your end of the =
cable, or the=20
B-time base is not set correctly. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI45>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-106?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 106" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P106.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 50. Multiple Reflections
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Increase the B-time/div from 0.1 to 0.2 or higher until a =
reflection=20
displays; or, decrease the B-time/div to 0.05 so only a single =
reflection=20
displays (as shown in <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI46">Figure=20
51</A>). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI46>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-107?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 107" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P107.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 51. Single Reflection
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>When the reflection is displayed, you must short the opposite end =
of the=20
cable. If the displayed reflection changes by 180 degrees, you are =
seeing the=20
other end of the cable. If the displayed signal does not change when the =

opposite end is shorted, the signal reflection is caused by a fault in =
the=20
cable. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Consider</B> <B>the</B> <B>following</B> <B>when</B> <B>you</B> =

<B>perform</B> <B>the</B> <B>tests</B>: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>To determine the length of the cable, it is recommended that you =
start=20
  with the remote end of the cable open (unplugged). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>You can use 110 Ohms resistor or a resistor assembly (IBM P/N =
7362344) to=20
  terminate the line, or you can terminate the line by plugging the =
cable into a=20
  workstation and setting the workstation terminator switch to 1. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>You can connect short cable segments up to a maximum length of =
1524 m=20
  (5000 ft). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Look for a bad reflection. The B setting of 0.1 msec displays =
cables of up=20
  to 100 m (328 ft) or the first part of longer cables. To display =
longer cables=20
  of up to 1524 m (5000 ft), use the B setting of up to 2 msec. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <UL>
    <LI>The 0.1-msec setting equals 9.9 m (32.47 ft)/div for a solid =
poly cable.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI>The 2-msec setting equals 198 m (649.4 ft)/div for a solid poly =
cable. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>
  <LI>To magnify small changes, adjust the Channel 1 position knob and =
Channel 1=20
  volts/div to a lower setting. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Major faults at long distances can cause reflections no larger =
than=20
  smaller faults close to the test end of the cable. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>After finding mismatches, you can measure close to the fault to =
describe=20
  it more accurately. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Faults too close to the tested end of the cable, within 6 m (20 =
ft), cause=20
  reflections to occur within the rise time of the oscilloscope. Test =
from both=20
  ends of the cable if no clear reflection of the fault is displayed. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE><B>Note:</B> The 6-m (20-ft) measurement =
is approximate and depends=20
on the oscilloscope that you use. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><I>Oscilloscope</I> <I>Display</I> <I>Examples</I>: See <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI47">Figure=20
52</A> through <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI53">Figure=20
58</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI47">Figure=20
52</A> shows a good cable that is 155.5 m (510 ft) long. A gradual =
upward slope=20
of the displayed signal is normal after the first division and appears =
as a=20
higher upward slope as the B-sweep time increases. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI47>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-108?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 108" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P108.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 52. Normal Cable (Properly Terminated)
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI48">Figure=20
53</A> shows a cable that is shorted at the end to show downward =
reflection and=20
length. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><PRE width=3D80><!-- * -->
   Length of sweep =3D 7.8 div
   B setting =3D 0.2 =B5s/div
   7.8 =D7 0.2 =3D 1.56 =B5s
   1.56 =D7 99 =3D 154 m or
   1.56 =D7 324.7 =3D 507 ft
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI48>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-109?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 109" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P109.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 53. Shorted Cable
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI49">Figure=20
54</A> is the same as <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI48">Figure=20
53 </A>but with a higher vertical gain (0.2V/div). <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The 0 points to start. Notice the two wrinkles 1.3 and 2.5 =
divisions from=20
the start. They represent very small mismatches at the workstation =
connectors.=20
These mismatches are at a distance of 26 m (85 ft) and 50 m (164 ft) =
from the=20
start. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI49>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-110?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 110" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P110.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 54. Shorted Cable (Higher Vertical Gain)
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI50">Figure=20
55</A> is the same as <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI48">Figure=20
53 </A>but with an open end. This is an effective way to measure the =
length of a=20
cable. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>The bumps at 1.3 and 2.5 indicate workstation connectors. The =
large bump=20
at 2.5 indicates a larger mismatch (poor connection) than at 1.3. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI50>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-111?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 111" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P111.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 55. Open Cable
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI51">Figure=20
56</A> is not a correct display of cable reflections. The multiple =
reflections=20
are at 26 m (85 ft) of a good cable with an open end. This display is =
caused by=20
the wrong vertical gain setting (0.5 V/div) and the wrong B-time/div. =
Only the=20
first reflection in this figure is important and should be magnified by =
changing=20
the vertical gain to 0.2 V/div and B-time to 0.05 =B5s/div. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI51>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-112?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 112" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P112.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 56. Open Cable (Wrong Oscilloscope Setting)
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI52">Figure=20
57</A> shows a 155-m (510 ft) cable with one wire shorted to shield at=20
approximately 78 m (255 ft). The end is left open. This scope figure is =
valid=20
for the twinaxial cable only. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Notice the steep slope changes that occur at the point indicated =
by the=20
<TT>short</TT>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>A reflection of more than 10% of the transmitted signal, if =
measured=20
within 100 m (328 ft) of the fault, usually indicates an undesirable =
impedance=20
change. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI52>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-113?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 113" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P113.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 57. Short to Shield
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI53">Figure=20
58</A> shows the same condition as in<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.3.8?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI52">=20
Figure 57</A> but with the alligator clips interchanged. In this figure, =
the=20
same short is easier to identify because of the incident wave signal =
being=20
referenced to ground. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI53>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-114?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 114" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P114.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 58. Short to Shield (Oscilloscope Leads Swapped)
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMIM3002>
<H3>E.2.4 Line Continuity and Polarity Reversal =
Tests</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>You can use the following guide for testing line continuity =
and=20
polarity reversals. The checks are for single line segments; however, =
you could=20
use them for a complete line if the station junctions are connected by a =
line=20
adapter or an IBM 5250 unit that has cable-through (if the power is =
off). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL></OL>
<UL></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.4.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>E.2.4.1 Line Continuity</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.4.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>E.2.4.2 Line Polarity</A> </LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRLCTST>
<H4>E.2.4.1 Line Continuity</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>The only tools you need for line continuity checks are an =
ohmmeter and=20
jumpers to connect between the connector pins (signal lines) and the =
connector=20
body (cable shield). When you make the following checks, all resistances =
should=20
be less than the indicated values. These values apply to a 1524-m =
(5000-ft)=20
cable. Corresponding values for shorter cables are proportionally =
smaller. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>With both ends of the cable open and the cable not plugged into a =
machine,=20
measure (at either end): <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Line to line, higher than 100 000 Ohms=20
  <LI>Each line to shield, higher than 100 000 Ohms <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>With both lines tied to the shield at the far =
end, measure (at=20
nearest end): <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Line to line, less than 110 Ohms=20
  <LI>Each line to shield, less than 70 Ohms </LI></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRLPTST>
<H4>E.2.4.2 Line Polarity</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>After testing the line continuity and making any necessary=20
corrections, check the polarity as follows using <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.4.2?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI54">Figure=20
59</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>With one of the pins tied to the shield at the far end, measure =
the pin at=20
the nearest end. The resistance should be less than 70 Ohms (if over 70 =
Ohms,=20
lines are crossed). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI54>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-115?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 115" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P115.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 59. Twinaxial Cable Plug
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRMIM3003>
<H3>E.2.5 Workstation Twinaxial Interface Check</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Do the following to check the twinaxial interface at the =
workstation: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Turn the workstation power <B>OFF</B> (<B>0</B>). =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>For workstations with only one twinaxial socket and no =
T-connector=20
  (without cable-through), remove the twinaxial cable and go to step <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.5?DT=3D19961016091447#LISMIS5">9</A>.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>For workstations with two twinaxial sockets (with =
cable-through),=20
  continue with step <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.5?DT=3D19961016091447#LISMIS6">4</A>.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3DLISmis6></PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Remove any connector from both workstation twinaxial =
sockets.</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Set the terminator switch (if present) to position 2 (not=20
  terminated). If you make this check on a 3180 display station, push in =
and=20
  hold the center pin on socket 2 while you make the check. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Check for the following resistances at <B>socket</B> =
<B>1</B> using=20
  <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.5?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI55">Figure=20
  60 </A>and <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.5?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLCHK1">Table=20
  58</A>, setting the ohmmeter to a range of 1 or higher. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3DHDRMIM3005>
<H3>E.2.6 IBM Cabling System Tests</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This section contains tests for accessories used with the IBM =
Cabling=20
System. The tests are: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Impedance matching device or direct-connect cable check=20
  <LI>Twinaxial Y test=20
  <LI>Twinaxial terminator assembly test. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL></OL></LI></UL>
<DL></DL>
<P>Subtopics:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.6.1?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>E.2.6.1 Impedance Matching Device or Direct-Connect =
Cable=20
  Check</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.6.2?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>E.2.6.2 Twinaxial Y Test</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.6.3?SHELF=3D&amp;DT=3D19961016091447&amp;CASE=3D"=20
  target=3D_top>E.2.6.3 Twinaxial Terminator Assembly Test</A> =
</LI></UL>
<UL></UL>
<HR>
<A name=3DHDRIMDCHK>
<H4>E.2.6.1 Impedance Matching Device or Direct-Connect Cable =
Check</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.6.1?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI56">Figure=20
61</A> shows an impedance matching device (IBM P/N 6091070). =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> The resistor assembly is not present for =
direct-connect=20
cables. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI56>   <A =

src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P117.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 61. Impedance Matching Device
<P>

  62</A>) on the IBM Cabling System connector of the impedance matching =

  or direct connect cable. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<H3>E.2.7 IBM Cabling System Data Path Tests</H3></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>This section contains the test procedures for the IBM Cabling =
System=20
data paths and includes the following tests: <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<UL>
  <LI>Test for cable drop from distribution panel to control unit =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Test for cable drop from distribution panel to workstations except =
the=20
  last workstation on the data path <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <LI>Test for cable drop to last workstation on the data path =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI>Test for cable drop between distribution panels. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></UL><PRE></PRE>A typical IBM Cabling System data path is =
shown in <A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.7?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI60">Figure=20
65</A>. A test connector like the one shown in<A=20
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.6.1?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI57">=20
Figure 62 in topic E.2.6.1</A> is needed for these tests. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI60>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-121?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 121" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P121.gif"></A>           </A>

   Figure 65. Schematic of a Simple IBM Cabling System Installation =
Using
              Twinaxial Accessories
