<A name=3DHDRDISTCU>
<H4>E.2.7.1 Test for Cable Drop from Distribution Panel to Control =
Unit</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><B>Attention:</B> To prevent destroying any active jobs, make =
sure=20
that you do not unplug the connectors for any data path other than the =
one being=20
checked. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>Use the following procedure to test the cable drop from the =
distribution=20
panel to the control unit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Make sure that you disconnect the control unit from the =
cabling=20
  system at the cabling system wall connector. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Go to the distribution panel and do the following steps =
using <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#FIGMI62">Figure=20
  66</A>: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- figure -->
<A name=3DFIGMI62>   <A =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/picture-122?mode=3Dzoom"><IMG alt=3D"PICTURE 122" =
src=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/bookmgr/pictures/co2v4002.199610160=
91447.P122.gif"></A>           </A>
<P>
<P>
   Figure 66. Testing Cable Drop from the Distribution Panel to the =
Control
              Unit
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <OL type=3Da>
    <LI><B></B>Make sure that all connectors are correctly labeled so =
that you=20
    can restore the original configuration. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>Disconnect the red cable of the Y (or the jumper cable) =
<B>A</B>=20
    that connects to the cable drop <B>B</B> going to the control unit. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>Install a test connector on the cable drop going to the =
control=20
    unit at <B>B</B>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
    <LI><B></B>Check for the resistances in <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLMIT7">Table=20
    65</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> For a continuity test only, use only the first two=20
    connections shown in <A=20
    =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.7.1?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLMIT7">Table=20
    65</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLMIT7></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"100%" colSpan=3D3><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Table 65. =
Distribution Panel to Control Unit                           =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"67%" colSpan=3D2><PRE><FONT size=3D2>       =

                      =20

<B>Positive</B>              </FONT></PRE></TH>

 &gt; 5000 Ohms          =20

name=3DLIShms1>                                                          =
              </A>

     resistance is 36 to 54 Ohms.                                      =20

<A name=3DHDRDISTWS>
<H4>E.2.7.2 Test for Cable Drop from Distribution Panel to Workstations =
Except=20
the Last Workstation on the Data Path</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Use the following procedure to test the cable drop from the=20
distribution panel to the workstation: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Install a test connector on the red cable of the Y that is=20
  connected to the cable drop to be tested. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Install a test connector on the blue cable of the Y that is =

  connected to the cable drop to be tested. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> The test connectors are not required for this test =
but are=20
  recommended for ease of connection. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Check for the resistances in <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.7.2?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLMIT3">Table=20
  66</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> For a continuity test only, use only the first two=20
  connections shown in <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.7.2?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLMIT3">Table=20
  66</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLMIT3></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"100%" colSpan=3D3><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Table 66. =
Distribution Panel to Work Stations Except Last Workstation  =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"67%" colSpan=3D2><PRE><FONT size=3D2>       =
<B>Connect</B> <B>Meter</B> <B>Leads</B> <B>As</B> <B>Shown</B> =
<B>Below</B>       </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"32%" rowSpan=3D2><PRE><FONT size=3D2>                   =
   =20
                      =20
 <B>Normal</B> <B>Resistance</B>     </FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TH style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: normal" width=3D"32%"><PRE><FONT size=3D2> =
<B>Positive</B> <B>at</B> <B>Red</B> <B>Cable</B> </FONT></PRE></TH>

workstation of the data path: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Install the test connector on the cable drop to the last=20
  workstation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

  =

  67</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3DHDRDP2DP>
<H4>E.2.7.4 Test for Cable Drop between Distribution =
Panels</H4></A><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE>Use the following procedure to test the cable drop between the =

distribution panels: <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI><B></B>Disconnect the Y (or jumper cable) that is connected to the =
cable=20
  drop between panels at the distribution panel that is nearest to the =
control=20
  unit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Go to the distribution panel at the other end of the cable =
drop and=20
  disconnect any Y (or jumper cable) connected at that end. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Install a test connector on the cable drop between panels =
at the=20
  distribution panel most distant from the control unit. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
  <LI><B></B>Check for the resistances shown in <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.7.4?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLMIT6">Table=20
  69</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> For a continuity test only, use only the first two=20
  connections shown in <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/co2v40=
02/E.2.7.4?DT=3D19961016091447#TBLMIT6">Table=20
  69</A>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
</P></PRE></LI></OL><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- table -->
<A name=3DTBLMIT6></A></PRE>
<TABLE border=3D1 cellpading=3D"3">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"100%" colSpan=3D3><PRE><FONT size=3D2> Table 69. =
Between Workstations                                         =
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D"67%" colSpan=3D2><PRE><FONT size=3D2>       =
<B>Connect</B> <B>Meter</B> <B>Leads</B> <B>As</B> <B>Shown</B> =
<B>Below</B>       </FONT></PRE></TD>
    <TD width=3D"32%" rowSpan=3D2><PRE><FONT size=3D2>                   =
   =20
                      =20

<H1>GLOSSARY Glossary</H1><PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<P>
<BR>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- glossary -->
<HR>
<BR><CENTER><B><FONT size=3D+4>A  </FONT></B></CENTER>
<HR align=3Dcenter width=3D100 SIZE=3D4></PRE><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS access procedure"></PRE><B>access</B> <B>procedure</B>. =
The=20
procedure or protocol used to gain access to a</A> shared resource. In a =
LAN, a=20
shared resource is the medium. Some medium access procedures specified =
by the=20
IEEE 802 standards are carrier sense multiple access with collision =
detection=20
(CSMA/CD), token bus, and token ring. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"GLS access unit"></PRE><B>access</B> <B>unit</B>. A unit that =
allows=20
multiple attaching devices access to a</A> token-ring network at a =
central point=20
such as a wiring closet or in an open work area. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS acknowledgment"></PRE><B>acknowledgment</B>. The =
transmission, by a=20
receiver, of acknowledge</A> characters as an affirmative response to a =
sender. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS active"></PRE><B>active</B>. Able to communicate on the =
network. An=20
adapter is active if it</A> is able to pass tokens on the network. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS adapter"></PRE><B>adapter</B>. (1) A general term for a =
device that=20
provides some transitional</A> function between two or more devices. (2) =
In a=20
local area network, within a communicating device, a circuit card with =
its=20
associated software that enables the device to communicate over the =
network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS address"></PRE><B>address</B>. (1) A value that =
identifies a=20
register, a particular part of</A> storage, a data source, or a data =
sink. The=20
value is represented by one or more characters. (2) In data =
communication, the=20
unique code assigned to each device or workstation connected to a =
network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS adjacent link station"></PRE><B>adjacent</B> <B>link</B>=20
<B>station</B>. A link station that directly connects to a given</A> =
node by a=20
link connection over which network traffic can be carried. For 5494, =
when the=20
link connection does not pass through an SNA Subarea Network, the AS/400 =
system=20
is the adjacent link station. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS advanced peer-to-peer networking =
(APPN)"></PRE><B>advanced</B>=20
<B>peer-to-peer</B> <B>networking</B> <B>(APPN)</B>. (1) An extension to =
SNA</A>=20
featuring (a) greater distributed network control that avoids critical=20
hierarchical dependencies, thereby isolating the effects of single =
points of=20
failure; (b) dynamic exchange of network topology information to foster =
ease of=20
connection, reconfiguration, and adaptive route selection; (c) dynamic=20
definition of network resources; and (d) automated resource registration =
and=20
directory lookup. APPN extends the LU 6.2 peer orientation for end-user =
services=20
to network control and supports multiple LU types, including LU 2, LU 3, =
and LU=20
6.2. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS alert"></PRE><B>alert</B>. (1) For IBM LAN management =
products, a=20
notification indicating a</A> possible security violation, a persistent =
error=20
condition, or an interruption or potential interruption in the flow of =
data=20
around the network. (2) In SNA, a record sent to a system problem =
management=20
focal point to communicate the existence of an alert condition. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS All Routes Explorer (ARE)"></PRE><BR>| <B>All</B> =
<B>Routes</B>=20
<B>Explorer</B> <B>(ARE)</B>. In LANs, a frame that is generated by a =
source</A>=20
<BR>| host and transverses the entire source routing part of a LAN, =
gathering=20
<BR>| information on the possible paths available. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS All Routes Explorer filter"></PRE><BR>| <B>All</B> =
<B>Routes</B>=20
<B>Explorer</B> <B>filter</B>. A set of criteria which determine whether =
or</A>=20
<BR>| not a frame crosses a bridge. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"GLS alternate host"></PRE><B>alternate</B> <B>host</B>. For =
the 5494,=20
an alternate host is an AS/400 system that</A> is not the primary host. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS American National Standard Code for Information =
Interchange (ASCII)"></PRE><B>American</B>=20
<B>National</B> <B>Standard</B> <B>Code</B> <B>for</B> =
<B>Information</B>=20
<B>Interchange</B> <B>(ASCII)</B>. A</A> standard code, using a coded =
character=20
set consisting of 7-bit coded characters (8 bits including parity =
check), used=20
for information interchange among data processing systems, data =
communication=20
systems, and associated equipment. The ASCII set consists of control =
characters=20
and graphic characters. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS amplitude"></PRE><B>amplitude</B>. The size or magnitude =
of a=20
voltage or current waveform.</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS analog"></PRE><B>analog</B>. Pertaining to data =
consisting of=20
continuously variable physical</A> quantities. Contrast with =
<I>digital</I>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS analog transmission"></PRE><B>analog</B> =
<B>transmission</B>. A=20
signal transmission that is continuously variable</A> in amplitude, =
frequency,=20
phase, or some combination of all three. (Data characters in a terminal =
are=20
coded in a dc square wave voltage or in specially identified pulses or =
signal=20
levels, and are referred to as digital signals. Voice or =
voice-compatible=20
signals are usually ac voltages that are not easily identified and are =
known as=20
analog signals.) <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS application"></PRE><B>application</B>. The use to which =
an=20
information processing system is put,</A> for example, a payroll =
application, an=20
airline reservation application, or a network application. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS application program"></PRE><B>application</B> =
<B>program</B>. (1) A=20
program written for or by a user that applies</A> to the user's work. =
Some=20
application programs receive support and services from a special kind of =

application program called a network application program. (2) A program =
used to=20
connect and communicate with stations in a network, enabling users to =
perform=20
application-oriented activities. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS architecture"></PRE><B>architecture</B>. The description =
of the=20
logical structure, formats,</A> protocols, and operational sequence for=20
transmitting information through, and controlling the configuration and=20
operation of, a network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS asynchronous"></PRE><B>asynchronous</B>. (1) Without =
regular time=20
relationship; unexpected or</A> unpredictable with respect to the =
execution of=20
program instructions. (2) In asynchronous data transmissions, data =
characters=20
can be sent or received at any time; no modem clocking is used to =
establish bit=20
timing. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS attach"></PRE><B>attach</B>. To connect a device =
logically to an=20
adapter, so that it can</A> communicate over the network. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS attaching device"></PRE><B>attaching</B> <B>device</B>. =
Any device=20
that is physically connected to a network</A> and can communicate over =
the=20
network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS attachment unit interface (AUI)"></PRE><B>attachment</B>=20
<B>unit</B> <B>interface</B> <B>(AUI)</B>. In a local area network, the=20
interface</A> between the medium attachment unit and the data terminal =
equipment=20
within a data station. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS attention (ATTN)"></PRE><B>attention</B> <B>(ATTN)</B>. =
An=20
occurrence external to an operation that could cause</A> an interruption =
of the=20
operation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS attention identifier (AID)"></PRE><B>attention</B>=20
<B>identifier</B> <B>(AID)</B>. (1) A code in the inbound 3270 data =
stream</A>=20
that identifies the source or type of data that follows. (2) A character =
in a=20
data stream indicating that the user has pressed a key, such as Enter, =
that=20
requests an action by the system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS attenuation"></PRE><B>attenuation</B>. A decrease in =
magnitude of=20
current, voltage, or power of a</A> signal in transmission between =
points. It=20
can be expressed in decibels or nepers. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<A name=3D"GLS attribute"></PRE><B>attribute</B>. (1) A characteristic. =
(2) A=20
terminal display language or</A> transformation definition language =
(TDL)=20
keyword that specifies a particular quality for the TDL object with =
which it is=20
associated. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS auto-answer"></PRE><B>auto-answer</B>. See =
<I>automatic</I>=20
<I>answering.</I></A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS automatic answering"></PRE><B>automatic</B> =
<B>answering</B>. (1)=20
Answering in which the called data terminal</A> equipment (DTE) =
automatically=20
responds to the calling signal. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> The call can be established whether or not the called =
DTE is=20
attended. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>(2) A machine feature that permits a station to respond without =
operator=20
action to a call it receives over a switched line. See also =
<I>manual</I>=20
<I>answering.</I> Contrast with <I>automatic</I> <I>calling.</I> =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS automatic calling"></PRE><B>automatic</B> <B>calling</B>. =
(1)=20
Calling in which the elements of the selection</A> signal are entered =
into the=20
data network contiguously at the full data signaling rate. (2) A machine =
feature=20
that permits a station to initiate a connection with another station =
over a=20
switched line without operator action. (3) Synonymous with auto-call. =
See also=20
<I>manual</I> <I>calling.</I> Contrast with <I>automatic</I> =
<I>answering.</I> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS auto removal"></PRE><B>auto</B> <B>removal</B>. Removing =
a device=20
from the data-passing activity without</A> human intervention. This =
action is=20
accomplished by the adapter. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- glossary -->
<HR>
<BR><CENTER><B><FONT size=3D+4>B  </FONT></B></CENTER>
<HR align=3Dcenter width=3D100 SIZE=3D4></PRE><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS backup copy"></PRE><B>backup</B> <B>copy</B>. A copy, =
usually of a=20
program or of a library member, that is</A> kept in case the original or =
the=20
working copy is unintentionally altered or destroyed. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS backup diskette"></PRE><B>backup</B> <B>diskette</B>. A =
diskette=20
that contains information copied from another</A> diskette. It is used =
in case=20
the original information is unintentionally altered or destroyed. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS baseband"></PRE><B>baseband</B>. (1) A frequency band =
that uses the=20
complete bandwidth of a</A> transmission medium. Contrast with =
<I>broadband</I>,=20
<I>carrierband</I>. (2) A method of data transmission that encodes, =
modulates,=20
and impresses information on the transmission medium without shifting or =

altering the frequency of the information signal. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS beaconing"></PRE><B>beaconing</B>. An error-indicating =
function of=20
token-ring adapters that</A> assists in locating a problem causing a =
hard error=20
on a token-ring network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS binary"></PRE><B>binary</B>. (1) Pertaining to a system =
of numbers=20
to the base two; the binary</A> digits are 0 and 1. (2) Pertaining to a=20
selection, choice, or condition that has two possible different values =
or=20
states. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS binary synchronous communications =
(BSC)"></PRE><B>binary</B>=20
<B>synchronous</B> <B>communications</B> <B>(BSC)</B>. Data transmission =
in=20
which</A> character synchronism is controlled by timing signals =
generated at the=20
sending and receiving stations. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS bit"></PRE><B>bit</B>. Either of the binary digits: a 0 =
or 1.</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS bracket"></PRE><B>bracket</B>. In SNA, one or more chains =
of=20
request units (RUs) and their</A> responses, which are exchanged between =
two=20
LU-LU half-sessions and represent a transaction between them. A bracket =
must be=20
completed before another bracket can be started. Examples of brackets =
are data=20
base inquiries/replies, update transactions, and remote job entry output =

sequences to workstations. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS bridge"></PRE><B>bridge</B>. (1) A functional unit that =
connects=20
two local area networks</A> (LANs) that use the same logical link =
control (LLC)=20
procedure but can use different medium access control (MAC) procedures. =
(2) See=20
also <I>gateway.</I> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> A bridge connects networks or systems of the same or =
similar=20
architectures, whereas a gateway connects networks or systems of =
different=20
architectures. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS buffer"></PRE><B>buffer</B>. (1) A portion of storage =
used to hold=20
input or output data</A> temporarily. (2) A routine or storage used to=20
compensate for a difference in data rate or time of occurrence of =
events, when=20
transferring data from one device to another. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS burst"></PRE><B>burst</B>. (1) In data communication, a =
sequence of=20
signals counted as one</A> unit in accordance with some specific =
criterion or=20
measure. (2) To separate continuous-form paper into discrete sheets. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS bus"></PRE><B>bus</B>. A type of network topology where =
the network=20
consists of a</A> bidirectional communication path with defined end =
points. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS bypass"></PRE><B>bypass</B>. To eliminate an attaching =
device or an=20
access unit from a ring</A> network by allowing the data to flow in a =
path=20
around it. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS byte"></PRE><B>byte</B>. (1) A string that consists of a =
number of=20
bits, treated as a unit,</A> and representing a character. (2) A binary=20
character operated upon as a unit and usually shorter than a computer =
word. (3)=20
A string that consists of a particular number of bits, usually 8, that =
is=20
treated as a unit, and that represents a character. (4) A group of 8 =
adjacent=20
binary digits that represent one extended binary-coded decimal =
interchange code=20
(EBCDIC) character. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- glossary -->
<HR>
<BR><CENTER><B><FONT size=3D+4>C  </FONT></B></CENTER>
<HR align=3Dcenter width=3D100 SIZE=3D4></PRE><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS cable segment"></PRE><B>cable</B> <B>segment</B>. A =
section of=20
cable between components or devices on a</A> network. A segment may =
consist of a=20
single patch cable, multiple patch cables connected together, or a =
combination=20
of building cable and patch cables connected together. See <I>LAN</I>=20
<I>segment</I>, <I>ring</I> <I>segment</I>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS cable-through"></PRE><B>cable-through</B>. A method of =
cabling that=20
allows multiple workstations to</A> be attached to a single cable path. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS cable wrap"></PRE><B>cable</B> <B>wrap</B>. A method of =
testing=20
5494 adapter cables. The cable wrap can</A> be performed using an =
external wrap=20
plug, or the wrap capability can be built into the cable. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS cabling system"></PRE><B>cabling</B> <B>system</B>. A =
system of=20
communication wiring installed in a building</A> to connect computers =
and=20
communication equipment. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS carrier"></PRE><B>carrier</B>. A continuous signal at a =
specific=20
frequency that can be</A> modulated or impressed with a second=20
(information-carrying) signal. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS carrierband"></PRE><B>carrierband</B>. A frequency band =
in which=20
the modulated signal is</A> superimposed on a carrier signal (as =
differentiated=20
from baseband), but only one channel is present on the medium (as =
differentiated=20
from broadband). Contrast with <I>baseband</I>, <I>broadband</I>. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS character buffer"></PRE><B>character</B> <B>buffer</B>. =

for display or printing on a terminal. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS character set"></PRE><B>character</B> <B>set</B>. (1) A =

specific=20
reason, for example, the set of characters a printer can print. (3) The=20

<A name=3D"GLS circuit"></PRE><B>circuit</B>. (1) A logic device. (2) =
One or more=20
conductors through which an</A> electric current can flow. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS circuit switching"></PRE><B>circuit</B> <B>switching</B>. =
A process=20
that, on demand, connects two or more data</A> terminal equipment (DTE) =
devices=20
and permits the exclusive use of a data circuit between them until the=20
connection is released. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS Clear to Send (CTS) flow control"></PRE><B>Clear</B> =
<B>to</B>=20

-->
<A name=3D"GLS cluster"></PRE><B>cluster</B>. A station that consists of =

unit (a cluster controller)</A> and the terminals attached to it. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS coaxial cable"></PRE><B>coaxial</B> <B>cable</B>. A cable =

external to a system that represents a request for system action. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS common carrier"></PRE><B>common</B> <B>carrier</B>. In =

(dial-up). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS communication link"></PRE><B>communication</B> =

<A name=3D"GLS controller"></PRE><B>controller</B>. A unit that controls =

<A name=3D"GLS control point (CP)"></PRE><B>control</B> <B>point</B> =
<B>(CP)</B>.=20

<A name=3D"GLS data access arrangement (DAA)"></PRE><B>data</B> =
<B>access</B>=20
<B>arrangement</B> <B>(DAA)</B>. (Canada, Japan, and US. For the US,</A> =
applies=20
only when the attaching device is not FCC registered.) An electrical =
isolation=20
device, required by common carriers enabling attachment of privately =
owned data=20
terminal equipment and telecommunication equipment to a network. It =
provides dc=20
voltage isolation and limits excessive signal levels into the =
telecommunication=20
line from the modem. See <I>data</I> <I>coupler</I>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS data circuit-terminating equipment =
(DCE)"></PRE><B>data</B>=20
<B>circuit-terminating</B> <B>equipment</B> <B>(DCE)</B>. In a data =
station,=20
the</A> equipment that provides the signal conversion and coding between =
the=20
data terminal equipment (DTE) and the line. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
   <B>Notes:</B>
<P>
</P></PRE>
<DD>1. The DCE can be separate equipment or an integral part of the DTE =
or of=20
the intermediate equipment. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE>
<DD>2. A DCE can perform other functions that are usually performed at =
the=20
network end of the line. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
<A name=3D"GLS data communication"></P></PRE><B>data</B> =

-->

clock signals is dependent on the presence of receive data transitions; =
that is,=20
receive data is not continuous 0-bits or 1-bits. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->

<B>link</B>=20

<A name=3D"GLS double-byte character set =
(DBCS)"></PRE><B>double-byte</B>=20
<B>character</B> <B>set</B> <B>(DBCS)</B>. A set of characters in which =
each</A>=20
character is represented by 2 bytes. Languages such as Japanese, =
Chinese, and=20
Korean, which contain more symbols than can be represented by 256 code =
points,=20
require double-byte character sets. Because each character requires 2 =
bytes,=20
typing, display, and printing of DBCS characters requires hardware and =
programs=20
that support DBCS. Contrast with single-byte character set. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS downstream"></PRE><B>downstream</B>. (1) In the direction =

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3D"GLS drop"></PRE><B>drop</B>. In the IBM Cabling System, a =

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3D"GLS EIA 232D"></PRE><B>EIA</B> <B>232D</B>. An electrical =
interface=20
defined by the Electronics Industries</A> Association for establishing=20
connections and controlling data flow between data terminal equipment =
and data=20
communication equipment. The interface has been adapted to allow =
communication=20
between DTEs. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS emulation"></PRE><B>emulation</B>. (1) The imitation of =
all or part=20
of one system by another,</A> primarily by hardware, so that the =
imitating=20
system accepts the same data, executes the same programs, and achieves =
the same=20
results as the imitated computer system. (2) The use of programming =
techniques=20
and special machine features to permit a computing system to execute =
programs=20
written for another system. (3) Imitation; for example, imitation of a =
computer=20
or device. (4) See <I>terminal</I> <I>emulation</I>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS enabled"></PRE><B>enabled</B>. On a local area network, =
pertaining=20
to an adapter or device that</A> is active, operational, and able to =
receive=20
frames from the network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS end-of-message delimiter"></PRE><B>end-of-message</B>=20
<B>delimiter</B>. A 111 in the station ID that indicates the last</A> =
frame of a=20
twinaxial message block. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS enhanced logical link control =
(ELLC)"></PRE><B>enhanced</B>=20
<B>logical</B> <B>link</B> <B>control</B> <B>(ELLC)</B>. A type of =
logical link=20
control used</A> in X.25 communication. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<A name=3D"GLS error log"></PRE><B>error</B> <B>log</B>. A record of =
errors that=20
is kept internally by the control</A> unit. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS Ethernet"></PRE><B>Ethernet</B>. (1) A 10-Mbps baseband =
local area=20
network that allows multiple</A> stations to access the transmission =
medium at=20
will without prior coordination, avoids contention by using carrier =
sense and=20
deference, and resolves contention by collision detection and =
transmission.=20
Ethernet uses carrier sense multiple access with collision detection =
(CSMA/CD).=20
(2) A passive coaxial cable whose interconnections contain devices or=20
components, or both, that are all active. It uses CSMA/CD technology to =
provide=20
a best-effort delivery system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS Ethernet network"></PRE><B>Ethernet</B> <B>network</B>. A =
baseband=20
LAN with a bus topology in which messages</A> are broadcast on a coaxial =
cable=20
using a carrier sense multiple access/collision detection (CSMA/CD) =
transmission=20
method. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS extended binary-coded decimal interchange code =
(EBCDIC)"></PRE><B>extended</B>=20
<B>binary-coded</B> <B>decimal</B> <B>interchange</B> <B>code</B>=20
<B>(EBCDIC)</B>. A coded</A> character set of 256 eight-bit characters. =

width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS fault"></PRE><B>fault</B>. An accidental condition that =
causes a=20
functional unit to fail to</A> perform its required function. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS field replaceable unit (FRU)"></PRE><B>field</B> =
<B>replaceable</B>=20
<B>unit</B> <B>(FRU)</B>. An assembly that is replaced in its</A> =
entirety when=20
any one of its components fails. In some cases a FRU may contain other =
FRUs; for=20
example, a brush and a brush block that can be replaced individually or =
as a=20
single unit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS filter"></PRE><BR>| <B>filter</B>. A set of criteria =
which=20
determine whether or not a frame crosses</A> <BR>| a bridge. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS file"></PRE><B>file</B>. A named set of records stored or =
processed=20
as a unit.</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS fixed disk"></PRE><B>fixed</B> <B>disk</B>. A rigid =

<A name=3D"GLS fixed disk drive"></PRE><B>fixed</B> <B>disk</B> =
<B>drive</B>. A=20
disk storage device that reads and writes on rigid</A> magnetic disks. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS flow control"></PRE><B>flow</B> <B>control</B>. (1) In =
data=20
communication, control of the data transfer</A> rate. (2) In SNA, the =
process of=20
managing the rate at which data traffic passes between components of the =

network. The purpose of flow control is to optimize the rate of flow of =
message=20
units with minimum congestion in the network, that is, neither to =
overflow the=20
buffers at the receiver or at intermediate routing nodes nor to leave =
the=20
receiver waiting for more message units. (3) The methods used to control =
the=20
flow of information across a network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"GLS flow control negotiation"></PRE><B>flow</B> =
<B>control</B>=20
<B>negotiation</B>. The ability to alter packet size and packet</A> =
window size.=20
These can be changed from call to call if the network subscription =
allows flow=20
control negotiation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS fractional T1"></PRE><B>fractional</B> <B>T1</B>. =
Fractional T1 is=20
the process whereby individual channels</A> on a T1 multiplexer are =
allocated=20
potions of the 1.544 Mbps transmission rate available on a T1 interface. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS frame relay"></PRE><B>frame</B> <B>relay</B>. An =
interface standard=20
describing the boundary between a</A> user's equipment and a fast-packet =

network. In frame-relay systems, flawed frames are discarded; recovery =
comes=20
end-to-end rather than hop-by-hop. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"GLS frame-relay network"></PRE><B>frame-relay</B> =
<B>network</B>. A=20
network that consists of frame-relay frame</A> handlers (FRFH) and in =
which=20
frames are passed from one frame-relay terminal equipment station to =
another=20
through a series of one or more FRFHs. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<A name=3D"GLS free- key mode"></PRE><B>free-</B> <B>key</B> =

system=20
program (unformatted). The mode that the workstation is in before logon =
to the=20

<A name=3D"GLS from diskette"></PRE><B>from</B> <B>diskette</B>. The =

microinstructions. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS microprocessing unit (MPU)"></PRE><B>microprocessing</B>=20
<B>unit</B> <B>(MPU)</B>. A processing unit that is</A> =
microprogram-controlled=20
and does internal machine operations. The MPU receives data, controls =
the=20

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS modified data tag (MDT)"></PRE><B>modified</B> =
<B>data</B>=20

that, when set, causes that field to be transferred to the channel =
during a=20

input to=20
the field, a selector-pen detection in the field, a card read-in =

detection=20
in the field, program control, or ERASE INPUT key. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3D"GLS packet"></PRE><B>packet</B>. Information transmitted =
through a=20
packet switched network is</A> divided up and inserted into packets. =
These=20
usually consist of control information fields giving destination, =
sequence=20
number, optional facilities, and often a user data area. Various kinds =
of=20
packets are used to transmit error codes and supervise the virtual =
circuit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS packet switching"></PRE><B>packet</B> <B>switching</B>. =
The=20
transfer of data by means of addressed packets that</A> occupy the =
network=20
channel only during actual transmission. The channel is available for =
the=20
simultaneous transfer of packets belonging to other network users. The =
network=20
determines the optimum routing of each individual packet during, rather =
than=20
prior to, the transmission from a DTE. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- =
* -->
<A name=3D"GLS parameter"></PRE><B>parameter</B>. (1) A variable that is =
given a=20
constant value for a specified</A> application and that can denote the=20
application. (2) An item in a menu for which the user specifies a value =
or for=20
which the system provides a value when the menu is interpreted. (3) Data =
passed=20
between programs or procedures. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS parity check"></PRE><B>parity</B> <B>check</B>. (1) A =

pre-given=20
parity bit. (2) A check that tests whether the number of ones (or zeros) =
in an=20

workstation that is attached to the AS/400 system</A> through =
communication=20
lines. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS remove"></PRE><B>remove</B>. (1) To take an attaching =
device off a=20
network. (2) To stop an</A> adapter from participating in passing data =
on a=20
network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS return code"></PRE><B>return</B> <B>code</B>. (1) A code =
used to=20
influence the execution of succeeding</A> instructions. (2) A value =
returned to=20
a program to indicate the results of an operation requested by that =
program. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS ring network"></PRE><B>ring</B> <B>network</B>. A network =

configuration where a series of attaching devices</A> are connected by=20
unidirectional transmission links to form a closed path. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS ring segment"></PRE><B>ring</B> <B>segment</B>. A ring =
segment is=20
any section of a ring that can be</A> isolated (by unplugging =
connectors) from=20
the rest of the ring. A segment can consist of a single lobe, the cable =
between=20
access units, or a combination of cables, lobes, and/or access units. =
See=20
<I>cable</I> <I>segment</I>, <I>LAN</I> <I>segment</I>. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS ring status"></PRE><B>ring</B> <B>status</B>. The =
condition of the=20
ring.</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS ripple level"></PRE><B>ripple</B> <B>level</B>. A voltage =

measurement.</A> <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS root-mean-squared (RMS)"></PRE><B>root-mean-squared</B>=20
<B>(RMS)</B>. Indicates the effective value of an ac voltage.</A> =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS routing"></PRE><B>routing</B>. (1) The assignment of the =
path by=20
which a message will reach</A> its destination. (2) In SNA, the =
forwarding of a=20
message unit along a particular path through a network, as determined by =

parameters carried in the message unit, such as the destination network =
address=20
in a transmission header. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS segment"></PRE><B>segment</B>. A section of cable between =

components or devices on the network.</A> A segment can consist of a =
single=20
patch cable, multiple patch cables connected, or a combination of =
building cable=20
and patch cables connected. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS segmenting"></PRE><B>segmenting</B>. In SNA, the dividing =
of a=20
basic information unit (BIU) into</A> two or more path information units =
(PIU). <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS serial"></PRE><B>serial</B>. (1) Pertaining to a process =
in which=20
all events occur one after</A> the other; for example, serial =
transmission of=20
the bits of a character according to V24 CCITT protocol. (2) Pertaining =
to the=20
sequential or consecutive occurrence of two or more related activities =
in a=20
single device or channel. (3) Pertaining to the sequential processing of =
the=20
individual parts of a whole, such as the bits of a character or the =
characters=20
of a word, using the same facilities for successive parts. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS serializer/deserializer =
(SERDES)"></PRE><B>serializer/deserializer</B>=20
<B>(SERDES)</B>. A register that is used to send data</A> from the =
workstation=20
to the control unit, one bit at a time. The data is entered serially and =
read=20
out parallel, or it is entered parallel and read out serially. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS Service Access Point (SAP)"></PRE><B>Service</B> =
<B>Access</B>=20
<B>Point</B> <B>(SAP)</B>. A logical point made available by an =
adapter</A>=20
where information can be received and transmitted. A single SAP can have =
many=20
links terminating in it. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS session"></PRE><B>session</B>. (1) In network =
architecture, an=20
association of facilities</A> necessary for establishing, maintaining, =
and=20
releasing connections for communication between stations. (2) In MLT, =
synonymous=20
with logical terminal (LT). (3) In SNA, a logical connection between two =
network=20
addressable units that can be activated, tailored to provide various =
protocols,=20
and deactivated as requested. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS Set Attribute (SA) order"></PRE><B>Set</B> =
<B>Attribute</B>=20
<B>(SA)</B> <B>order</B>. (1) An order that specifies an</A>=20
attribute-type-value pair defining the property to be applied to =
subsequent=20
characters in the data stream. An SA order is required for each property =

assigned. (2) An order that associates attributes in the EAB with =
individual=20
characters. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS short hold mode (SHM)"></PRE><B>short</B> <B>hold</B> =
<B>mode</B>=20
<B>(SHM)</B>. An X.21 switched communication option that allows</A> a =
link=20
between two stations to remain established only when there is data to =
transfer.=20
The 5494 supports, but does not initiate, an SHM session. The AS/400 =
system=20
determines and controls SHM sessions. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"GLS single-byte character set =
(SBCS)"></PRE><B>single-byte</B>=20
<B>character</B> <B>set</B> <B>(SBCS)</B>. A character set in which each =

character</A> is represented by a one-byte code. Contrast with =
double-byte=20
character set. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS SNA character string (SCS)"></PRE><B>SNA</B> =
<B>character</B>=20
<B>string</B> <B>(SCS)</B>. A character string composed of EBCDIC</A> =
controls,=20
optionally intermixed with end-user data, that is carried within a=20
request/response unit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS soft error"></PRE><B>soft</B> <B>error</B>. An =
intermittent error=20
on a network that requires</A> retransmission. Contrast with <I>hard</I> =

<I>error</I>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> A soft error by itself does not affect overall =
reliability of=20
the network, but reliability can be affected if the number of soft =
errors=20
reaches the ring error limit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS spanning tree"></PRE><BR>| <B>spanning</B> <B>tree</B>. =
In LAN=20
contexts, the method by which bridges automatically</A> <BR>| develop a =
routing=20
table and update that table in response to changing <BR>| topology to =
ensure=20
that there is only one route between any two LANs in <BR>| the bridged =
network. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS spanning tree explorer (STE)"></PRE><BR>| <B>spanning</B> =

<B>tree</B> <B>explorer</B> <B>(STE)</B>. Are frames that are intended =
to be</A>=20
<BR>| forwarded only by ports assigned to forward them by the spanning =
tree=20
<BR>| protocol. (See all routes explorer for a contrasting frame type.) =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS station"></PRE><B>station</B>. (1) An input or output =
point of a=20
system that uses</A> telecommunication facilities; for example, one or =
more=20
systems, computers, terminals, devices, and associated programs at a =
particular=20
location that can send or receive data over a telecommunication line. =
(2) A=20
location in a device at which an operation is performed, for example, a =
read=20
station. (3) In SNA, a link station. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"GLS subscription"></PRE><B>subscription</B>. An agreement =
between a=20

<A name=3D"GLS storage"></PRE><B>storage</B>. A unit into which recorded =

which it can=20
be retrieved. See also <I>memory</I>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"GLS switched line"></PRE><B>switched</B> <B>line</B>. A=20

<A name=3D"GLS switched network backup (SNBU)"></PRE><B>switched</B>=20

the=20
primary line becomes unavailable or unusable. <PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS switched virtual circuit (SVC)"></PRE><B>switched</B>=20
<B>virtual</B> <B>circuit</B> <B>(SVC)</B>. A switched virtual circuit =
is the=20
packet</A> switched service equivalent of a switched line. It allows=20
communication between the 5494 and one of several possible AS/400 =
systems.=20
Switched virtual circuits are also know as virtual calls. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS synchronous"></PRE><B>synchronous</B>. (1) Pertaining to =
two or=20
more processes that depend on the</A> occurrences of a specific event, =
such as=20
common timing signal. (2) Occurring with a regular or predictable time=20
relationship. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS Synchronous Data Link Control =
(SDLC)"></PRE><B>Synchronous</B>=20
<B>Data</B> <B>Link</B> <B>Control</B> <B>(SDLC)</B>. A discipline =
conforming to=20
subsets</A> of the Advance Data Communication Control Procedures (ADCCP) =
of the=20
American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and High-level Data Link =
Control=20
(HDLC) of the International Organization for Standardization, for =
managing=20
synchronous, code-transparent, serial-by-bit information transfer over a =
link=20
connection. Transmission exchanges can be duplex or half-duplex over =
switched or=20
nonswitched links. The configuration of the link connection can be=20
point-to-point, multipoint, or loop. See also <I>binary</I> =
<I>synchronous</I>=20
<I>communication</I> <I>(BSC)</I>. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
<A name=3D"GLS system configuration"></PRE><B>system</B> =
<B>configuration</B>. A=20
process that specifies the devices and programs</A> that form a =
particular data=20
processing system. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS system operator"></PRE><B>system</B> <B>operator</B>. A =
person who=20
uses a personal computer or workstation</A> that is designated as the =
system=20
console, to activate certain system functions, and to control and =
monitor system=20
operation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS system reference code (SRC)"></PRE><B>system</B> =
<B>reference</B>=20
<B>code</B> <B>(SRC)</B>. A system-generated code, either four or =
six</A>=20
digits, indicating an error or condition. This code is displayable on =
any=20
attached workstation. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS system services control point (SSCP)"></PRE><B>system</B> =

<B>services</B> <B>control</B> <B>point</B> <B>(SSCP)</B>. In SNA, the =
focal=20
point within an</A> SNA network for managing the configuration, =
coordinating=20
network operator and problem determination requests, and providing =
directory=20
support and other session services for end users of the network. =
Multiple SSCPs,=20
cooperating as peers, can divide the network into domains of control, =
with each=20
SSCP having a hierarchical control relationship to the physical units =
and=20
logical units within its domain. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS Systems Network Architecture (SNA)"></PRE><B>Systems</B>=20

twists per foot. This type of cable is commonly used in telephone =
installations=20
for voice transmission. It can also be used for data transmission. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS terminal multiconnector"></PRE><B>terminal</B>=20

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->

<A name=3D"GLS threshold (receive levels)"></PRE><B>threshold</B> =
<B>(receive</B>=20
<B>levels)</B>. A specific voltage level that is compared to</A> a =
signal in=20
order to determine whether that signal is active or inactive. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS timeout"></PRE><B>timeout</B>. (1) An event that occurs =

of a predetermined period of</A> time that began at the occurrence of =
another=20
specified event. (2) A time interval allotted for certain operations to =
occur;=20
for example, response to polling or addressing before system operation =
is=20
interrupted and must be restarted. (3) A terminal feature that logs off =
a user=20
if an entry is not made within a specified period of time. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS token"></PRE><B>token</B>. In a local area network, the =

authority passed among data</A> stations to indicate the station =
temporarily in=20
control of the transmission medium. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * =
-->
</PRE><B>Note:</B> A token is a particular message or bit pattern that =
signifies=20
permission to transmit. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS Token-Ring connection"></PRE><B>Token-Ring</B> =
<B>connection</B>. A=20
method of connecting a workstation to the 5494</A> through a Token-Ring =
network.=20
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS Token-Ring network"></PRE><B>Token-Ring</B> =
<B>network</B>. (1) A=20
ring network that allows unidirectional data</A> transmission between =
data=20
stations by a token-passing procedure over one transmission medium so =
that the=20
transmitted data returns to the transmitting station. (2) A network that =
uses a=20
ring topology, in which tokens are passed in a circuit from node to =
node. A node=20
that is ready to send can capture the token and insert data for =
transmission. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS translate table"></PRE><B>translate</B> <B>table</B>. A =

EBCDIC=20

width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS transmit activity check"></PRE><B>transmit</B> =
<B>activity</B>=20
<B>check</B>. An error condition detected by the workstation</A> adapter =
on the=20

not=20

width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS transition"></PRE><B>transition</B>. A point in time when =

or signal change occurs</A> between two specified levels. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS transmission coding"></PRE><B>transmission</B> =
<B>coding</B>.=20

<A name=3D"GLS twinaxial cable"></PRE><B>twinaxial</B> <B>cable</B>. A =

<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS twinaxial workstation attachment"></PRE><B>twinaxial</B>=20

<A name=3D"GLS twisted pair"></PRE><B>twisted</B> <B>pair</B>. A =

<A name=3D"GLS Type 3 Media Filter cable"></PRE><B>Type</B> <B>3</B> =

itself=20
by returning the output of the mechanism as input. For example, when=20
unrecoverable communication adapter or machine errors occur, a wrap test =
can=20
transmit a specific character pattern to or through the modem in a loop =
and then=20
compare the character pattern received with the pattern transmitted. =
<PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- glossary -->

width=3D132><!-- * -->

<I>X.21</I>.</A>=20

<HR>
<BR><CENTER><B><FONT size=3D+4>3  </FONT></B></CENTER>
<HR align=3Dcenter width=3D100 SIZE=3D4></PRE><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS 3270 data stream"></PRE><B>3270</B> <B>data</B> =
<B>stream</B>. (1)=20
The commands, control codes, orders, attributes,</A> and data or =
structured=20
fields for 3270 devices, that are transmitted inbound to an application =
program=20
or outbound to a terminal. (2) Data being transferred from or to an =
allocated=20
primary or tertiary device, or to the AS/400 system, as a continuous =
stream of=20
data and 3270 Information Display System control elements in character =
form. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<P>
</P></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- glossary -->
<HR>
<BR><CENTER><B><FONT size=3D+4>5  </FONT></B></CENTER>
<HR align=3Dcenter width=3D100 SIZE=3D4></PRE><PRE></PRE><PRE =
width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS 5250 connection"></PRE><B>5250</B> <B>connection</B>. A =
method of=20
connecting a workstation to the 5494 using</A> any cable that supports =
5250 data=20
stream communication. The cable can be twinaxial, telephone =
twisted-pair, IBM=20
Cabling System, or fiber optic. <PRE></PRE><PRE width=3D132><!-- * -->
<A name=3D"GLS 5250 workstation"></PRE><B>5250</B> <B>workstation</B>. =
An NWS or=20
PWS that is attached to the 5494 using a 5250</A> connection.=20

  var i ;
  var aLink ;
  =20
  if ( cookieTest(admin) ) {

    if ( noise ) alert("Fix up Links- cookie true ") ;
    for ( i =3D 0 ; i < document.links.length ; i++ )=20

         =20

     =20

     =20

if (disallowNestedFrames ) {  =20
   =20
  if(document.location.href !=3D top.location.href) // prevent being =
framed
    {
       if(noise) alert("FramesOn - Don't get framed");
       return;

   cookieON() ;

function FramesOff() {
   cookieOFF() ;

   var pBooks ;
   var thePath =3D location.pathname;
   var queryString =3D location.search;
   var qsLength =3D queryString.length;

   pBooks =3DthePath.indexOf("/frameset/") ;

       pBooks =3DthePath.indexOf("/FRAMESET/") ;
   if ( pBooks > 0 ) {
       thePath =3D thePath.substring(0,pBooks) + "/BOOKS/"+ =
thePath.substring(pBooks+10,thePath.length) ;

       if (noise) alert("QueryString =3D " + queryString); =20

   {
       if (noise) alert("FramesOff -/frameset/ missing  "+ thePath ) ;   =

       if (noise) alert("FramesOff:  QueryString =3D " + queryString);
   }

   {
       var fsString =3D queryString.indexOf("FS=3DTRUE");
      =20
       if(fsString =3D=3D -1)  // FS=3DTRUE not part of queryString

       }
       else if(qsLength =3D=3D 8) // FS=3DTRUE only thing in queryString
       {
            parent.location.href =3D thePath;
       }
       else  // take FS=3DTRUE out of queryString
       {

            {

queryString.substring(9,qsLength);

            else if((fsString + 7) =3D=3D qsLength) // FS=3DTRUE is last
            {

queryString.substring(0,fsString-1);

        }=09
   } =20
   else
   {
       parent.location.href =3D thePath ;=20
   }

function cookieON(){
  setCookie("bookserverframes","ON", validDays);

}
function cookieOFF(){
  setCookie("bookserverframes","OFF", validDays);

}
function cookieValue(){
  return getCookie("bookserverframes");

}
function cookieTest(admin) {

if (disallowNestedFrames ) {  =20
   if(document.location.href !=3D top.location.href) // prevent being =
framed
   {
       if(noise) alert("cookieTest - False...Don't get framed");
       return false;
   }
}
  =20
   if ( cookieValue() =3D=3D "ON" )
	  return true ;
   else=20
   if ( cookieValue() =3D=3D "OFF" )
	    return false;
   else  // cookie is null
   if ( admin =3D=3D "0" )=09
	    return false;
   else  =20
        return true;
}

// Use this function to retrieve a cookie.
function getCookie(name){
var cname =3D name + "=3D";              =20
var dc =3D document.cookie;            =20
    if (dc.length > 0) {             =20
    begin =3D dc.indexOf(cname);      =20
        if (begin !=3D -1) {          =20
        begin +=3D cname.length;      =20
        end =3D dc.indexOf(";", begin);
            if (end =3D=3D -1) end =3D dc.length;
            return unescape(dc.substring(begin, end));
        }=20
    }
return null;
}

// Use this function to save a cookie.
function setCookie(name, value, days){
    var expires =3D new Date();

    if(days)
    {
        expires.setTime (expires.getTime() + (days * 1000 * 60 * 60 * =
24) );

        document.cookie =3D name + "=3D" + escape(value) + "; path=3D/" =
+ "; expires=3D" + expires.toGMTString();
    }
    else
        document.cookie =3D name + "=3D" + escape(value) + "; path=3D/";
}

// Use this function to delete a cookie.
function delCookie(name) {
document.cookie =3D name + "=3D; expires=3DThu, 01-Jan-70 00:00:01 GMT" =
+  "; path=3D/";
}
